    'body' => 'Hi there

Grant Sinclair said 
> There is one official piece of library data that clashes with this 
> Imperial Law, however, being the Spinward Marches world of Nexine, which 
> "is an underpopulated water world where the Imperial Ministry of 
> Conservation currently operates a reseeding program using _biologically_ 
> _altered_ humans.  Candidates are provided with gill implants, synthetic 
> skin insulation and webbed extremities.  They participate in sea farming 
> operations under the world\'s shallow seas". (The underlining is mine)

Surely this isn\'t genetic engineering of human DNA, but biological 
engineering of human volunteers.  However, there is _another_ piece of 
canonical background in MTJ3, regarding the Jonkeereen, to qoute:

"Though Imperial attitudes were very wary of altering the human genome, 
several different projects were begun under the Imperial Ministry of 
Colonization.  Their goal was to produce human colonists suited for 
envirnoments which would otherwise seem inhospitable.  One of th emost 
successful of these projects was the Jonkeereen"

The article goes on to say that the Jonkeereen project was started in the 
500s, in an attempt to "limit Suerrat expansion".  This project used 
geneered humans for the ends of the government, military, and SuSAG (who 
were given the development contract), with little concern for the 
individuals involved.  Eventually, the need for the project dissappeared, 
and the Jonkeereen were left to fend for themselves on the world on which 
they were developed (Jonkeer in Deneb sector).

If this article is taken as canonical (I\'m not sure DGPs products are, 
but they are used in my campaign as such), then this clearly clashes with 
Jo\'s post.  However, it can be salvaged if

1) you are willing to believe the Imperium will quite openly contravene 
their own laws in such a big way

or

2) assume human genome experimentation is wimply closely regulated, and 
so many of the adventure possibilities are still available.

