    'body' => 'Generic Library <library@babylon5.dss.gov.au> wrote:

>- I can find no reason to force Traveller starships to orbit a planet, if 
>they are using thrusters. That is, they could "hover" (even at orbital 
>height) with no long-term problem. Sure, they would need power to remain 
>there, but there is no other barrier that I know of.
[...]
>Now, I know that Striker (Mk 1) and such state that orbiting ships are only 
>overhead for one-third of the time - but WHY? there is nothing in the 
>rules to force this situation. It looks as though a ship could sit in one 
>spot and blast everything on the ground to bits, esp. with the ridiculous 
>figures given in MT for starship weaponry.

There is no good reason.  Any craft with gravitics should also present
the same problem, or worse.  In fact, gravitic vehicles present a problem
for orbital traffic control, too.  If gravitic technology "works" by
screening all or most of a planet\'s mass from the craft, then the actual
orbital velocity of the craft at a given height will be very sharply
reduced, and quite unnatural, as long as gravitics are on "full".  And if
the planet is rotating, the geostationary (and geosynchronous) orbits 
will drop in altitude substantially as well for the gravitic ship. 

Most of the time, ships would probably be required by law to turn off 
the gravitic lifters and enter a normal orbit.  Otherwise, if the 
lifters were shut down, the ship would change it\'s orbit in a fairly
spectacular, if not lethal, manner.

For that matter, even if you don\'t have gravitics or incredible thrusters,
a geostationary orbit around the Earth is within the range of starship
weapons in MegaTraveller.  You could just take up station way up there
and fire at will.  A case could be made that it\'s harder to hit ground
targets than starships from that far away, I suppose. 

Of course, sitting in one spot, especially while using thrusters, is
foolish if the defenders have any starship-grade surface-to-orbit PD
batteries to return fire with, but predictable orbits are not much
better....

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonn0015@gold.tc.umn.edu>
 
