    'body' => 'The Query began with:

>     "Now, I know that Striker (Mk 1) and such state that orbiting ships
>     are only overhead for one-third of the time - but WHY?

They were probably assuming a specific kind of orbit where only 1 third of
the planet would be in the arc of fire. An over-simplification to be sure,
but it be be some silly Naval Regulation: Thou Shalt Not Orbit Closer thatn
X distance. No more, no less. X shall be the distance, and Thou Shalt not
orbit closer nor farther from this distance, known as X".

As for real reasons to avoid orbital bombardment, examine this:

Orbital bombardment is great for destroying things. However, it can\'t
occupy ground, and not all conflicts involve destruction of property.

The enemy may be huddled around vital, sensitive targets. The danger space
of a Meson Gun is what, a mile? What if you accidently destroy one of your
dirtside objectives?

In the Imperium, especially Classic Traveller, use of orbital bombarment
may be seen as excessive, especially if targeted near civilian areas. There
are likely "Rules of War" that govern martial disuptes within the Imperium,
and orbital bombardment is likely heaviliy regulated.  (Of course, this
doesn\'t matter in the Rebellion - the Knightfall campaign opens with
orbital Meson bombardment of the spaceport the PCs occupy).

>     I get the feeling original Striker was just trying to downplay the use
>     of such strategies so the ground forces could get into more detailed
>     conflicts with each other.

Probably so, but nonetheless it is reasonable for starships to *not* play a
role in ground action. IMO they will be brought to bear on a case-by-case
basis - it\'s a degree of escalation and efficiency.

>     I ship _should_ be able to sit in geosynchronous orbit over the AO and
>     fire away unless it is involved in combat with other ships.

Provided of course it is not harrassed by other enemy ships. Of course,
this is a given if friendly troops are on the ground - I wouldn\'t deposit
them unless I had space superiority.

