    'body' => '>>  It looks as though a ship could sit in one   spot and 
blast everything on the ground to bits, esp. with the 
ridiculous   figures given in MT for starship weaponry <<


There are various problems with sitting in orbit and blasting 
everything to bits.  Many are political or humanitarian - I\'ll 
not try to explore those - There are however some practical
considerations;

Lasers and Particle Accelerators are supposedly heavily inhibited
by atmosphere.  I seem to remember CT (or striker maybe?) not 
allowing these weapons to be used for ortillery except on vacuum
worlds (as I recall, vacuum worlds were not generally contested
once enemy ships were in orbit ;).

Missiles are never in infinite supply.  this doesn\'t prohibit their
use but certainly limits it.  As for nuclear missiles, see political
considerations above.  Still, I would think missiles to be the orbital
bombardment weapon of choice for vars. reasons; capability of terminal 
guidance, and guided and unguided submunitions come especially to mind.

I once designed a (MT) Company assault transport which was armed almost
exclusively with missiles.  It was not intended to fight other ships, but
to act as orbital support for the landed troops.

Ah, now we come to Meson Guns, the ultimate High Tech weapon.  Anyone
care to guess at it\'s destructive power?  I think that I would put most 
starship mounted Meson Guns in a class with nukes for limits of usage.  
Perhaps the 50-ton bay mounted meson guns would be a bit better - and these
would be used extensively for support if that is the case.  I still
think missiles (purpose built) would be the primary orbital support
weapon.

Anyone remember the _battlefield_ meson accelerator?  Talk about artillery 
support!  I would rule as GM btw that insurmountable engineering problems
prevent anyhting smaller than the battlefield accelerator being built.

In practical terms I think that the 50-ton bay mesons would be equivalent
to the battlefield accel. in destructive power when used against ground
targets.  Accuracy at this range would be of the "which rock" variety
(as in "shouldn\'t we tell them which hill?""no, we should tell them
which rock.").  The problem is one of intelligence, not targetting.

Pete
