    'body' => 'One issue that could be interesting to address is that of indirect fire.
Apart from starship indirect fire or support fire which is obviously
important,
and has already been discussed in the list, one thing that I have always
found 
hard to accept is the lack of modern indirect fire weapons at TL 12-15. 
In practice after the introduction of the mass driver the only improvement is
the meson gun.
I believe that indirect fire will remain very important in ground
operations, however the minimum meson gun size is crucial. I have 
tried to design TL 13 support vehicle in MT (the TL13 equivalent of the M109)

and I end up with something in excess of 1000 tons...Using the old
mercenary meson gun would produce (although at higher TL) something more
reasonable.

My feeling is that Army generals would either ask for lighter meson gun 
designs or for some new more powerful and smarter kind of ammo for the 
mass drivers.. The idea of hiding your artillery where the opponent cannot
see it, looks too good to be abandoned. Faster vehicles (especially with
high signature) would just call for deadlier weapons.

If the list could agree on what "rules" we should follow, one could attempt
to sketch the order of battle of a TL 15 battalion. The reason why
I think this is a good starting point is that IF indirect fire becomes
even more efficient and common than it is now (TL 8) typical troopers might
all become forward observers equipped with light personal weaponry to
guarantee survival with a minimal signature.
In contrast, IF there is no indirect fire support apart from occasional
starships, it would seem reasonable to assume that every soldier has
an FGMP or even something heavier suitable to dispose of a tank....

On a separate issue, how do people on the list see sensors and naval cbt?
obviously it all depends on the precise rules, but I do like to have 
AWACS ships doing the sensor work for battleships. Is this common?

                  Max
