    'body' => 'Dear Max,
	I would like to make a few comments regarding your article "indirect 
fire and sensors":

"one thing that I have always found hard to accept is the lack of modern 
indirect fire weapons at TL 12-15..... I believe that indirect fire will
remain 
very important in ground operations."

Is the emphasis today not increasingly focused upon direct-fire solutions ?  
Artillery today utilises smart technology like the Merlin system for mortars 
offered by British Aerospace, and the \'skeets\' and various smart submunitions

developed by the US military ?  In future would it not be the case that as 
armies become smaller and more manoeuverable, that the emphasis switches to 
direct-fire weaponry, backed up by good sensor technology ?  
	Indirect fire still maybe potent for use against low-tech military 
formations relying upon attrition, but at TL 12-15 the formations are
probably 
victim to that most common of ailments - assuming that their opponent will be

equipped like they themselves are ....

My own feeling vis a vie Traveller HIGH tech combat is that rapid moving grav

vehicles and battle dress troops with grav belts etc. will use plasma weapons

and so forth to directly nail their opponents.  The defence may deploy smart 
mines that sense grav-modules (anyone thought about that ?).  What say you
Max 
in defence ????
 
"On a separate issue, how do people on the list see sensors and naval cbt? 
obviously it all depends on the precise rules, but I do like to have 
AWACS ships doing the sensor work for battleships. Is this common? "

There seems on the face of it similarities between submarine warfare today
and 
space warfare tommorrow (plus several caveats).  In underwater warfare
sensors 
are paramount, and picket ships of some form acting as forward scouts will 
provide a crucial role, and have in my campaign.  AWACS ships are a little 
tricker - do you have designs for any for CT ?

Regards
Jeff
