  {
    'body' => 'Is it just me, or is Traveller in need of a serious reworking 
scientifically?  I mean, yah, the whole "space opera" thing is fine & 
dandy, but we have made SO many scientific, astrographic, and astronometric 
advances since the first edition was written that the rationalizations are 
becoming a bit too threadbare.  But here are my points:
1) Keep the Traveller culture, races, timeline, as much as possible.  
2) Seriously rework the system generation & frequency tables - ala the 
Goeran archives - the stellar system foundation from 2300 was a magnificent 
start (albeit a pretty weakly done game) from a hard-science point of view. 
(in that vein, I think someone had a woody for \'beanstalks\')
3) Seriously re-work planetary details; i think the game Outpost, while 
lame from a playability standpoint, admirably represented the kind of \'raw 
worlds\' available.
4) Some minor rewriting and development of the equipment and tech level 
systems - personally, the TL15 Imperium marine is wimpy, given that the 
difference in lethality should be to TL9 us as we are to TL3(!)
5) (my personal bugaboo) a 3d map.  geez.  it\'s space, after all.  take 
the  "10,000 world of the imperium" and put \'em in 3d space, suddenly the 
imperium\'s pretty dinky.  it\'s not that complicated of a thing, when you 
realize that it\'s a natural candidate for an RPG that mandates having a 
computer - rather than being a book-game that has some computer support.

None of these things are really that significant, given the resources that 
could be marshalled via this medium.

What does anyone say - care to come up with a set of XBOAT rules that 
maintain the essence of classic traveller, but are written in 1995, rather 
than re-hashings of rules written in what, 1980?

Steve Lieb
liebx004@maroon.tc.umn.edu
Cologne, MN

...still looking for that killer .sig 
