The BF series of fast battle-riders were produced on Mora/Spinward
Marches to fulfil demand for a pure ship-killer. Their role is similar to
that of the strike fighter: to carry heavy weapons for short durations on
relatively simple seek-and-destroy missions. While fighters use their
agility to avoid serious damage, BF series craft employ thick armour.
Sometimes power is diverted from the meson gun to achieve respectable
emergency agilities for pursuit or evasion. BF series craft are most
effective against escorts, and are dangerous to cruisers. They have
proved slightly vulnerable to concerted attack by fighters, and cannot
withstand heavy missile bombardment or the heavier spinal mount weapons,
but cause damage out of all proportion to their displacement when
correctly employed.

In addition to 5 and 6 kiloton vessels, there are also two 7.5 kiloton
designs, one with a meson-N spinal mount and another with increased
agility and greater endurance. In general, BF series battle-riders are
deployed in squadrons of four to six from cruiser-sized tenders (100 kton
range). [The tenders have a 30kton carrying capacity, which allows them
to carry four 7.5 kton craft, two 7.5 kton and three 5 kton, five 6 kton,
or six 5 kton craft, or a standard-sized 30kton battle-rider.] If pressed
into service as system defence craft, they will sport drop tanks or
external demountable tanks, to extend patrol duration. However, their
lack of any subsidiary craft is a distinct handicap to such employment.


Design notes: I\'ve assumed Book 5 CT rules for meson screen energy usage
(as is obviously done in Fighting Ships) and for purification plant
volume and mass (= 2 x volume). Needless to say, the 7.5 kton designs and
the tender aren\'t done yet, except for some preliminary calculations to
see if a meson-N can be squeezed into 7.5 ktons, 6G etc. Add extra
sensors to taste, and don\'t retro-engineer to CT -- they\'ll die horribly!
I\'m also tempted to produce a 5kton missile boat, with enormous agility,
as a variant.


Nick

