Depends on the trade status of the world. 200 million people in a
dirt-poor backwater aren\'t going to generate that much business. 10 
billion people on Trin, with a decent industrial base, are going to 
generate a *huge* amount of merchant traffic. Although I\'d say that 
most of that traffic should be transported by bulk carrier, there 
should still be some good pickings for tramp skippers.

It also depends on how well-integrated interplanetary economics is. 
If most worlds are self-sufficient in basics (hydroponics or algae 
for food, biomass or radioactives or solar power for energy), I 
wouldn\'t expect to see the kind of mass transport of foodstuffs that 
we encounter on Earth. Luxuries and high-tech items are another 
matter of course. I have a vague recollection of a discussion on the 
TML a long time ago concerning this -- I think the consensus was that 
the old Imperium was such a heavily-integrated market.

As a matter of interest, what\'s the breakdown for cargo types through
New Orleans and Houston? Given that the US is a major industrial 
nation (I hesitate to put the word "still" in there :-) as well as a
major agricultural producer, it\'d be interesting to see the split 
between agricultural produce and other stuff.

>                                     ----Steve
