    'index' => 'ab394',
    'topic' => 'MT Trade Rules modifications',
    'body' => 'Hi All,

while trying to run a CT game (using MT) during the week, I "found" and area
of 
the rules that I had previously ignored, the interstellar trade section.
After 
plummeting beneath the screen for 20mins when my players casually asked "So,
what 
cargo\'s are available?", I was distressed to find that all the effort I had
put 
into generating cargos etc was of no consequence and in fact just a faceless
job 
lot from the first table would have done!

Now, people have probably mailled such things before but here\'s my "solution"
to 
this problem:

INFLUENCE OF TRADE-GOOD TYPES ON RESALE PRICE
my goal here was to integrate the roll for general class of trade goods
(Processed 
Resources, Natural Resources, Manufactured Goods, Information and Novelties)
into 
the trading system.  Thus not only do Ag world goods sell better on an As
world 
but specificaly biological natural resources (as the asteroid belt has
none/very 
little).

Assumptions
1)As per MT you must roll on the first trade-good type table you can
(although  
this is inconsistent within MT)
2)The goods generated  by these tables represent the abundence of a
particular 
resource type on a world.
3)No modifiers to the tables were considered.
4)Both Natural and Processed resources are split into 2 catagories Nat I, Nat
II, 
Proc I and Proc II corresponding to (11-33) and (44-66) on the tables.

Analysis
First I calculated the percentage chance of a given type of good being
available 
on a world type - this would show which worlds had an abundence/scarcity of 
particular goods.

  WORLD: Ag   WaRi AsVaDeNa  Ni   In  Others  Average
GOODS      
Nat I    4.2  13.9   41.7   20.8  4.2   8.3    15.5
Nat II  37.5  13.9    0.0   20.8  4.2   8.3    14.1
Proc I   0.0  15.3   16.7    8.3  9.7  22.2    11.2
ProcII  30.6  15.3    0.0    8.3  9.7  22.2    14.3
Man     11.1  16.7   30.6   25.0 55.6  11.1    25.0
Info    13.9  25.0   13.9   13.9 13.9  19.4    16.6
Nov      2.7   2.7    2.7    2.7  2.7   2.7     2.7

Results
Once you have this data you can rank the worlds to see where a particular
type of 
good will sell well (or poorly).  I have generated two such tables below.  To
use 
these tables just insert a new step into the resale price calculations.  In
order 
not to upset things too much I use these modifiers in addition to the
destination 
world/sourceworld modifiers (this also has the advantage that you can just
skip 
determining cargo type if you want a quick resolution).

TABLE A (based on double/half average abundance generates a -/+1 to resale
price)

  WORLD: Ag   WaRi AsVaDeNa  Ni   In  Others   
GOODS      
Nat I    +1    +0     -1     +0   +1    +0     
Nat II   -1    +0     +1     +0   +1    +0     
Proc I   +1    +0     +0     +0   +0    -1   
ProcII   -1    +0     +1     +0   +0    +0     
Man      +1    +0     +0     +0   -1    +1    
Info     +0    +0     +0     +0   +0    +0     
Nov      +S    +S     +S     +S   +S    +S     
Novelties are special and have an unpredictable selling price so when the
item is 
to be sold( ie on arrival at a destination world) roll 1d6 where 1,2=-1,
3,4=+0, 
5,6=+1.


TABLE B (based on each +/-10% from average abundance generates a -/+1 to
resale 
price)
This is an alternate table to be used instead of TABLE A if more influence on

price is desired.

  WORLD: Ag   WaRi AsVaDeNa  Ni   In  Others   
GOODS      
Nat I    +1    +0     -2     +0   +1    +0     
Nat II   -2    +0     +2     +0   +1    +0     
Proc I   +2    +0     +0     +0   +0    -1   
ProcII   -1    +0     +2     +0   +0    +0     
Man      +1    +0     +0     +0   -3    +1    
Info     +0    +0     +0     +0   +0    +0     
Nov      +S    +S     +S     +S   +S    +S   

As you can see there\'s endless possibliities here.

And now a question, in MT there is mention of both freight and cargos but the
two 
seem confused.  How do I determine how much freight is available, and how
much 
cargo is available?

byee
Rob

