    'topic' => 'Avoid rocks through jump errors',
    'body' => 'Sorry if I touch again a much debated issue, but I\'d like to say something
on the rock throwing/jump accuracy business. This is meant especially
for those who don\'t like people smashing planets. Those who like it
can skip this message...

The jump time accuracy even for the most accurate Imperial Navy ships
is, I believe,  in the 15-30 minutes range. However, apparently Marc Miller
in his JTAS #24 "Jumpspace" article (I haven\'t seen it, I am quoting
from Steve Bonneville posting in Xboat 155) states that a jump is accurate
to 1E-10. This is a lot! a minor retcon would be to say that spatial accuracy
equals temporal accuracy times the speed of light. Therefore typical
spatial accuracy for a very accurate jump (within 15 minutes) would
be 18 Mkm = 0.12 AU. The benefits of such a choice are:

1- make rock throwing to smash planets more difficult.
2- make  coordinate fleet jumping a bit more difficult, fleets have
to reassemble after jumps. This explains why the Imperial Navy is still
building battleships rather than only battleraiders.
3- make piracy a bit more interesting. Merchant ships will not jump
routinely within 100 diameters and pirates have a chance.

                        Max

P.S. my apologies to Jo Grant for a misleading subject in my post, 
I did not intend to bug him...(sorry for the joke..)


