>on enemy locations in relation to their positions.

This is true. Still EMS counter measures will also be very powerul
at high TL and densitometers and neutrino detectors are very bulky,
the latter probably too bulky for a single trooper. If you do without
them it is a totally different game.

>Do you need a meson gun? Don\'t munitions improve at all at upper TLs?

Yes, I do need it. Munitions improve, too. If we concentrate on Traveller
the improvement in munition and the relevant ranges are given in the rules. 
I believe that a Meson Gun would be a useful asset, although probably too 
expensive and bulky to be really the TL13-15 equivalent of the M109. A meson
gun is powerful, has long range, is harder to track where it is hiding
(since your EMS won\'t see the shells coming...).

>Drones and missiles maybe become more effective and cheaper alternatives to
>traditional artillery.

I partly agree. But look at air-to-air Real World combat. Missiles have
not totaly replaced guns. A fast dumb projectile may have advantages.
Artificial gravity fields can be detected in MT, so that a drone so
equipped, though useful, may  have to face alerted point defences. It all
depends on the exact rules...If point defence is very effective, one
may have to saturate the target and saturation is very expensive to
achieve with smart ammo. Here again a meson gun would not require a
logistic system able to ship around tons of ordnance every day for
every battery. I have to agree that missiles might be an alternative 
to mass drivers (for me that\'s still artillery, when at artillery 
[technical..] school apart from a few 40 mm our group only saw missiles...).

>The improved targeting I mentioned above might let artillery finally target
>vehicles on the fly - right now it\'s just too difficult to hit a fast
>moving vehicle with artillery.

Agreed! the battlefield will indeed look very different at higher TL.

I hope to have soon some more material and vehicle designs for my 
TL 14  armoured brigade and then be able to start some tests.
I\'d like to see what happens when an energy-weapons unit meets one
with more standard ordnance at the same TL.

>Still, IMHO most starships will be capable of detecting objects
>for themselves,..

Again I think it all depends on the exact rules under consideration.
I have only CT and MT experience. In MT it seems to me that it is
easier to hit something than it is to find it in the first place.
Under this assumption it pays to have sensor ships directing
fire. It is not too unlike soviet cruisers equipped with surface-to
surface missiles (or even the French-Italian OTOMAT Mk 3 with a   
range significantly exceeding 100 km). The effective weapon range
is larger than the detection range, therefore they need midcourse
guidance (often provided by helos).

Derek says:
>I have seen FFW, and it does sort of work this way.

Thanks for the info!

                                 Max

