7/6-95 Jeff Zeitlin wrote:

>  Zhodani was a tough one.  It "feels" more like Polish than
>  anything else, for some reason, which makes it a slavic language.
>  OK, let\'s use the Cyrillic alphabet - but don\'t use any letters
>  that bear a strong resemblance to Latin alphabet letters, and use
>  similarly non-latin characters from the Greek alphabet to fill in.

Oh, but what if your players can read one or both of these alphabets?
Some of mine can. This problem goes for all the other languages
you\'ve mentioned too. Don\'t get me wrong, I think it\'s a cool idea.
Maybe one should invent new alphabets instead. I\'ve done a couple
for one of my friends\' Warhammer Fantasy campaign and I thought it
was fun. Ok, maybe you won\'t think that.

But this raises another problem: If you write handouts in a language
or alphabet that the PCs are supposed to be able to read, but the
players aren\'t, at the very best they\'ll have to sit down and decipher
it all, which seems wrong when the PCs can read it without effort.
Also: is this fun? Some players seem to think it is, and some don\'t.
Personally I don\'t think it\'s fun, but I\'ll have to admit that it adds
great flavor to a game.

>  For Galanglic, naturally, I use the standard latin alphabet, in a
>  font suitable for the purpose.  Representation of older dialects
>  of Galanglic (Anglic, English, etc.) I generally try to render in
>  a font that looks "old fashioned" - perhaps Goudy Old Style for
>  something dating back to the Rule of Man, Fraktur or blackletter
>  for something dating back before Terran Confederation days, or
>  pre-starflight.  The further back you go, the more you should vary
>  spelling - mutate consonants (d to/from t, f to/from v, etc.),
>  add or remove aspirants (h, w), and so on.  With a little work,
>  including contextual analysis, your characters should be able to
>  dope it out, just like you or I can manage Middle English, or
>  someone with both Modern English and Modern German can figure
>  out a good amount of modern Dutch or Afrikaans.

I like the idea with mutated spelling. I think I\'ll remember to use that
once. I don\'t know about the fonts, though. First of all, players
shouldn\'t get assosiations to medieval times or something like that,
when they are reading a text from the Rule of Man.
.
Another thing: Is galanglic written with latin letters at all? 3000 years
is a lot of time for an alphabet to mutate. Illustrations, especially from
DGP, seems to indicate that galanglic letters aren\'t to similar to latin
letters.

In my game galanglic is a language decendant from english, but it
isn\'t english more than danish sounds like the old nordic tongue.
It seems reasonable that ordinary people of the Imperium will be able
to read texts written some hundreds years ago, yes maybe even back
to the beginning of the Imperium, but not from across the Long Night.

But anyway, thanks for the article, which I thought was inspiring and
recieved the rare honor of being saved to my harddisk.

Mark Seemann
