Which is exactly my point. A Traveller Model/1 computer is rated as 
TL 5 (1900-39, which makes it the equivilant of a glorified adding 
machine!). And this is the model used in a standard Free-Trader 
straight \'from the yard\'?  Model/1 has a cpu of 2, and an additional 
storage capacity of 4. Therefore, because the cpu has a capacity of 2, 
only 2 programmes can be run together (multitasking?)

To quote from Deluxe Traveller (page: 70): "During the computer 
reprogramming phase, specific programs may be removed from the 
computer and others inserted.  ... both jump-1 and navigation would 
be required for the performance of an interstellar jump. Both 
programmes would be fed into the computer during the programming 
phase, but only after sufficient space had been cleared (perhaps by 
removing the maneuver and auto-evade programmes)."

Now I\'m writing this on a 486SX-25 with 8 Meg of RAM (not particularly
grunty I\'ll admit) from home. But with it I can work one application 
in Windows *and* have UUPOLL access my server, download email and 
news, unbatch it, and let me know there\'s mail. That\'s the equivilant 
of a cpu of 2. The idea that in the Far Future programmes have to be 
physically(?) removed before beginning another set of tasks smacks of 
the good ol\' days(?) of the Spectrum ZX (which is about the time when 
Traveller was originally written).

>     Sure, hardware has improved, but in general software
> has expanded to fill the gaps. I have absolutely no
> problem with computers in traveller, and I\'m a computer
> professional! If you want to search a database, the
> algorithyms may be better, and the software faster, but
> you can damn well bet the database will also be several
> orders of magnitude larger. 

Which is again my point. Today\'s hardware has improved to the point 
where my 486 at work handles 6 extremely powerful graphics programmes. 
And what about networking? And the gigabyte computer? The computer
technology presented in Traveller is seriously outdated and IMHO needs 
to be upgraded. Or ... do I have it all wrong?

> Jo

Enquiring minds would like to know.
- Dorian


