Jo Grant <Jo_Grant.LOTUSINT@crd.lotus.com> writes...

X::>>Things like foreign languages
 ::>>being written in non-Latin characters.
 ::>    Hiya. On a long car trip (in which I wasn\'t driving)
 ::>I sat down and began writing a "alphabet generation system"
 ::>for traveller. Once I had that I thought I would then write
 ::>the software to go with my sysgen stuff to generate unique
 ::>alphabets for each ethnic region. I haven\'t got much further
 ::>than the back of an envelope design but you sound like you
 ::>would be interested.

 I most certainly would.  In your design, though, you want to 
 remember that languages evolve, and that the form of the language, 
 both written and spoken, depends much on the mindset of the
 culture that is writing/speaking the language - or, sometimes, on 
 the mindset of the culture being hired as historians or 
 bookkeepers.  An example of the latter is modern Mongolian, which 
 bears a strong resemblance to vertically-written Arabic - because 
 at some point, the Mongols hired Arabic-speaking people to act as 
 record keepers.

 Also consider that mass written communication is going to have a 
 simplifying influence on the written language - compare, for 
 example, the blackletter type of the Gutenberg Bible with the
 simple Times of the Times.  Or "modern" Simplified Chinese in use 
 in the People\'s Republic, as compared to the Traditional Chinese 
 in use in the Republic (Taiwan).  Or even the two Japanese kana 
 sets as compared to the more traditional Kanji.

X::>Alphabetic representation:
 ::>    In general a written symbols can be used for individual sounds
 ::>(english), just vowels (?), just consonents (hebrew), syllables
 ::>(korean), whole words (mandarin), or whole sentances (?). A
 ::>writing system will mainly consist of one of these methods.

 True, with the caveat that there may or may not be a one-to-one 
 mapping of phonemes to glyphs in the alphabetical representations.
 Similar comments hold for the syllabaries or pictographics.  I\'m
 not aware of any languages that map sentences into single glyphs, 
 although I am given to understand that a single word in Inuktitut
 may in fact express an entire sentence concept.

X::>Alphabetic grouping:
 ::>    Generally symbols will be grouped at one level higher than
 ::>their representation. I.e. if individual sounds are represented
 ::>then spaces are more likely to occur between words. If words
 ::>are represented then spaces are more likely to occur between
 ::>sentences, etc. But not always.

 Very true.  Traditional Chinese springs to mind here; until 
 recently, even punctuation wasn\'t used.  Sentence/concept breaks 
 were implied from context.  It makes for a very dense printed 
 representation.

X::>Punctuation:
 ::>    Punctuation may occur to several different levels. Paragraph,
 ::>Sentence, phrase, word, or syllable. A special case is in either
 ::>a all consonent or all vowel language where punctuation can
 ::>indicate the unrepresented vowels or consonents.

 Except that those are not called punctuation, \\per se\\; those are 
 called "diacritics" or "lentition marks".  Punctuation is a
 contextual aid, not a pronunciation aid.

X::>Alphabetic form:
 ::>    What do the characters look like? I thought of four general
 ::>classifications: Caligraphic (Kanji, Arabic), Typographic (most
 ::>roman fonts), Pictographic (Hiroglphics), or Digital (Braille).

 As long as you allow for hybrids of these, I see nothing wrong 
 with these classifications.

X::>    Anyone interested in fleshing this out into a more formal
 ::>generation system? If I like it I may even encode it in a font
 ::>generation program...

 If you choose to go the diacritical/lentition route, remember that
 most of the marks have their origins in "shorthand" writing of the 
 basic forms of the letter.  For instance, the circumflex over many 
 French vowels is believed to have its origins in a superscripted
 script "s", and the umlaut similarly started as a superscripted
 "e".
==========================================================================
Jeff Zeitlin                                      jeff.zeitlin@execnet.com
