    'topic' => ' IN and Noble Control',
    'index' => 'ab440',
    'month' => '06',
    'body' => 'mstiavel@astro.sns.it (M. Stiavelli) wrote:
 
>On a different subject, has anybody understood the logic behind having local
>nobles interfering with the Navy? I was shocked when I read that in
rebellion
>(I had not realized it was that bad until that time..). History tells us
>that one of the best ways to achieve complete failure in a military mission
>is to have the politicians influence the military (see, e.g., Winston
>Churchill during WW I..).

The reason is, the nobles that have "insinuated" themselves into the chain
of command *are* the local civilian Imperial government.  Here in the USA,
we have civilian control of the military through President as commander-in-
chief.  In the Imperium, the reigning Emperor can\'t directly control the
entire military due to the communications lag, so he is forced to delegate
these powers to the dukes of the marches, who know the Imperial eye is on
them if they mess up.  It helps that many of these high nobles were in the
navy themselves -- if Norris hadn\'t been Duke of Regina, his career path
suggests that he might have had Frederick Santanocheev\'s job and rank 
during the 5FW.  Also note that Norris, as a subsector duke, did not have
enough authority to override the sector or vice admirals until *after*
he recieved near-Imperial powers from Strephon\'s Imperial Warrant -- the
old 5FW board game simulates this.  Offhand, I\'m not sure if he was able
to override even fleet admirals (one-stars in 5FW) before he got the 
Warrant.  I suspect that the high nobles know what they can and can\'t tell
the admirals to do -- and if not, they\'ll have it "carefully explained" to
them by their liege when they complain about not being listened to.  The
dukes also help raise the subsector colonial navies, so they get some input
that way too.  

The Imperium judged that having powerful, independent Grand Admirals at the
domain level was a failure -- they tried that before the Civil War, and it
was one of the things that Arbellatra abolished afterward.  Local direction
of the IN was given to the sector and subsector dukes, and the archducal 
level was cut out altogether, at least partly to avoid turning the domain
archdukes into what the Grand Admirals had been.  Of course, the dukes still
owe fealty to the archdukes, so this power *is* available to the domain
government, it just has more checks on it.   It\'s probable that "modern"
Imperial Grand Admirals don\'t have direct control of troop formations but
create policy.  The megacorps face a similar problem in their operations.
If it\'s all working, it\'s a carefully crafted balance of powers between
the civilian government and the Navy, and the nobles and the Emperor,
designed to keep the Imperium together.

It could be argued that the big mistake made by Strephon and his advisors
was in strengthening the archducal power in an attempt to strengthen the
civilian Imperial government.  It wasn\'t entirely his fault -- it failed 
because the people he trusted also failed. 

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonn0015@gold.tc.umn.edu> 

