13/6-95 Massimo Stiavelli wrote:

>I have understood that e.g. the Duke of Lanth cannot stop the
>Imperial fleet based there from being repositioned somewhere
>else, but can he interfere on what battleship types are built? or
>can the Duke/Granduke of the Spinward Marches interfere on
>moving a fleet from Trin to Guzulin? or on battleship design
>issues? or on budgetary issues?

This touches upon the subject about where is the distinction
between the political and the militatry forces of society?
Military personnel has (in principle) purely a executive function.
They have to make the decisions about where the ships are
and what they are going to do.

Policy makers, on the other hand, are the persons who decide
upon issues pertaing to the grand perspective. They can take
advise from specialists (navy personnel), but eventually, *they*
are the people who make the decisions. This is what makes
them policy makers.

This means that budgetary issuis, IMHO, are in the hands of
the nobility. This way, they will also have very much to say about
which ships ought to be build. Maybe not in detail, but they are
the ones to decide if the Imperium should build Dreadnoughts,
ordinary Battleships, Battleriders or a lot of Cruisers, for example.

On the other hand, the nobility will have only very little (if any) to
say about strategy and tactics, which is the responsibilty of
high ranking Navy officers.

But the distinction can easily become somewhat blurred: A duke
or archduke might decide that "I want a buffer zone between us
and the Aslan here!" or "Our main priority must be to turn away
Vargr and Aslan incursions, and we\'ll just have to hope that the
Zhos won\'t make any trouble!" These are decisions of strategy,
but as far as I can see reasonably an issue that a noble, and
not a navy officer, should decide upon.

>Is it really possible to combine efficiency and local political control?

Well, no one said that the organization of the Imperium is optimal.
Sometimes, when we discuss this, we tend to forget. When I
write how things are in my campaign, it isn\'t a picture of what I
think is perfect organization, it\'s a picture of how I think the
Imperial society actually works. And I don\'t think it\'s perfect.
Personally, I\'m not very keen on feudal systems, yet this is how the
Imperium works, and this is the way I play it. Complete with corrupt
nobles amidst honorable nobles, incompetent nobles among
competent nobles.

The Imperium is not a Utopia, it\'s a simulation of a real society.

Mark Seemann
