    'body' => 'Mark Seemann says:
>The Imperium is not a Utopia, it\'s a simulation of a real society

Well, I guess that\'s the whole point of it..

What I was just trying to say is that since it does not make much sense
for politicians to decide whether to buy Dreadnoughts or Cruisers and
then leave the strategy and tactics to the military, I would have
hoped that one of the first steps taken by Norris would have been to
put some reasonable admiral in charge of the Aslan and Vargr operations
completely free of political interference. In my universe Norris himself
supervises the Vargr front and Tranathiaf (sp?) is in charge of the
Aslan front. (not by chance this is the point where my universe and
GDW\'s started to seriously depart from each another).

Also, I am not worried by politicians saying:
"Our main priority must be to turn away Vargr and Aslan incursions, and 
we\'ll just have to hope that the Zhos won\'t make any trouble!"

but rather by them saying:

"aahhh, now that the Aslan and Vargr are attacking us certainly the
Zhos are not expecting a surprise attack, let\'s do that"
or something equally smart.

My preferred view of political control over the military is that the
civilian government says how much money they can spend and the military
spend it. Or may be they present a number of budgetary options. I would
hope that by the 56th century no civilian would look over the budget for
selectively cutting this and that or moving money from something to something
else.

While I agree that the feudal intermixed chain of command is what we are
told Imperium has, I find plausible that it would be rectified asap when
the chance arises..

One serious problem of the Traveller world is that the technological
advancement has not been followed by a similar cultural and political
development. Despite everything the world has evolved a lot in the
last two thousand years. What we seen in Bosnia now, was rather normal
two centuries ago...On average, countries that develop some technology
develop also the cultural background to use it properly. Obviously
there are exceptions, but I think that the trend is rather clear.
Enslaving the population of a defeated city was normal two thousand
years ago. Armies in the middle ages instead were satisfied by sacking the 
city and raping the women. Nowadays, these things are not normal thanks God.

The Rebellion, the succession by right of assassination, etc.. are very
hard to believe in the 56th century. 

                                    Max


