14/6-95 Massimo Stiavelli wrote:

>One serious problem of the Traveller world is that the technological
>advancement has not been followed by a similar cultural and political
>development.

<snip>

>The Rebellion, the succession by right of assassination, etc.. are very
>hard to believe in the 56th century.

When we look at society today it is correct that feudalism has been
eliminitated in modern societies, but this is due to a wide array of
determining factors. One of them is cheap fast coomunication. The
Imperium doesn\'t have this. For information to travel from one end
of the Imperium to the other takes months! This will seriously affect
the mindset of the people.

Why is the feudal system of the Imperium hard to believe? Because
we look at it from *our* enlightened time with *our* prejudices towards
feudalism. But the fact that feudalism failed once in our history is not
sufficient argumnet that it will never work again.

I think that the average citizen of the Imperium views him/herself as
a free individual. The feudalism of the Imperium does not extend to
the individual citizen, but only defines a hierachy of the upper
echelons of society.

In principle aristocracy can be defended just as well as meritocracy.
In an aristocracy, nobles are raised to lead. When they start out on
their duties, they have a lifetime of education about their responsibilities.
This might work as well as a meritocracy. And remember that nobles
typically will have advisors which are chosen for their skill and not
their heritage, and thus we have a meritocracy on the level just
below the nobles.

As for example Ilelish or Antares was defined as distinct cultural
regions of the Imperium, the Rebellion makes perfect sense to me.
If I lived in Ilelish, I wouldn\'t want to live under the reign of Lucan.

And the right of assasination: I see it as merely a tool for legitimization
of a change of power. When Cleon the Mad was assasinated, his
succesor took over, not because she performed the assasination,
but because she had the support to do it. This works excactly like
the right of fleet control, which was excercized during the first civil
war, although this was never legitimized.

So, as it turned out, Dulinor coudn\'t become emperor because he
didn\'t have the sufficent support. And this in spite of the fact that
if the right of assasination is real, he is the theoretical emperor.

So what you have is a question about power. Strephon\'s greatest
mistake probably was to delegate more power to the Domains. When
the Domains feel they have the power to oppose the Imperium, a
Rebellion-like situation is likely to arise. Not because the system is
a feudal one.

Mark Seemann
