    'body' => 'Hi there

Has anyone considered the effects of atmospheric pressure and local=20
gravity=E2=E2on the performance of aircraft?  I couldn\'t find anything in=
=20
COACC or FF&S which made sense.  Here are my rough ideas.

Fixed Wing aircraft.

Lift: For a given aircraft, at a given speed, this is proportional to the=
=20
gas density.  The density is roughly proportional to air pressure, and=20
also depends on temperature.  Thus, as a rough guide to the ability of=20
your aircraft to fly, multiply its rated weight by local atmospheric=20
pressure to find its lift.

Load: The force due to the aircraft\'s mass depends on the local gravity. =
=20
Thus, to find an aircraft\'s effective maximum load, multiply by local=20
gravity.

Can it fly?  If the lift is more than or equal to the weight, it can=20
fly.  OR As lift also depends on speed, if the lift is less than the=20
speed, then you just need to go faster to take off, but the aircraft will=
=20
not stand up to the sort of manoeuvres it could do under the conditions=20
it was designed for.

Rotary Wing aircraft

About the same as Fixed Wing, except lift must be greater than load, as=20
you can\'t spin the rotors faster without redesigning the aircraft.

Lighter than Aircraft

Lift:  This is equal to the mass of atmosphere displaced.  Thus, as for=20
Fixed Winged aircraft, multiply the lift by local atmospheric pressure,=20
although for different reasons.

Load:  Multiply the unloaded weight by local gravity, and subtract from=20
the lift given above.  Divide the result by local gravity to give you the=
=20
mass which can be carried as load.

Various restrictions need to be made regarding the upper and lower limits=
=20
of pressure and gravity at which an aircraft can still operate if=20
designed for a different environment.  You might also want to modify the=20
construction rules to allow for optimisation to a specific environment.

Speed of sound varies with pressure, too, so maybe the speed limits on=20
airframes could change.

At least these were my thoughts.  Anyone want to pick holes?

