    'body' => 'Some more comments about civilian noble control of the military in the
Imperium:

We have one example of the procurement process from "classic" Traveller.
In the 990s, just after the 3FW and as the Solomani Rim War roared into
life, the IN issued the specification for a new fleet intruder class, 
the _Azhanti High Lightning_ class.  Construction contracts are important
enough to the sector economy that all regions vie for a contract.  Why?
Because the Imperium is paying billions of credits for each ship, which
creates high-tech work for shipyards, key to interstellar commerce.
And with the Marches growing quiet after the end of the 3FW, the raging
Solomani Rim War to rimward meant that most construction contracts would
go closer to the fighting to rimward, and the previously busy naval yards 
in the Marches would lose work.

In order to secure a contract, the Duke of Regina (probably Duke Norris\'s
great-grandfather) spoke for the Marches (before the Moot?) and relayed 
the sector\'s offer to procure an additional cruiser from sector funds on 
the condition that they would be allowed to produce part of the cruiser 
run.  The offer was accepted, and judging by Supplement 5, the LSP yards
at Mora were awarded a contract to build five of the nearly seventy ships.
(Mora was probably one of the few tech-14 worlds in the Marches in 990.)
This was a fairly unique offer, since the Marches covered the additional
cruiser by mounting a fund drive in the schools, collecting quarter-credits
from kids\' lunch money for it, _Children of the March_.  But this sort
of deal might be more common, without the patriotic bells and whistles
and creative fund-raising.  (If I remember the library data version of
this right, it added a comment about a minor scandal involving the way
some local planetary governments handled the money....)

I suspect that IN appropriations are recommended to the Emperor, along with
the rest of the budget, by the Moot.  We also know that there\'s a Ministry
of Defense, with an Imperially-appointed minister of ducal rank, which may
work with the IN in making requests for funding before the Moot committee
in charge of preparing the budget.  Since the nobles are all Moot members,
they through their proxies at the Moot (senators?) can have an influence on
these decisions.  In any case, to make decisions the nobles will need to
get advice from their staffs, since the jobs for the highest of them is
otherwise utterly unmanageable on a scale that is almost incomprehensible. 
And the senators at the Moot will also hear from the fellow nobles whose
proxy votes they hold, and need to report to them afterwards.  Of course,
communications delay means that the Moot attendees will need to vote how
they think now and talk about it after the fact.  Even without the election
cycle, the politics of this means that the Moot will be slow to implement
radical changes, to avoid mistakes.

This brings up another interesting point.  Norris, as Duke Regina, is in
charge of the interstellar government of Regina and Jewell subsectors, and
the Quar/Chronor outpost. (Spinward Marches Campaign)  But he doesn\'t
directly rule Regina -- it has it\'s own planetary executive elected locally
by lottery (I think), who might control the planetary naval flotilla.  
Norris, as Marquis Regina, is only the representative of Regina to the 
Imperium (via the Moot, even if he never attends himself).  This isn\'t 
always the case -- some worlds with gov codes of A or B are ruled by
Imperial legates of marquis rank, like Vincennes in Deneb.  Norris does
have some sizable holdings on Regina which he (actually his staff) must 
oversee, including fiefs, but these are different things.

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonn0015@gold.tc.umn.edu>

