20/6-95 J. Robertson wrote:

>Query: Why are they x-rons? I see that BatRon is some sort of
>Battleship (or formation thereof) and CruRon I assume is a Cruiser
>unit. . .but whence comes this \'ron\' suffix?

The suffix \'ron\' comes from \'squadron\'. Thus, a BatRon is a
Battleship Squadron and a CruRon is a Cruiser Squadron. There
are also Battle Rider Squadrons, Tanker Squadrons and some
other squadron types which I don\'t remember right now.

You can read more about this in GDW\'s \'Fighting Ships of the
Shattered Imperium\' or \'Rebellion Sourcebook\' if you can get hold
on any of these. It\'s the same material offered in both books, so you
only need to buy one of them to get that further information. I
seriously suggest that you buy \'Rebellion Sourcebook\' as \'Fighting
Ships of the Shattered Imperium\' in my opinion is a waste of money.

Mark Seemann
