Wow, you mean it existed?  Hm, I seem to have invented something already
made.  Sheesh.  That always happens.  I just mentioned it in case anyone was
interested in seeing it.  Since then, tho, I cannot find the electronic
files, just the paper printout & transparencies.  
It seems to work pretty good, especially if you prefer (as i do) to have
combat play a minimal and lethal part of the game.
For combat, it\'s straightforward.  I have silhouettes of people at
point-blank, short, med long and xlong ranges.  Player declares what weapon
is shooting, lays the cross hairs where he hopes to hit, and rolls 2d6-skill
(for the hit) and 1d20 for the location.  On the silhouettes are marked into
three areas that signify the lethality of a hit in a given location - light
wound, med, and, you guessed it - heavy.  For the light wound roll 2d6-2 vs
END.  For med 2d6+2, for heavy 2d6+6.  Add 1,4,or 8 to the roll for every
previous wound in this combat (lt,med,hvy, respectively)  So a traveller
that had been hit for a moderate wound previously gets hit by a light wound,
would roll 2d6-2+4= +2 roll vs END.
Couldn\'t ever figure how to do sprayed autofire.
Steve Lieb
