    'body' => 'In x317, David P. Summers asks:

>Regarding the Droynes invisibilty ability.  Since this is a psionic talent
>that affects the mind of the potential observer, do people think it affects
>hearing, etc.???

There are several possible approaches:
(1) Treat as AD&D invisibility - i.e. sound, smell, etc. are not affected.
(2) Treat as full sense invisibility - i.e. sound, smell, etc. ARE affected.
Note that this does not make the Droyne\'s footprints invisible if it walks
through mud or if someone throws flour over the Droyne.
(3) Have you read any Terry Pratchett? Treat as the \'invisibility\' of Death
(and his close relatives). i.e. people sort of remember seeing someone but
they can\'t quite pin down who, and obviously it wasn\'t very important and...
basically they just aren\'t \'aware\' that the Droyne is there, as long as it
doesn\'t do anything to bring attention to itself. If someone really
concentrates damned hard (having already been made aware of the Droyne\'s
powers) then they might be able to pick up the Droyne. The rest of the time,
people just appear to \'ignore\' the Droyne, in every possible sense - i.e.
it\'s footprints are ignored, because if there\'s no one there to make the
footprints, then by definition they don\'t exist, so the onlooker doesn\'t see
them. And if the Droyne isn\'t there, then covering it with flour obviously
won\'t make it any easier to see, so that\'s how it works - it isn\'t any
easier to see! Impeccable logic.

Cmdr Lilly, PITS (Political Intelligence Team, Scout)
Chief Investigator, Alien Mind-Emanating Racial Invisibility Conspiracy
Association (AMERICA), sponsored by Kindred Imperial Culture Konclave Across
Stellar Systems (?)

