    'body' => 'In a message dated 95-07-09 14:57:35 EDT, Massimo Stiavelli  wrote:

> the missile is capable of 6G for 6 turns..(that\'s
>how I read 6G6..) are these 6 seconds turns or 1200 seconds turns??

Then  Django Upton wrote:

>I thought 6G6 indicated a maximum acceleration of 6G per turn with fuel for 
>6 G-turns of acceleration although I might have that wrong.
>This is from Special Supplement 3: Missiles.
>The turns were assumed to be 1000 seconds ( use 1200 seconds for MT ).

In case it might help shed some light, way back in 1978, GDW published a game
called MAYDAY,  one of thier Series 120 games which they called a "variant"
of the Traveller ("classic") starship rules.  Marc Miller was it\'s designer.
 In MAYDAY Miller writes:  "The acceleration, or G factor for vessels (in
MAYDAY this includes missles) is expressed as an indication of maximum
acceleration for the movement phase, and maximum total acceleration allowed
before fuel exhaustion.  Thus 1G5 indicates a maximum course change of 1 hex
(per movement phase), and a total course change of 5 hexes."   If Miller\'s
and GDW\'s past use of the 6G6 style notation is any indication, 6G6 means
that the missle can pull 6 Gs for 1 turn, or 1 G for 6 turns, or 2 Gs for 3
turns, or 2 Gs for 1 turn and 4 Gs for a second turn, etc.

But to confuse matters futher, in MAYDAY the turns were _100  minutes_ and a
hex was 1 light second across!  Those 6G6 missles (which were standard in the
game) could haul butt, accelerating at a constant 1 G for 10 hours!!

By the way MAYDAY is still my favorite system for small ship movement and
combat.  It\'s simple and elegant, only has 7 pages of rules so new players
can be controling ships in a short time, and meshes very well with Classic
Traveller.  It meshes a little less well with MegaTraveller.

Hope this helps.

