    'body' => '"M. Harelick"  <msh9848@hertz.njit.edu> asked:

>1. Why is tactics more important than dexterity? 

Tactics governs group activity, not any individual 
characteristic.

>2. If players have different ideas about how to fight 
>an enemy, why should their tactics be put together? 

I\'ve never been in the military, nor in any covert operations, 
nor in any other situation where I was intentionally exposing 
myself to violence, but if I were going to do so with other 
adventurers, I would damned well be sure that, if violence arose,
I could count on them to act cohesively and competently and for 
the good of the group.

>I think that alot of the Traveller combat system believes that 
>two sides of a combat are going to act as two whole groups 
>rather than as individuals. 

Yes, I think it does.  I\'m not going to raid Genentech\'s corporate
offices, nor sabotage Alameda Naval Air Station, nor hijack the
Larkspur/SF ferry with people I don\'t know, who have their own 
agendas and goals, and who might start shooting when to do so will
blow surprise and get us all killed, or who will shoot at their own
preferred targets of opportunity and not at the squad of troops about 
to kill me.  My character isn\'t likely to participate in such actions 
against the 58th Century equivalents in those circumstances, either.

In refereeing and playing various rpgs for almost 20 years, I\'ve found 
that conflicts among player characters that lead to a lack of trust 
on the battlefield are the most likely causes of failed missions and 
failed games.  I suspect the same is true for real world small groups 
engaged in organized violence.

--Glenn
