    'body' => '> In refereeing and playing various rpgs for almost 20 years, I\'ve found 
> that conflicts among player characters that lead to a lack of trust 
> on the battlefield are the most likely causes of failed missions and 
> failed games.  I suspect the same is true for real world small groups 
> engaged in organized violence.


I\'ve found that mature players generally have no problems acting as a group. 
Sure there are disagreements, but they get resolved at the planning stages. 
When I started reffing games for my high school students I had a hard time
adjusting to the "every player for himself" style of the less mature players.
 

Now, there are games (such as Paranoia) when backstabbing and treachery are
essential.  If everyone knows they are playing this style game, and it is
just a game, then I wouldn\'t label it immature.  Generally, though, I\'ve
found "going your own way" strongly correlated to "sulks", "argues with GM",
and "carries grudges between games".  

That said, I\'d rather play with some of my high school students than many
adults.  Great people, and getting better.
