    'ts-index' => '1995-07-17.ab558',
    'body' => 'As the original poster of the question about interrupts, I\'ve been
getting enough email that I think it\'s time to clarify a few things.

I understand the utility of interrupts in a many-to-many combat situation.
If person A sees enemy B about to give a killing shot to A\'s friend C,
then it is reasonable to expect A to try to interrupt B.

My problem is if, in the above example, C tries to interrupt B.  I\'m 
finding that it is not fair to allow a person to interrupt one\'s own
attacker.  The rules make this clear for hand-to-hand combat but imply
that it\'s okay in direct fire combat.  I am beginning to disagree with
this implication.

Basically, I\'m looking for a good reason to allow interrupts against
one\'s own attacker in direct fire situations.  Can anyone come up with
a good example of where it\'s realistic?

Someone pointed out that the initiative being discussed here is not like
the D&D initiative.  With MT, having the initiative means you get to say
who goes first.  I maintain that, in 99% of the cases involving non-military
player characters, it is essential that the side with the initiative goes
first.
Traveller combat is very deadly.  The person who gets off the first shot 
usually survives.

Comments?

-- 
Erwin Fritz  (erwin@fritz.cuug.ab.ca)
Technical Analyst
DMR Group, Inc.

