    'index' => 'ab561',
    'month' => '07',
    'body' => 'This is a first report on engagements by units of a Red and a Blue Gamma
Iridium bdes in a desertic range.

Red order of battle:
1 Mechanized company
Anti-Tank section (from Mech. btn) 
1 Tank company
Cavalry lance (from Tank btn)
2 Air-Defence sections (from Artillery grp)
2 FIST sections (from Artillery grp)

Blue order of battle:
1 Mechanized company
Anti-Tank section (from Mech. btn)
FIST section (from Mech. btn)
1 Tank company
Cavalry lance (from Tank btn)
Anti-Tank section (from Tank btn)
Cavalry troop
2 FIST sections (from Artillery grp)

The Blue party has a modest numerical advantage but otherwise their forces
and goals are similar, i.e. conquer and defend for 5 turns a given hex
in the desert.

I will skip the detailed description of the house rules used and the
battle outline, listing only the lessons learned so far (some we already
knew about...)

1- artillery is very effective and counter-battery fire is deadly.
2- the most effective vehicles (FIST and HKV anti-tank) are equipped
   with starship weapons rather than vehicle weapons.
3- in the engagements FIST and HKV were used much too close to the
   enemy forces and were therefore very vulnerable to counterbattery.
4- MBGT are of very little effectiveness and they were not involved
   in any engagement (except as targets..).
5- CGT have some effectiveness. A faster version of CGT able to operate
   with the IFV would be much more useful.
6- sensor performance is crucial, the detailed sensor rules may totally
   change the outcome of an engagement. It would be interesting to explore 
   the possibility of requiring a forward observer also to direct long 
   range direct fire.
7- infantry should leave the IFVs before engaging (or being engaged by)
   the opponent.
8- air-defence units are useless in fighting other vehicles.




