    'body' => '
> >1. Why is tactics more important than dexterity?
>
> Imagine an Imperial Marine gets in a gunfight with a gold medal gymnast at
> the Imperial Olympics. My money\'s on the Marine to get the first (and last)
> shot off, even if the gymnast outpoints him/her heavily in the dex
department.

>
> Traveller seems to assume that training is more important than natural
> ability in this sort of situation; for the most part, I agree with them.
> Tactics skill was probably chosen as a pretty good indication of this sort
> of training.

In the situation you describe, I would rule that for initiative:

Marine : Tactics + Dex/5
Gymnast: Tactics + Dex/5

In a pure shot for shot round the Marine would shoot first and probably nail
the gymnast. However even if the gymnast went first, he/she/it probably
would not hit which means the Marine would nail him/her/it anyway.

The difference between what I am saying here and what Traveller is saying is
lets say Marines A, B, and C are shooting at the gymnast then
each marines initiative would be

Tactics of A + Tactics of B + Tactics of C + Dex/5. This should not be
the case for several reasons:

1. Each marine is taking an individual action.

2. Even if they are acting in unison, the other marines can not make the
first one any faster.

Matthew S. Harelick
My opinions are my own, not IBM\'s.



