20/7-95 Zane wrote:

>have a planet with a Chlorine-Nitrogen atmosphere.  I\'ve
>checked out "Special Supplement 2: Exotic
>Atmospheres" and the "World Builders Handbook", so I
>know that it would have strong concentrations of liquid
>Hydrochloric Acid.
>    The real problem is this planet is inhabited.  Does
>anybody have any idea what kind of life and vegetation
>would inhabit a planet such as this?

Are the inhabitants native? In Traveller, lots of lifeless
planets have been settled by humans or other races,
who then lives in sealed environments.

If the life and vegetation is native, though, there are at least
two possibilities: One is to have ordinary carbon-based
life with a resistance to hydrochloric acid (not that unlikely
- just postulate a slime covering like in the human stomach).
The other possibility is to have life based on another
element than carbon. There is a little about it in WBH in the
section about exotic atmospheres. I don\'t exactly
remember, but I think chloride was a possible substitute
for carbon as a building block for life.

Anyway, according to evolution theory, lifeforms would
develop fit to their environment. Thus, appearence
probably would not differ much in either case. Take a look
at the planet and try to determine which sort of life is
present.

Remember that life does not have to be a full fledged
complete eco-systems with animals, plants and
complicated food-chains (sp?). Microbiological life is life
too, and maybe that\'s all there is. In my (Mega)Traveller
universe, this sort of native life is very common on worlds
with hostile environments, if present at all.

>    For all that goes what would the planet look like?  I\'m
>sure it wouldn\'t be green with a blue sky!

It depends on the type of the star. An M-type star, for
example, emits light almost only in the red spectrum.
Therefore such a star would make a sky red regardless
of atmosphere.

A G-star, OTOH, emits white light, which can be broken into
all other colors. The color of the light predominant in the
sky depends on the density of the atmosphere. There\'s
a rule of thumb, but I don\'t remember it right now. I have it written down at
h
ome, so if anyone\'s interested, I\'d try to
remember to look it up.

More specifically about an atmosphere containing
hydrochloric acid. Much of it will probably be in gas form.
As impure hydrochloric acid tends to be slightly green
(actually, it\'s a rather noxious looking color), I would expect
this atmosphere to be maybe a hazy green. An otherwise
blue sky would shift towards green, depending on the
amount of hydrocloric acid.

>    Does anybody have any idea where I can find further
>ideas for such a planet, other than the two that I\'ve
>mentioned.

There was an article in Challenge called something like
"getting science into science fiction", but I don\'t remember
the number. If noone else remembers, I can have a look
at it at home.

This is where I\'ve gotten lot of the stuff about star spectres
and sky color.

For an idea about other elements than carbon as building
blocks for life, take a look at a periodic table and pick
common elements with the same valens (sp?) as carbon.
I believe sulphur is a viable alternative too.

Hope this helps.

Mark Seemann
