    'body' => 'This is a report on engagements by units of a Red Iridium bde Gamma
and a Blue Regiment Delta  in a desertic range.

As usual it has been abridged, the unabridged version is in
http://astro.sns.it/~mstiavel/Traveller

Red order of battle:
3 Mechanized companies
Anti-Tank section (from mech btn)
FIST section (from mech btn)
1 Air-Defence section (from mech btn)
1 Cavalry troop
1 Air-Defence section (from Artillery grp)
2 FIST sections (from Artillery grp)
1 Meson-Gun Boat (from Artillery grp)
6 S-drones

Blue order of battle:
3 Cavalry troops
1 Tank company (from cavalry sqdn)
2 FIST sections (from cavalry sqdn)
1 Air-Defence section (from Artillery grp)
2 FIST sections (from Artillery grp)
1 Meson-Gun Boat (from Artillery grp)
10 S-drones

The battle went as follows:

The Blue has the initiative and moves two platoons of mechanized infantry
and one air-defence section on the target, while moving all forces to
surround it. A fair fraction of its units are moved at subsonic speed to 
reduce signature. 
The Red moves most of its forces near the target, moving at subsonic speed. 
Two Red mechanized infantry companies and the tank company face the target,
while the third mechanized infantry company attempts an encircling maneuver
(moving at supersonic speed).
Once at their final positions (15 km from the target for some three platoons)
the infantry dismounts from the vehicles.

Both parties carry out numerous sensor tasks. Two Blue mechanized platoon
are detected and fired upon by the Meson gun boat and the Anti-tank
section. However, both fire at more than 50 km range and miss the
target. Further recognaissance from the Red identifies the Blue forces
on the target. They are fired upon by a Red FIST section at 45 km
range and destroyed. The Red FIST is then destroyed by Blue Meson Gun fire.

Both parties become very conservative in the use of their Artillery,
to avoid counterbattery fire. In practice, the use is restricted to
low signature weapons (Meson Gun and, for the Red, Anti-Tank guns).

The Red occupies the target with dismounted infantry. The battle
becomes confused and violent with the Blue attempting to destroy the
Red tanks while trying to preserve its numerically inferior infantry.
Since the Blue has available a total of 9 platoon equivalents of tanks
(6 cavalry lances + 1 tank company), while the Red has only 3, it is
relatively easy for the Blue to eliminate the Red Tank force. At this
stage the Blue can start to engage the Red infantry which is now 
incapable of penetrating the armor of the Blue tanks (except by
directing long distance artillery fire).

The end-result could then be classified as a Blue marginal victory.

Lessons:
1- mechanized infantry needs a weapon able to inflict at least
   low penetration hits to the cavalry tanks.
2- infantry can be useful to held positions since it has low
   visibility and it can be used to direct Meson Gun fire.
3- with improved anti-tank infantry weapons and speed reduced to
   subsonic to avoid detection, the MBGT, with its heavier armor, 
   regains part of its usefulness.

As a reaction to the these engagements the Imperial Army has introduced the
IFV2, a version of the IFV with one of the point defence RPA14 replaced
by a fusion gun FY14 able to penetrate the CGT and CGT2 armor
(although not the MBGT armor).





