    'body' => 'I hope that the following problem has not been so 
extensively discussed before that this post draws pgip 
attacks (here in Berkeley, we call them "plasma gun, 
individual-portable", not the sexist/specist 
"man-portable").

In MT, are astrogation and its related observing and 
measuring devices adequate for ships to rendezvous at 
prearranged coordinates in a hex not containing a star 
system?

It seems that it would not be difficult to say, "we\'ll
meet during the period 100 to 110-1109 in the Terra/Sol
system, at Point Option, defined as the intersection of
Line A and Line B, where Line A runs through the centers of
Sol and Terra and Line B runs through the centers of Mars
and Jupiter." A ship could jump into the system anywhere,
observe the location of the four points, draw the lines to
determine , use the computer to figure out where Point 
Option will be when the ship arrives, and go there.

Now suppose you want to meet in deep space, more than one
parsec from any star system.  One problem with defining
Point Option as the intersection of lines connecting two
stars is that the lines may not be in the same planes, and
hence may not intersect.  So our definition of Point
Option must be more complex.  Maybe it\'s the point at which 
the angle between the rays from the point to stars A and B 
measures x degrees, and the rays from the point to stars A 
and C measures y degrees.

So if we define Point Option as in the last paragraph, how
much error will our ship\'s sensors and computer cause; or,
stated more relativistically, how much will our conception
of Point Option\'s location disagree with that of the other 
ship(s) that we\'re meeting here?

In what other ways have you handled or heard of handling
deep space rendezvous?  

