    'body' => '"Glenn M. Goffin" <ggoffin@igc.apc.org> asks:
>In MT, are astrogation and its related observing and 
>measuring devices adequate for ships to rendezvous at 
>prearranged coordinates in a hex not containing a star 
>system?

and then goes on to mention crossing lines between known objects to get a
meeting point in space.

My comments are:
3D-nav in space uses measured positions of system bodies plus data from nav
satellites/beacons to locate oneself according to a 3D XYZ or angle/range
coordinate system, usually centred (e.g. XYZ = 0,0,0) on the main system
star. In addition to the possibility of extending these coordinates out
beyond the given parsec into adjacent ones there are also wider-scale
navigation coordinates based in the 3D position of star systems around a
ship, etc. Although the Traveller parsec mapping appears planar (2D), this
is widely accepted to be an approximation with \'adjacent\' parsecs often some
distance above or below this plane. Some coordinate systems radiate from a
given homeworld to the subsectors around, while others are based on the
theoretical centre of the Milky Way. Such involve _huge_ numbers to get a
resolution of even millions of kilometres, let alone tens or hundreds.

3D positioning by satellite is a common system now (GPS, etc.) and merely
requires distances to be measured (using the time delay of a signal from the
beacon) from which, given the known locations of the satellites (data
transmitted by the satellites themselves) you can calculate your 3D
position. No \'line intersection\' is required.

Accuracy at parsec ranges is not obtainable using the nav beacon systems
because:
(a) No one bothers to transmit that powerful a signal when the main use is
in system, so a parsec away you can\'t detect the signal.
(b) If you could receive it, it would be 3.26 years out of date. Not much
use unless you keep accurate almanacs detailing the satellite movements etc.
for the past 3-4 years.

So, the directions to multiple stars (any direction - no intersecting
lines!) would be used to calculate 3D position in deep space. Probably
accurate to within a few tens of kilometres given the high tech sensors and
computers to be found on even a simple trader ship.

Hope this is of some use?

