In XBOAT Digest 346, "Glenn M. Goffin" <ggoffin@igc.apc.org> writes:

>In what other ways have you handled or heard of handling
>deep space rendezvous?  

This was a little something that I once thought of - why has there not been
a refueling station built in the middle of the Great Rift to enable less
than J5 crossings? It would only need J2 or J3 tankers moving fuel to it on
a regular basis and you could have a convenient waypoint for traders - with
fuel at much increased prices to pay for the priviledge.

So I reasoned that if they don\'t do it, then they can\'t!

My reasoning and handling of Jump drives is that they are intrinsically
linked to gravitational wells. This is not so unreasonable as they are
obviously affected by them due to misjump likelihood within 100 diameters of
a planet etc.

So, in my universe, Jump Drives link two places of equal gravitational
potential. i.e. if you jump 101 diameters out from a planet, you will arrive
101 diameters away from the next one. (In actual fact, I prefer to use
0.0001 G and 0.01 G as my jump problem cutoffs rather than 100 and 10
diameters and recalculate diameters for extremely dense or un-dense(?)
bodies). Sort of a conservation of gravitational potential energy type idea.

Hence, you could not jump into an empty hex as there is no equal gravity
potential location to jump from. (I guess if you really wanted to spend a
few weeks trawling out of system on M-Drives to a very low gravitational
potential then you could do it).

I also do not allow specific positioning of re-entry point and exact
orientation - you know exactly how far out you will arrive, but it could be
anywhere on that sphere. The point on the sphere will technically depend on
the positions of the other bodies in that system and their cumulative effect
on the gravitational potential which is far beyond the scope of a
roleplaying game, so I just take the nearest body. This unknown arrival
point prevents the old rock chucking exercise :-) However, for the sake of
heightened gameplay, I do allow task checks to place the ship *roughly* in
the right place and pointing the right way, but never exactly.

I suppose it is possible to go and build an artificial planetoid out in an
empty hex and use that as a gravity well which you can match in the
departure system, but this would be a massive project requiring
transportation by M-Drive first. 
Hey - adventure idea - misjump into an empty hex containing a jump
waystation put there by the Ancients :-)

Ralph.
