    'topic' => 'jump and physics',
    'body' => 'Commenting on the recent discussions on jump exit points.

The idea of jump from equipotential points has indeed the advantage of
conserving energy but seems to me quite in contrast with the rules.

The 100 diameters idea is not that bad since, under the assumption that
all bodies have roughly the same density, makes the jump
dependent on the strength of tidal forces (rather than potential
or force) which are related to the Christoffel symbols in general
relativity. Why it should be so is unclear, but since in G.R. every
observer can choose a coordinate system making spacetime locally flat
with only tidal forces left, such a dependence does not seem totally
dumb. Actually I must admit that I found it surprisingly smart, and
would be tempted to guess that GDW did not think about it.

The 100 diameters rule would then have to be changed near extremely dense
bodies like white dwarfs, neutron stars or black holes.

In this scheme energy conservation must be solved in some other way,
my best guess is thermal radiation: the jump drive releases enormous
amounts of energy which could be easily decreased or increased by
the potential energy difference (which above 100 diameters is not
very large). 

>From the game point of view I have always use the jump in the middle
of nowhere capability. Fleets do it, players do it. 
The ability to jump where no star exists also affects to a significant
extent naval strategy.

In my universe there are also a certain number of refuelling stations in 
the rift but they are reserved to military and intelligence purposes. Once
it is possible not doing it would not be smart..

