    'topic' => ' deep space rendezvous <XBd#346)',
    'body' => '"Glenn M. Goffin" <ggoffin@igc.apc.org> asks:
> In MT, are astrogation and its related observing and 
> measuring devices adequate for ships to rendezvous at 
> prearranged coordinates in a hex not containing a star 
> system?

Yes.  Ships can choose a set of jump coordinates for an arbitrary location
in deep space, and ships jumping to those coordinates will be able to
contact one another without difficulty.

A canonical reference exists in _The Traveller Adventure_.  A deep-space
location is used for rendezvous and refuelling by Akerut Lines, a Tukera
subsidiary.  During a tradewar with Oberlindes Lines, Oberlindes manages
to acquire the rendezvous coordinates, and dispatches a few starships to
capture Akerut ships that use the point.

> In what other ways have you handled or heard of handling
> deep space rendezvous?  

Normal interstellar navigation routines, for programming jumps, have to be
accurate to within a few light-seconds at very most.  This is easily
accurate enough to establish a rendezvous.


wildstar@quark.qrc.com

