    'id' => '<9508030851.AA14090@internet1.lotus.com>',
    'date' => '3 Aug 95  8:45:15 EDT',
    'body' => 'Yo Folkes,
    I took brief umbrage at a previous message where a poster
said that because he was a "Christian" he considered much of
SF fantasy. I wished to correct him saying that the bulk of
Christians are happy considering the creation myths in Genesis
along side the parables of Jesus as religious education stories,
not literal truth. It is the Fundamentalist (or Evangelical)
movements of Christianity, Judaism and Islam that choose to
believe these things literally, and dispite the press, these
are not the mainstream, world-wide.
    However having spawned far too many political arguments in
the past (i.e. more than one) I didn\'t want to spawn a religious
one. So I made no direct response. It does, though, bring up an
interesting field that has never been adequately exploited in
most role-playing games: religion. Obviously real publishers
stay well away from it for commercial reasons but as religious
is often such a large part of our lives (if not personally then
how it affects people we deal with) it should be a fertile
ground for RPGs.
    In a Paranoia campaign I played in I had a character who
dealt with, and was eventually converted by, The First Church
of Christ: Computer Programmer. It was great fun trying to
reinterpret Christianity in the world of Alpha Complex (gives
a whole new meaning to the Alpha and the Omega :-). I even
went so far as to "translate" the first few books of Mark
to Alpha Complex Terms. Amusing, fun, and perhaps giving a
small insight into our own religious experience.
    Anyway, in a Traveller setting worlds are often portrayed
as extensions of certain mundane stereotypes. There are already
two government codes for religious based societies.
    A wonderful example of a good use of religion in SF is
Dune by Frank Herbert (actually I would be A Canticle for Liebowitz
at the top but that doesn\'t have as many RPG hooks). Forget
about the big worms. Forget about the spice. Forget about the
woeful notion of biological determinism that permeates the
whole first book. Instead read the appendicies. Read about the
council of religions and the religious history of the Empire.
Take and use.
    For example "The Butlerian Jihad" was a movement to exterminate
all "thinking machines". Parallels exist in Traveller with the
Society for Supremacy of Man over Machine (?). Take the philosophy,
permeate it with religious ritual and language, and populate a
planet with it. The temptation is to play such a place as ignorant
fanatics. I would urge you not to. These are likely to be genuine
people with genuine concerns for your players soul. They may phrase
their concerns in religious terms like "use of Abominations imperils
your soul" where the philosophical translation is "reliance on
machines you cannot reproduce leaves you vulnerable to what
unreliability they possess."
    In Dune a large Ecumenical Council was convened to put an end
to religious factionalism. They spent a good number of years and
together produced a body of literature "The Orange Catholic Bible"
to subsume the best and most tolerant of all their religions.
Many of them were lynched and all but 12 of the original 120(?)
recanted. Yet 4000 years later this has become THE religious work.
Using this sort of a mechanic in a campaign is very useful as
it allows the DM to develop and become familiar with a single
religious tract for the whole Imperium.
    One of the coolest concepts in Dune was "The Missonaria
Protectivia" (sp?). This was a branch of the Bene Gesserit (which
can be described as a religion) sent "missionaries" out beyond 
the fringe during their equivalent of The Long Night. They contacted
primitive or emerging cultures and indoctrinated them with
myth-cycles and specific religious language and terminology.
Easily accomplished through the use of more advanced drugs and
machines. Thus as their Empire pushed back the borders, sometimes
hundreds of years later, their "cult" could step in, fulfil these
amazing secret prophecies, and immediately be accepted in
religious authority by the people. It would be really cool as
a particular offshoot of the Scout service.
    So lets go back to the original seed of this discussion.
Fundamentalism provides a satisfying religious view for a
large number of people. It is unlikely to go away in the
future. What of a world of such people? Say the players had
the first Aslan to visit the world. What would a people who
religious don\'t believe in aliens make of it? Again, the temptation
is to play them as bigoted fanatics, willing to kill and eradicate
this challenge to their ways. Perhaps at a common level this idea
might permeate. However it is more likely that those religiously
trained would attempt to seek to understand where this fits
into their religion. Perhaps there is an overlooked hook in
their Holy Book that can be reinterpreted to deal with such.
Perhaps a wider interpretation of another statement. Congregations
would be upset at this apparent challenge and such players might
find their Clergy more than willing to engage in discourse to
attempt to find their place in the universe so that they can
pass the message on.
    Take it another way. Say a member of clergy from some
religion crashed on a primitive planet. Say she was moved by
what were obviously intelligent, non-human natives, and
preached her religion. Say this caught on and long after her
death these aliens are contacted and given spaceflight. Perhaps
they might particularly welcome it because now they can go
on pilgrimage to all the ancient shrines and holy places of
"their" religion. But if the original religion (or its descendant)
does not accept alien worshipers, the conflict of the devout
has much potential. Especially if the players are piloting the
ship of the pilgrims on behalf of the Scout service for Imperial
concessions on the new planet.
    The last word I would say is "don\'t back out for fear of
offending people". There are loads of conflicting view in modern
society. They challenge people and make people think. As long
as you don\'t try to say what you portray in the game relates to
reality they can always take the approach that it is all "fantasy".
Always allow for the exploration of new ideas. Role-playing doesn\'t
have to be "Just Escapism". 
     Cheers,
                  Jo
