    'topic' => 'Nuclear missiles and nuclear dampers',
    'body' => '
Glenn Goffin asks what sort of radioactive materials might be used at higher
tech levels.  I think GDW has yet again overlooked an important consequence of
traveller technology.  I would guess that after nuclear dampers become 
available, there is no need to use radioactives in warheads.  Macroscopic 
manipulation of the strong and weak forces allows so much neat stuff!!! You\'d
have to be able to manipulate both to stop all radioactivity.  So why not put
a lump of lead 208 in the warhead, which is non-radioactive, but getting up in 
that range where nothing is stable.  Flip on the nuclear damper (properly tuned
of course) and suddenly, lead 208 decays by spontaneous fission with a halflife
of a microsecond.  You have an instant nuke, no messy triggers, and you don\'t
even need a chain reaction because the whole reaction mass is coaxed into
fissioning all at once.

Does anything in the canon say anything about this?  I don\'t know much of the
background, I\'ve only been playing trav for 5 years :)

you might even do something like this in reactors (fission or fusion) so long
as the power required by the nuclear damper was less than that produced in the
reaction.

-Ted Baltz				Pigs make lousy ninjas.
-fizix student
-eabaltz@mit.edu			-Hamton, from Tiny Toons
