    'body' => '

"Glenn M. Goffin" <ggoffin@igc.apc.org> said:

> I assume that naval-type vessels will have self-destruct
> capabilities (as in the Classic Star Trek episode, Let
> That Be Your Last Battlefield).

Why would you want to self-destruct your ship?

>destruction of boarding parties and their mother ships would sort of
> an anticipatory revenge function

Except that if self-destruct mechanisms were a common feature of warships, 
boarding stricken warships would be an extremely under-utilised tactic. The 
most common tactic would be to keep firing on the thing until it was 
completely destroyed.

The only other reason that I can think of is to stop technology falling into 
enemy hands. Except that this assumes two things:

1. the enemy\'s espionage network is rubbish.
2. the item has not already been destroyed in the battle.

> The most efficient destructive methods that I can imagine are (1)  programmed
> jump failure and (2) fusion power plant explosion.

Alternatively explode a shaped charge in the ship\'s missile magazine - or 
just set fire to the magazine (think about HMS Argonaut in the Falklands 
war). That\'d do it every time.

Modern warships don\'t carry dedicated self-destruct mechanisms (at least not 
in the Royal Navy) - and I personally would not have been happy living on 
board one that did. Also, modern warships are too cramped to allow space to 
be taken up by something that would (hopefully) never be used.


Finally, jeff.zeitlin@execnet.com (JEFF ZEITLIN), unable to resist being 
tacky and speciesist (no self-control <sigh> :-) ), said:

> Perhaps they don\'t stick their heads out the window while driving
> - but do they still drink out of the... ummm... "facility"?

Only when they can\'t find a glass.


Dave

