    'month' => '08',
    'index' => 'ab628',
    'body' => '<Jo\'s excellent commentary snipped>

Back in the mid 80\'s I had a Ref run an absolutely incredible adaptation of
the short story "The Way of Cross And Dragon"  by, forgive my memory, John M.
Ford or George R.R. Martin (both no strangers to Traveller).  Each of us
played retainers and crewmembers to a Knight empowered by her holiness the
Pope to root out heresies.

The original story involves an idyllic planet swept by a novel form of
Catholicism that elevates Judas to sainthood(!) with a mythic retelling of
his life that resonates with the natives on a fundamental level.  In this
alternate version Judas becomes the master of Earth\'s dragons and is
eventually tested by his conflicting love for them and devotion to Christ.
 His tale of revenge, triumph, defeat, and redemption is so beautiful and
moving that you genuinely wish it were true, and that\'s the lynchpin of the
story: the entire heresy has been carefully manufactured to appeal to the
natives and advance the agenda of an underground movement.

The Ref did a masterful job of bringing the story alive.  The first act had
us researching the details of the heretics canon and manuevering through the
politics of the church administration.  The second act involved the footwork
needed to prove the heresy false (the planetary database was filled with
"facts" supporting it), discover it\'s origins, and expose the perpetrators.
 The final act was the physical and theological confrontation with the rather
noble founders of the heresy.  The adventure worked on so many levels that I
still remember it fondly nearly a decade later.

Since then I\'ve always thought that a campaign built around the activities of
the church in the Imperium would be a blast.  If you happen to run across the
story you\'ll see almost immediately how easy it would be to translate into
the classic universe.  I\'ve even wondered if it\'s possible that it *started*
as a Traveller adventure considering the two potential authors familiarity
with the game.

Cordially,
MM

PS- Pick up Martin\'s "Tuf Voyaging" for some great adventure fiction filled
with game ideas.  When I read it I thought he\'d set it in the Traveller
universe and just filed off the serial numbers
