    'topic' => 'Certain cultural issues relating to the Vargr',
    'index' => 'ab645',
    'month' => '08',
    'body' => '>Finally, let\'s lay one common myth to a long-overdue
>rest. After three hundred thousand years of evolution
>Vargr no longer stick their heads out of the window when
>they\'re driving.

>I\'m sorry.  It\'s totally tacky and speciesist, but I can\'t
>resist:

>Perhaps they don\'t stick their heads out the window while
>driving - but do they still drink out of the... ummm...
>"facility"? 

Now comments like the foregoing don\'t really help further 
the development of interstellar society, do they?

Seriously though, what do you do when you get home from
another crazy day at Yoyodyne Propulsion Systems and your
partner has left you the following email:  "I\'ve invited
the new writer and spouses (the Gvaekneuerrs, you remember,
we just hired Vengue) out for dinner tonight -- meet first
for drinks at our place at 19:30 -- please pick a
restaurant and make reservations -- xxOO see you soon"?

Well, vegetarian restaurants are right out, of course.  In
fact, the Vargr metabolism requires ingestion of fairly
raw red meat on a regular basis, so perhaps the Original
Melharris [sorry SF joke] [no, San Francisco, not science
fiction] is in order. 

But first, what about those drinks at 7:30?  I wouldn\'t
recommend serving anything in champagne flutes or little
cordial glasses. While Mr & Mrs & Mr & Whatever
Gvaekneuerr can certainly stick their tongues down to the
bottom of a narrow glass, they\'ll probably be more
comfortable with a broader lapping surface, like, well,
like a bowl.  Maybe those little celadon soup bowls or the 
ceramic cha cups will do.

Ok, what do Vargr drink?  We should serve some
non-alcoholic beverages as well as cocktails.  You can\'t
go wrong with water, but it\'s boring.  Will they have
problems with bubbles going up their snouts if you serve
something carbonated?  Are they lactose-intolerant?  Maybe
you should just ask the meat department at the grocery
store for a few pints of fresh blood.  (Gvurrdon Bloody
Marys are the an initiation drink in certain elite Imperial
Marine regiments -- a treat for the Vargr recruits, but
bloody awful for the humans.) 

Alcohol is another problem.  We know that canines will get
drunk (a chihuaha once consumed a huge tequila sunrise that
my friend had put on the floor by his chair -- after
staggering around and making a few odd noises, the dog
threw up violently and went to sleep).  England\'s
beer-drinking dogs are famous, too.  So maybe you should
get some dark beer and skip the tequila.  Will nitrites in
the wine be a problem?

The Gvaekneuerrs arrive and are very nice and lap up their
MHD Plasma (locally microbrewed, of course) with gusto. Did
you cover your good fabrics with plastic? -- some
splashing is likely to have occurred.  Maybe 57th Century
cleaning technology can handle it.  The real reason that
Vargr wear shoes is probably to protect the furniture from
their sharp nails (how many times have your mothers told
you, "now put your shoes on before you start running
around in the house"?)

After a pleasant hour of "Oh, yes, I did smuggle that red
rock home from Mars when we went there on vacation 15
years ago -- I hope there weren\'t any microorganisms on
it," and "Gryess, thrat\'s rour rold hrouse ron Rrrejrina,
rin thra Sprinrrrd Mrarchres", your taxi arrives and
whisks you to Original Melharris.

Vengue Gvaekneuerr orders a raw rack of lamb:  "You meant 
underdone, sir?" "Nro, dron\'t cookr it at rall -- jrust 
warm it rup a rittle."  When it arrives, Vengue eschews knife 
and fork and zestfully tears strips of meat from the bone, 
chewing (as he must) with his mouth at least partially 
open.  He probably learned when he was a pup not to shake 
his meat to make sure that it was dead.  

What about the chicken samosa appetizers?  I think that you
and the Gvaekneuerrs will both eat them by hand in quick
bites.  The arugula and tomatillo salad (this is San
Francisco, after all): probably with forks at a human
restaurant, but at home, probably slurped up with their
tongues.  The prawn and coconut milk soup?  Slurrp!  I\'ll
bet the staff at Melharris gave them and you lobster
napkins, even if nobody ordered lobster.

Lobster?  They\'d probably use the tools to break open the
carapace, but their fingernails are a lot easier to work
with.  

Dessert:  Flan and mousse could be problems if they
can\'t handle lactose.  Non-dairy ice cream? easy to eat
(slurrp!).  Apple pie (our dogs always tried to steal some
of mom\'s apple pie): maybe with a fork.

Wine with dinner?  Better have it in goblets.  Coffee 
after?  Vargr probably can deal with hot liquids as well as 
we can.  Brandy in a snifter?  "Snriftrers mrust\'ve breen 
invrented by Vrargr -- threy frocus the rexperience rin 
thra nrose.  Mmmmrrmrm."

Then how about a nightcap and dancing at one of the clubs
floating over the San Francisco Bay?  It\'s still only 1
meter deep in places after thousands of years of dumping
stuff into it, but it\'s being dredged out?  Vengue has
had a few drinks by now, so he might very well roll down
the window and enjoy the smells of a big city at night --
this could lead to a severe allergic reaction if the wrong
plants are in bloom.  Cab drivers have seen it all, so no
rude comments will be made.

Even after several more nightcaps, however, the Gvaekeuerrs 
won\'t be drinking from the facilities.  In fact, as your 
partner learns at the firm\'s New Year party, the Vargr 
ability to throw up easily and return to the table feeling 
none the worse for wear makes the new colleague a 
formidable adversary at drinking contests.

