> fusion bombs.  Current H-bombs use a small A-bomb as a trigger to get
> the fusion reaction going.  The A-bomb trigger makes it "dirty" with
> lots of radioactive debris and heavy isotopes lying around.  A "clean"
> H-bomb would use a laser to start the reaction, and with gravitic
> technology to contain the reaction long enough, you get an H-bomb with
> no heavy isotopes to clean up.  One side effect of this method of
> H-bombing is that nearly all of the radiation emitted will be hard gamma
> rays - very lethal, but very short-lived.

True, leaving out the fission bomb saves you from creating fission-byproducts
which are usually very "dirty", but a fusion reaction creates *lots* of fast
Neutrons as well as Gamma rays (rememebr the proposed Neutron Bomb...). Like
the
GR, these too are lethal but short lived, though stopped more easily than GR
--
but unlike GR, they can transform other nucleii when they collide, leaving
radioactive elements to decay later.

In addition, some of the fusion products may be unstable and decay after the
explosion...
