    'index' => 'ab649',
    'topic' => 'RE: self-destructing fusion plants',
    'body' => 'STEAM-CLEANING THE INSIDE OF A SHIP

I\'ve always assumed that if the power plant can output the huge number of
Watts required to tear a ship out of this space into jump space (stored in
jump capacitors or whatever) then if this energy were released in an
uncontrolled manner (and quickly) a large explosion would result. Given the
armoured nature of a ship\'s hull, the majority of the blast would initially
be concentrated within the ship, presumably vaporising most of the contents?

That\'s a pretty good way of ensuring a ship can\'t be used by the enemy. It
doesn\'t make a big explosion outside though, even if the hull ruptures. Then
again, if the danger space for a mere shipboard laser is 50m, perhaps one
could (just for the Hell of it) expand that up by comparing the laser power
with the total output power of the plant? Then say halve it to allow for the
reduction due to hull containment. This would give a very rough estimate of
a ship\'s destructive capability.

HYDROGEN + OXYGEN + LIGHTED SPLINT = POP!

A number of people have discussed the explosive capability of the power
plant itself. I haven\'t yet heard mention of the inherent lethality of
escaping hydrogen fuel being ignited. I once calculated that if the \'small\'
amount of fuel carried on a scout ship were allowed to escape such that it
expanded into hydrogen gas in a uniform density (standard atmospheric
pressure) cloud, this cloud, once ignited would create a _huge_ fireball -
sufficient to make an AD&D mage wimper and go home in the realisation that
real life can out-zap magic any day of the week!!!

WHY DO IT?

My players have mined their ship (dontya just luuuv Claymores...), but only
to the degree of providing internal kill zones against hijackers. The
relative worth of the ship means that none of them would ever dream of
blowing themselves up.

So why install such a system. Can you ever have enough fail safes? Would you
go on a ship which (in the 50th century) has such complex s/w that only the
semi-AI robots that wrote it can understand it? And one false bit
transmitted, one RF glitch... the error handler that forgets to tell you the
4-out-of-5 decision-making computers for the self-destruct have just gone
off line, leaving the notoriously unreliable number 5 in charge... hey Mr.
Virus pay _me_ a visit!

What happens when the enemy ship\'s laser gets that one lucky shot?

Sad joke: "How do you make a Vargr go woof?" "Shoot their ship\'s
self-destruct system..." <pathetic laughter>

Cmdr Lilly, PITS (Political Intelligence Team, Scout)
PITS Team motto: "We are never outgunned."
* Nothing I say or do in any way reflects the views of my very kind
  and generous employers who have no interest in outgunning anyone. *

