    'body' => 'Andy Lilly says:
>..Would you go on a ship which (in the 50th century) has such complex 
> s/w that only the semi-AI robots that wrote it can understand it?

Actually many new generation military planes are either marginally stable
or inherently unstable and I\'d rather trust of complex program on one of
them. Consider also that most programs that all of us use today are in a 
certain way so complex that we do not understand them.... In fact we use 
high level languages and some semi-AI robot = ..the compiler.. translates 
them into the "real" program. As the level of languages gets higher you 
might tell the "compiler" or whatever "blast them!". Actually the 
compiler undeestands them better than we do, detecting problems and
optimizing them better than a human could do.

My feeling is that starships computers that have to be trusted to run
the jump drive can certainly also be trusted for anything else.

Concerning Andy\'s idea of hydrogen chemical ignition, I think that we are
sadly facing again the ten years old issue of fusion power in MT: nuclear
energy should be one million times more efficient than chemical and it
is only 1000 times (give or take some factors). Any inefficient way
of blowing up your fusion reactor would likely produce much more energy
than any chemical explosion in real life, not necessarily so in Traveller..


                                 Max

P.S. chemical ignition of H also requires O, few scoutships carry
around hundred tons of oxygen...


