difference. One wants computers to do more and more difficult things.
If you call  Prolog a language for AI applications then my optimizing
compiler is at least semi-AI. If you don\'t...you are excused...

Concerning what AI is.., my congratulations, you are the One who knows
what it really is... As you certainly know more than I do, in the last years
so many approaches have been tried (expert systems with euristics, 
neural networks, perceptrons, something else I do not know about, etc) with, 
to my view from the outside, so little success that I would not be that 
optimistic..We have a Connection Machine that is used by a dozen computer 
scientists working at their thesis every year and their end-product is 
often little more than their degree...(unfortunately for me, I was in
charge of reviewing their CPU time applications..)

Some friends (computer scientists themselves) are working on new
generations of compilers for Camel and similar functional  languages, 
with the goal to have syntactic correctness implying also semantic
correctness. May be that would not be real AI but would be quite
a step forward, well deserving the semi-AI name, and hopefully by
the 57th century...

Finally, I officially challenge you to write machine language code more
efficiently than current compilers on Risc CPUs (e.g. IBM POWER2)...
there are so many criteria involved in optimizing on such cpus that
of the many people I know who have tried none have succeeded. Of course 
you can understand what is doing and, may be, even guess why some 
instruction sequence  gets executed in one machine cycle and some other 
not (if you know the details of the CPU..). Real compilers are pretty 
damn "smart", although, of course, if you want to optimize better than 
many (tempted to say all..) compilers on  the PC market you can do it 
standing on one leg after  four martinis .. 
I would tend to agree with you that the compiler does not anything more 
than you told him, as I sadly found out when programming the above
mentioned Connection Machine..BUT faster IS better, if the speed difference
is factors of one thousand or more.

