    'body' => '
Hi:

I want to respond to a few of the issues that were raised in this discussion.

This is long, anyone not interested in the AI discussion, should skip this.


1. What is AI? Historically, AI is the term that refers to a set of
research that started a while back to in effect create an artificial brain.

These days AI has broken up into fields which attempt to find what people
to believe to be subprocesses in this field such as:

Vision or Image Processing
Natural Language Recognition
Planning
Deduction and Reasoning
Learning

2. A compiler is semi-AI? I really don\'t know what semi-AI means. I can tell
you that compiler technology evolved out of AI research. Back in the 50\'s
when people were using punchcards and machine language to program (1\'s and
0\'s
or just numbers), compilers would have looked like AI technology because
it turned a set of instructions written in a language resembling English
into a language that could be processed by a machine.

However, since higher-level programming (with languages) is now the most
popular way to program, this technology does not appear to be AI.

This is another point about AI. AI has also come to characterize any
sufficiently advanced technology which appears to be taking human intent and
 converting into something that can be processed by a CPU.

3. The computer is only as good as the programs that run on it: This is
true to a certain point. Any program that can be written for a particular
CPU can with sufficiently advanced technology be turned into a chip to
be installed on that computer. That means that if someone managed to come
up with a way for a program to learn, interact with its environment,
and hypothesize new information, then this would be a good example of an AI.
Given a sufficiently advanced technology, this AI could be turned into a chip
or even a CPU itself. So then maybe some company comes up with this chip
and markets it. Each AI can then take on a different "personality" given
a different environment.

The problem is that creating this software is a very difficult thing. Lets
take for example, the brain of a mouse.   This brain has to do the following:
* Manage sensors (nerves)
* Control glands and muscles
* Manage nesting instincts
* React to fear, hunger, pain
* Adapt to new situations and environments
The mouse brain has to do each of these in parallel and in real-time.

AI software today is nowhere near the above model. In addition, any
canonical AI type of operation takes many resources to complete.

Now given 3000 years, things may change. There might even be a new invention
which makes things alot easier.


Matthew S. Harelick		aka msh9848@hertz.njit.edu
My opinions do not reflect the opinions or policies of IBM.
http://hertz.njit.edu/~msh9848
