    'body' => 'Andy Lilly says that he has always allowed jump from anywhere to anywhere.
I actually have always done the same and I think IT IS canon. I have seen 
many times in the rule the idea of jumping in open space both in CT (last 
one was on TCS [thanks Niko!]) and in MT (e.g. the Riftbreaker scoutship).

David J. Golden does not like the hundred diameter rule. I think the rule 
has two advatanges : 1- it is simple, 2- it makes physically sense.
In fact, due to the equivalence principle, it should not make any 
difference whether you are in a gravity well or accelerating the other way. 
If one introduces a rule saying that one cannot jump if the gravitational 
acceleration at the jump point is larger than some threshold than he 
should also require the ship not to accelerate faster than the same 
threshold for consistency. As I argued some time ago, the 100 diameters
rule when seen as a schematization of the tidal forces strength it 
actually makes a lot of sense (as long as all bodies can be approximated
as having the same density). The tidal force limit would change by 90 
per cent in terms of diameters when going from the Earth (as dense 
as you get for known planets) to Jupiter. Thus 100 diameters for 
Earthlike planets would be too conservative by a factor two for gas 
giants. 

The reason I like the tidal force constraint is that by  redefining your 
reference frame you  can always cancel the effect of any  gravitational 
acceleration but you cannot cancel out the tidal forces.

Note that some of these arguments are more general than general relativity
ie could be correct even if general relativity was wrong.

