    'body' => 'Dear Folks -

Re: LIMITERS ON JUMP

To those who asked about the "canon" of jumping to a particular
gravity well, I may have been the one who raised it (?!). It
was an idea - a *suggestion*, not "canon" - raised by Leroy
Guatney in "From Port To Jump-point", JTAS #23 (??). The
full details are in one of my an earlier postings.

In xboat #363, Mark Seemann wrote:

>Actually, according to the SOM, a body emerging from
>jump space will *automatically* emerge at least 100
>diameters from any mass. That means that you can\'t do a
>dangerous jump *to* a point inside the 100 diameter sphere
>of an object. You can, however, make dangerous jumps
>by jumping *from* such a point.

The ruling I remember is that a jump to a point inside a 100
diameter limit will *AUTOMATICALLY* "precipitate" the ship
out of j-spaces and back into n-space. My memory says that
this included "disasterous results" - probably akin to
the ship running into a brick wall.

I do remember the ruling that a ship has its own 100-diameter
limit 9just not the source). There was another, similar case
where one ship was tethered to another and misjumped when its
drive was activated (catastrophically). I *think* this was in
MT Journal #4, in the TAS news reports ??

As for the 100-diameter rule itself, I would say that the
"reason" for it is a GAME reason: any running from space
combat to a jump-point is meant to be a dangerous nail-biting
experience for PC\'s - or should allow the PC\'s to chase down
an ememy.

BATTLE TENDERS

In Xboat #363, Fred Kiesche asked:

>Has anybody ever used the "battle tender" portion of a battle rider combo to
>other uses?

Yes. _Supplement 9: Fighting Ships_ stated that a buffered planetoid was
shipped to Mora (or was that _from_ Mora?) via one of the Navy\'s million-ton
battle tenders. The planetoid was a non-jump monitor, and the transfer took
place during "fleet exercises". It was shipped in place of one of the normal
battle riders.

Also in Supp 9 was a "jump ship", which carried gear (_any_ gear) in a sling
behind it. The sling was used to extend the jump field. The ship started as
a j-6 ship, which was reduced for every 1000-tons diplacement that was
added as cargo (max 6000-tons, j-1). Nothing in the description disallowed
smaller ships to be carried in this manner!

- Hyphen
  (David Jaques-Watson)

