    'topic' => ' Jump Diameters (XBd#365)',
    'body' => 'goldendj@csn.net (David J. Golden) wrote:
> [Jump-drive gravity gradient explanation]
> 
> I like this explanation. But I just thought of something ...
> 
> Another corollary is that it becomes possible to jump from the surface of a
> planet ... use an artificial gravity generator to smooth the gravity field
> gradient in a localised area ... say, mount it in the roof of a cavern
> pointing "down." Set up properly, you can reduce the gravity gradient below
> where it would be at 100 diameters, and jump is perfectly safe.

That depends, I suppose, on whether or not you want to allow this in your
game.  There\'s "pro" and "con" arguments both ways.  On the "pro" side, it
allows some really nifty tricks (jumping from the surface of a planet,
for example, could be a clever escape route for a villian).  On the "con"
side, there would have to be some reasonable explanation why it\'s not used
regularly - it would be worth a _lot_ to be able to avoid the travel-time
out to 100 diameters, particularly on worlds that orbit close-in to a very
large star.

If you DON\'T want to allow it, here\'s a suggestion:

Postulate that grav technology has some property that\'s incompatible with
using the jump drive.  One possibility would be to assume that a grav field
isn\'t constant, but instead varies some significant amount (even a small
percent) at a frequency that is fast enough that it doesn\'t matter for most
normal uses of grav fields (*).  The variation is too great to allow a
ship to safely jump, or the best that can be done is to allow the equivalent
of a "desparate jump".

(*) This could be invoked to explain why grav vehicles "hum" or "whine", and
    why starships "rumble" or "whoosh" as they fly.  Vibrations in the
    air or ship\'s structure, induced by the grav field, are just at the 
    threshold of audio perception.  These barely-perceptable sounds vary
    with the type of grav generator and the load.

If you want to make it POSSIBLE but VERY DIFFICULT:

Assuming that artificial-gravity-flattened space is suitable for jumping,
it makes a lot of sens to make sure that the technique isn\'t economically
feasable and/or isn\'t very safe.  That would explain why it isn\'t in use
in the Imperium, but would allow for it\'s use in special circumstances.
The following items need to be addressed by any such facility:

- The jump envelope for a ship extends above the ship\'s hull, somewhere
  between a few centimeters and a meter, depending on the ship and the
  drive.  The ship\'s landing gear will have to be retracted, and the ship
  flying (floating) free in the chamber when the jump drive is activated.
  If this precaution isn\'t taken, the jump field will try to bring along
  a chunk of whatever the ship is touching, and will also raise the
  probability of misjump to the equivalent of a Desparate jump.

- The jump drive releases a large amount of energy into space (as visible
  light, infrared radiation, and probably stronger stuff, too - enough to 
  be clearly visible to an observer several kilometers away).  The
  facility will have to be designed to take this sort of abuse.  Treat
  the discharge as a large explosive device (the equivalent of several
  tons of explosive) detonated at the point where the ship exits.

- It\'s reasonable to assume that the ship\'s jump drive has local space
  warping effects larger than the ship itself (the rift into jumpspace
  through which the ship passes has to be large enough to give a safety
  margin, and it\'s reasonable to assume that there are strong effects
  many times larger than the rift itself).  A reasonable assumption for
  these sort of effects would be a radius of 100 times the largest
  dimension of the ship.  This whole area would have to be in null-g, so
  the null-g zone would have to be a sphere many kilometers in diameter.
  An area only 10 times the largest dimension of the ship would be the
  equivalent of a Desparate jump, and smaller areas would be the equivalent
  of jumping from within 10 diameters (suicidal).

- Jump drives normally operate in the vacuum of space, so that there is
  no nearby matter to interfere.  Even an atmosphere in contact with
  the ship\'s hull would be enough to distort the jump field, so the
  null-g zone would also have to be pumped down to a hard vacuum.  Jumping
  from a non-vacuum would raise the probability of a misjump to that of
  a Desparate jump.


If you want to make it POSSIBLE and EASY:

Not recommended - if this trick could be done safely and reliably at
Imperial tech levels, it would have been done.  Instead, make it either
a high-tech item that\'s beyond normal Imperial grasp, or some variant
universe (this would be the functional equivalent of some type of
stargate).

Implement some type of stargate technology.  This way, the grav eqipment
and the jump drive itself are built into the fixed base.  The ship has
to have a small protective field generator (call it a J-0.5 drive), but
can omit the jump drive fuel, and the larger drive.  This makes star
travel cheaper and more efficient, as well as piracy very unlikely.


