    'body' => '
"Any sentient lifeform within Imperial borders, regardless of its origin, 
is a protected being, and thus a citizen of the Third Imperium."
                                   - Cleon, 17

Now, the above, found in the World Builders Handbook, is a whopper of an 
idea: if taken at face value, it seems to mean that anyone within 
Imperial borders is automatically an Imperial!

Yipes!  

Actually, I think that it\'s actually a workable concept, but I have no 
idea how to do it.  What about those who have no alliegence to the 
Imperium, but just happen to be within it\'s borders?  Is there any such 
thing as dual citizenship?

And, umm, what exactly are the rights of a citizen of the Third 
Imperium?  If I remember correctly, the Imperium is actually a massive 
trade federation of politically independent worlds: the Imperial 
Government actually controls the space between the stars, not the worlds 
themselves.

In this view, the government, nobility and Navy should strictly concern 
themselves with keeping the trade lanes open, protecting the rights of 
traders and perhaps encouraging economic development.  I can see how a 
set of rights would be drawn up for merchants, and to people on government 
business. But why did the Imperium - from it\'s very beginning - grant 
rights to everyone within the Imperium?  

I mean, yes it\'s generous, but it\'s a massive increase in workload!  
Moreover, there\'s a vast number of political, philosophical and religious 
philosophies within the Imperium: how do the basic Imperial rights of any 
citizen (say, at a guess, the right to a fair trial) interact with a 
lawless world?  Or a totalitarian dictatorship?  Or even your standard, 
vanilla-flavoured Impersonal Bureaucracy?

Idea: the Imperium isn\'t the miminalist government I always 
thought of it.  Well then, what is it for besides trade and shared 
security?

**************

And how do these rights interact with other interstellar governments, 
ie. 
     The Zhodani Consulate 
Does the local Zho ambassator have the right to be 
psionic?  And surely he isn\'t an Imperial citizen, simply because he 
crossed the Border?
     The Solomani Confederation 
(which doesn\'t offically exist!)
     The Hierate 
(which does, but is not as important as the 29 clans), 
     The Hive Federation 
(how does Imperial law handle the right to manipulate?)
     The Two Thousand worlds 
(how does the local embassy deal with Imperial citizens who happen to be 
carnivores?  Get the centaurs to expell him, rather than kill him?)
     Imperial Client States
(What exactly can an Imperial Citizen do in a Client state that he can\'t 
do in a non-aligned world?)


----
Alvin Plummer
"Preserve what we created, Norris, and remember what we stood for."
                               - Strephon, 179-1126

Reply to: alvin.plummer@SHERIDANC.ON.CA

----

