    'body' => 'Alvin starts:
>"Any sentient lifeform within Imperial borders, regardless of
>its origin,  is a protected being, and thus a citizen of the
>Third Imperium."
>                                   - Cleon, 17
>Now, the above, found in the World Builders Handbook, is a whopper
>of an idea: if taken at face value, it seems to mean that anyone
>within Imperial borders is automatically an Imperial!

I think the motive behind the declaration is the answer to
your question:
>And, umm, what exactly are the rights of a citizen of the Third 
>Imperium?
"to pay taxes."

>What about those who have no alliegence to the 
>Imperium, but just happen to be within it\'s borders?
If a planet officially doesn\'t have alliegence then
it isn\'t "within imperial borders". It may be completely
surrounded by the Imperium but that part of space isn\'t
part of it. You should see a low level plot of the
border between Ireland and Northern Ireland. It goes
in and out and around particular farms. I think it is
based along the parish lines, which are not necessarily
continuous or complete (in the topological sense).

>But why did the Imperium - from it\'s very beginning - grant 
>rights to everyone within the Imperium?
  For their tax money. It makes sense. If they are within
their borders then they are gaining the benefit of their
patrolling the "space between the stars." They should have
the "right" to support it.

>(What exactly can an Imperial Citizen do in a Client state that
>he can\'t do in a non-aligned world?)
  Pay tax. :-)


