6/9-95 Alvin Plummer spake:

>And, umm, what exactly are the rights of a citizen of the
>Third Imperium?

Well, there may not be many rights, but there sure are
some! Right now, I can think of one. Remember what you
cited Cleon for stating in 17:

>"Any sentient lifeform within Imperial borders, regardless
>of its origin, is a protected being, and thus a citizen of the
>Third Imperium."

The key word here is \'protected\'. It seems like I read
somewhere that "killing a sentient lifeform without
provocation is murder, and thus illegal" or something along
those lines (maybe it was in an article called something
like "The Problems of being Artificial" in TD #12(?)).

The way I read this, murder is illegal, in it is always illegal,
no matter where you are, as long as you are inside the
borders of the Imperium (or in jumpspace between two
imperial worlds). I think I read somewhere once, that
Imperial law defined a minimum set of rules, which applies
if nothing else does. Thus, murder is still illegal on a world
with government code 0. On the other hand, in reality it will
be hard to enforce on such a world, because there is no
set of rules defining what "provocation" is.

>Does the local Zho ambassator have the right to be
>psionic?

This is an interesting question. As all ambassadors, he
must have diplomatic immunity. What else are the imperials
going to say? "You, sir, are a psionic. We cannot tolerate
that!" Ssccwwooaarr!! <sound of fusion gun fire>

So I guess that psionic ambassadors are accepted. But
remember that a Zho embassy is NOT imperial territory,
and thus, the Zho ambassador can practise all the
psionics he/she wants, as long as their effects doesn\'t
spread outside of the embassy. I would guess that a Zho
ambassador using psionics outside the embassy would
be frowned upon. Repeated offences could even get him/
her expelled.

But as long as he/she is in imperial territory, he/she is a
protected being, and by THAT definition a citizen of the
Imperium.

Btw, isn\'t there an imperial law stating that it is illegal to use
pionics? Such a law would be a good candidate for the
minimum set of rules always applying anywhere in the
Imperium.
#012#
Oh, and more btw, (in response to an idea by Jo Grant)
paying taxes is not a right, it\'s a duty :-)

Mark Seemann
