    'from' => 'Hans Rancke-Madsen rancke@diku.dk',
    'body' => 'Glen Goffin writes:
>LIC business organizations are (1) substantially involved in interstellar 
>commerce; (2) very large (there is probably a BCr or TCr number, but I 
>don\'t know what it is); (3) publicly held (at least partly).  LIC 
>corporations must report annually to the Imperial government.  At least 
>three Ministries receive reports:  the Ministry of Taxation (of course); 
>the Ministry of Finance (which oversees disclosure under the Imperial 
>securities laws, which only apply to the publicly traded securities of 
>LIC businesses); and whatever Ministry or Ministries govern the primary 
>businesses of the company.  For example, Tukera Lines, LIC, reports to 
>the Ministry of Transportation as well as Taxation and Finance.

Once, while paging through the list of Megacorporations, I noticed that the
Imperial Family owned at least two percent (often more) of all but one of 
them. Checking the information of the few other LIC corporations we\'ve
had library data on (Oberlindes Lines and a few others) showed that there, 
too, the Imperial family owned at least two percent. I therefor decided
that in my universe the price of a LI Charter was to assign an unsellable
2% of the company to the Emperor. It\'s IMO a nice, simple way to finance
the Imperium (or perhaps just the Imperial Household; I never tried to
calculate how much money would be involved, but 2% of every LIC company in 
the Imperium should come to a tidy bit, shouldn\'t it?), and it seemed 
perfectly in accord with the commercial origin of the Imperium.

There remained that one pesky Megacorporation that didn\'t have any shares
owned by the Imperial Family (I forget which one it was), but I liked the
idea so much that I decided that it must have been a misprint.

Btw. by "financing the Imperium" I do not include the Imperial Navy. That,
according to _TCS_ and _Striker_, is financed by assessing each member
world a per capita tax. 


