    'month' => '09',
    'index' => 'ab777',
    'body' => 'Stewart Eyres commented on the slowness of p-p fusion. Actually I believe
that a reaction is neither fast or slow, it all depends on the physical     
conditions one is interested in. Take the sun as an example, given the 
abundances of deuterium and tritium and of CNO elements and the temperature
and density in the sun core p-p ends up being the dominant reaction. As the
temperature changes 9e.g. going to more massive stars) CNO reactions may be
more convenient. The fact that a proton in the sun can live a happy life
for a billion years without having to fuse is just because the sun is
roughly at the Gamow peak and protons need to be very unlucky to pass by
tunneling the coulomb barrier. A manmade thermonuclear plasma would almost
certainly be at higher temperatures than the sun to beat the coulomb barrier
without the need of quantum effects. The big difference is that the sun
is in equilibrium while we actually do not want a reactor to be in 
self-sustained equibrium. It is a nice feature to have the reactor turn off
once
something happens...
 
Summarizing the whole trick depends on the nuclear cross-sections for the
various reactions (which have a different dependence on temperature) and
on the heat losses from the plasma. I once asked to a plasma physicist  
(he was director of the theory group at the JET near Oxford) why nobody
is considering CNO fusion given that high temperatures are easier to
achieve than high densities and he gave me a long and complete explanation
that I have essentially forgotten but was based on this kind of arguments.
 
      Cheers,
 
         MAx
