    'topic' => 'Fusion, Imperial wealth, etc.',
    'body' => '
Hi 
,
	first, the post about p-p fusion being slow is a very valid point.
The reason for it is the 
very low reaction rate in the step where you 
convert a proton into a neutron - i.e. p+p => D + gunk.. This i s done
using the weak nuclear force , which as the name implies , is weak. THis
means that the total cross-section for the reaction above is small - i..e
a very small probability of reaction. which e means that you have to 
collide a LOT of protons to get a decent number of intereactions. It is 
improbable that you could create high enough densities for this to occusr. 
(my delete key isn\'t working right, so please forgive the typos.) 
But y\'all are forgeting one thing - at TL-15 you can control the strong 
as well as the weak nuclear force. (Ok, Ok, that\'s what they say - don\'t
ak me to do the math on it. ) If you could mess with the reaction t rate ,
perhaps p-p fusion would become viable. You could say that at TL-15 they
only know how to do a few things like that , not total control over the
forces at will, which would be messy game-wise. (transmutation of anything,
inckluding lanthanum, and enemies) So, the way I explain it to my players 
is that a TL-15 p-p (actually TL-14, TL-15 does Triple-alpha fusion a s well,
producing _carbon_ , i.e. soot, as exhaust) power plant has a fiedl of 
some kind that speeds up that single crucial step in the chain reaction. note

that it is affecting the WEAK nuclear force here, so it won\'t change 
rates of other kinds of fusion. 
CNO fusion I leave for TL-16 since it requires high temperatures, and 
not much else. 

Interesting point - once you get to triple-alpha fusion (fusing three 
He into carbon) you can start to make some useful elements as a by-product.
Mg, C, N,O, S, and BE are the most probable - which means that your 
starship is a source of raw materials that are sometimes valuable .
How about diamonds for exhaust? It\'s carbon after all... I\'ll be you 
that some worlds don\'t mine their rwa materials, they produce them while
making power at the same time - if you can control certain interaction
rates you could start making _a lot_ of materials. the exact reaction 
trees are beyond me, but they r known pretty well even today..

Now for the Imperial economy ; what is the Gross Imperial Product / capita ?
That , and how it is distributed are important questions.
I am sceptical of these numbers concerning the imperium - they work out
to enormous amounts of money. my players don\'t handle that kind of cash, 
and if anyone in the imperium did, it would be VERY noticeable. 
If the imperium was that stupendiously rich - why on earth are there worlds
that are stuck at TL-8? That by the way is a question I STILL have ty to 
hear a convincing explaination of. Cultural reasons? sure, on a few planets.
but I find it very improbable that there would be so many living in what
comparesd to TL-15 is the Stone Ages. Literally. 7 tech levels....
if someone had the odd 100 trillion credits to invest - don\'t you think a
few of them would invest it in bringing "primitive savages" out of their 
misery? 
The imperium was very rich - but these numbers are too big.

cheers,
/ben
