    'body' => 'How does one damage a jump grid? 

Is it part of hull damage or part of jump drive damage? 

> From: mhclark@iastate.edu
> To: xboat@MPGN.COM
> Subject: Jump Drive Failure
> Message-ID: <9510072124.AA09423@las2.iastate.edu>
> 
> > Diavid Summers didst query:
> > >I\'m looking for an official or semiofficial answer to the following...
> > >You are in jump space and your jump drive shuts down cold (suppose
> > >someone just disconnects the power supply).  What happens?  Do
> > >you immediate emerge from jump space (now that you are being "held"
> > >in it) at some random location?  Or do you not get out until the
> > >drive is fixed (since you can\'t "push" you way out.)  Or do
> > >you just come out some random time later in some random
> > >location.  (Or do you just all die? :-)
> > 
> > Based upon DGP\'s Starship Operator\'s Manual: Nothing happens. It\'s shut
> > down almost immediately after transition. Once you\'re in jump, only
damage
> > to the lanthanum hull grid (which is used to create the jump bubble)
> > remains at a charged quantum state, and decays after about a week.
> > 
> > If you damage the grid, you could be exposed to the nature of jump space,
> > which tends to drive sapient carbon based life forms insane.
> 
>   Based on other canonical sources, the impact is illness rather than 
> insanity - jumpsickness is almost always fatal.  Note that uptures in the 
> jump grid can allow jumpspace to intrude into the ship, sucking folks out 
