    'body' => 'Dear Folks -

1.      DROYNE LEADERSHIP

In Xboat 400, David P. Summers asked:
>A question about the Droyne and the workings of the caste system.  A Droyne
>of another caste will obey the orders of the leader caste without question.
>What if the leader comes from another Oytrip?

The general rule is this: within an oytrip (community), the leaders will be
obeyed. Across oytrip boundaries, however, things differ.

"On an internal level, the bonds of caste are such that all the leaders work
together for the common good. But such co-operation rarely extends from one
oytrip to another, for their leaders are unable to recognise the concept of
themselves answering to one another. The oytrip\'s needs come first; if a
resource is in short supply, a leader will do what it can to secure that
resource for its people". (_Droyne_, p 9).

This idea seems to be based on the primary motivation of the Protectors (from
Larry Niven\'s various Known Space texts). The difference is that they only
fight when they have to, and they do not conduct pre-emptive strikes.

In order to overcome this leader inflexibility (and incapacity for
negotiation), the Sport sub-caste of Speaker was developed. They "emerged as
a corps of professional diplomats. Sports could present their oytrip\'s needs
to their opposite numbers, who in turn could use the normal processes of
appeal to convey those needs upward to the leadership". (_Droyne_, pp 9-10).

The rule seems to be that a leader from outside the oytrip would NOT
be obeyed by any member of the oytrip. However, a Speaker-Sport could make
an Appeal to the oytrip member. Now, the Droyne were never updated to MT,
but resolution of the Appeal would have to be an interpersonal task -
probably
in a similar fashion to the use of Liaison skill, but at a higher Difficulty
level. The Appeal skill is shown below:

"Appeal: the ability to address persons within the Droyne caste system with
requests or suggestions, and to attempt to have them implemented.
Given the fact that there is a rigid caste system for the Droyne, there must
be some provision for inter-caste communication. Appeal is that provision.
Generally, Appeal allows the individual to present a cast to a leader or
caste superior and to be listened to. The request is taken on its merits,
with some DM based on skill for reactions and receptiveness". (_Droyne_, p
20).

The only Droyne who can receive Appeal skill from character generation are
Drones, Sports and Leaders.

Under the Reactions table, the rules are:
"Within a caste, Liaison works on inferiors# and Appeal works on superiors.
Between castes, Liaison works on all but Leaders; Appeal works with Leaders".
(_Droyne_, p 36). #A sub-note adds "and equals" to the Liaison list.

I would tend to make tasks by krinaytsyuni ("the deathless" - Droyne who are
outside of an oytrip, eg. most Droyne PC\'s) one level more difficult. This
is based on:
- the scorn placed on these individuals by Droyne who live in oytrips (SEE
  _Droyne_, p 9);
- the fact that krinaytsyuni are included on the "Out-Community Reactions
  Table" (_Droyne, p 39);
- that when the rules talk about a contact who is "Permanently loyal", they
  say the "_even_ a krinaytsyuni can Appeal to such a friend with some hope
  of response" (_Droyne, p 39), ie. they are lowest on the list.

Also note that many negative reaction results can be submitted to a
prediction
by the coyns. "A new reaction roll is made (with all standard DM\'s) plus any
modifiers resulting from the coyns." (_Droyne_, p 36).

..by the way, also note that the rules state that a failed Appeal against
one of your own leaders means that you must undergo krinaytsu!! "Lets...be
careful out there".

Acknowledgments:
_Traveller Alien Module 5: Droyne_, J. Andrew Keith, Marc Miller, and John
Harshman, GDW, USA, 1985.

Sorry for the length of the reply, but nothing has been said about the
poor old Droyne for 10 years, so people may well be unaware of these old
rules.

..and yes, I do have one in my campaign. Do you know how difficult it is to
control a level-15 psionic?? And TNE doesn\'t even attempt to nobble them!

2.	RULE OF MAN COINS

As an aside, the coins originally came from an Amber Zone called "Rule of Man
Commemorative", JTAS#9. They are fakes (or at least, good forgeries!).

- Hyphen
(David Jaques-Watson)

