    'date' => '20 Oct 95 14:34:30 MS',
    'body' => 'A few years back a ran a very mercantile and plotical campaign, with the PCs 
acting as corporate and government leaders in the Glisten region.  In support

of this, I came up with a set of rules for naming and registering ships.  All

ships reagrdless of size or jump capability need to be registered with an 
Imperial member world to be considered an Imperial-registered ship.  Such
ships 
would have Imperial-mandated taxes and safety standards, which were to be 
enforced by the registering world.  In addition, ships with a Jump Drive
would 
need a separate certification of that drive.  This could be done at any 
Imperial Naval or Scout facility, but was actually managed by the Imperial 
Ministry of Trade.  Imperial ships without a current Jump certification could

be impounded by Imperial authorities.  Of course, the ship owners benefitted 
from this because the Imperial registration would naturally mean Imperial 
protection.

The naming convention I used was

INS  Imperial Naval Ship
INV  Imperial Naval Vessel
ISS  Imperial Scout Ship
ISV  Imperial Scout Vessel
IGS Imperial Government Ship
IGV Imperial Government Vessel
ICS Imperial Civilian Ship
ICV Imperial Civilian Vessel

The distinction between Ships and Vessels would be the presence of a Jump 
Drive; Ship\'s got them, Vessels do not.

For Civilian vessels, I also included a three-character designation in the 
registration number that would define the type of ship.  For example. the ICS

Alaric, MTH232301, was a Merchant Transport (Heavy).  Imperial ships do not
get 
this for security reasons.  Also, civilian ships that are armed with
offensive 
weapons (basically, anything but sandcasters, meson screens and nuclear 
dampers) receive an "A\' at the end of their registry number.


Steven Charlton
scharlto@avalon.com
scharlto@rtd.com
