    'topic' => ' Space combat questions.',
    'index' => 'ab862',
    'month' => '10',
    'body' => 'Hi Rodge.  I too have spent a lot of time developing space combat 
systems.  Here are some of my major observations:
(Answers to your question, or at least attempts at them, are below.)

1. Don\'t try to shoe-horn large High Guard designs into a system, pick a 
scale (say, ships under 2000 tons) and stick with it.  Every time I try 
to create an "any size ship" space combat system, it ends up being 
unrealistic or unplayable for one end of the spectrum or the other.

2. Use a hex map and a vector system.  It\'s quite easy and fast to play.  
I\'ve developed such a system, inspired in part by Brilliant Lances.  If you 
want, I\'ll send you details.

3. The hardest part is usually the hitting and damage systems.  These are 
hard to make both realistic and fast-playing.

Having said that, here are some answers to your questions.  (Boy, that\'s 
a lot of "food for thought", I think I\'m geting cerebral indigestion)  Be 
warned, these are based on my own peculiar vision of space combat and may 
not mesh with other people\'s views, but this is the only realistic view I 
can think of.

> What is the range of sensors, such as the sensors aboard naval 
>battleships?

Book 2 says that ships can be detected to a range of several 
scale meters.  Each cm is 1000 kms, so we\'re talking on the order of 
light seconds.  I\'ve usually put it at about 500 000 km for civilian 
ships with scout and navy vessels doubling to quadrupling that.  

> What are the ranges of starship weapons?

If you can detect it, you can target it.  Missiles have no inherent range 
limitations, and lasers should be able to reach out to the several light 
second range.

> What kind of defense is there against ships jumping in to a system
> and firing immediately?

Nothing, except that they will be pulverized by ground-based defences
shortly thereafter.  Ships jumping in have a very high signature which
appears before they fully emerge from jump space, so defences can lock on
completely (no chance of missing, with modern computer tech and a stable,
"loud" target) and completely melt the invaders. Even a poor planet can
afford to sink a few BIG meson guns into the ground to mash invading
forces.  And that\'s not mentioning automated satellite defences and such. 
There was a very good article on planetary invasions in one of the JTAS
issues, though I can\'t rem which one.  Of course, primitive planets are 
easily taken if they don\'t have any such defences installed by other forces.

> Since light travels relatively slow, planet-bound targets won\'t 
> detect the enemy until enemy fire has already reached them (since
> energy blasts also travel at the speed of light).  


True, except for missiles of course.  But like I said above, most 
planetary defenses can be sunk a mile or two into the ground (think 
Cheyenne) with multiple outlets all over the planet.  Unless you totally 
pulverize the whole place in one shot, you\'re likely to get mauled right 
after the first wave.

> What\'s to prevent a battleship from jumping-in to a system and
> immediately firing its weapons at premapped planetary targets?

Targets cannot be premapped, as you won\'t know your exact position on
emergence (jump only gets you in the general vicinity of the planet, it
cannot give you a pinpoint location. 

> If they fire from far away, it could conceivably take 10 or more 
> minutes for the blasts to reach the planet.  By the time the planet
> fires back, the attacking ships could easily jump back out of system,
> or change vectors.

At those kind of ranges, lasers lose focus and won\'t do any damage.  For
example, the best lasers we have today become pencil-sized, harmless beams
of light by the time they reach the moon.  Missiles can be tracked from
far away and be destroyed by defensive forces. 

> How do you lock-on to a target that is 10 light-seconds away, that
> is continously changing vectors?
> How do you hit such a target?

	Once you\'ve detected the ship\'s position, it has already moved for
ten seconds (i.e. it has taken the light or whatever from the ship 10
seconds to reach your sensors).  If you fire back immediately, there\'s
another 10 seconds before your shot reaches him.  In those 20 seconds, a
ship at 1G can adjust its vector by 2000 m, effectively giving you a
"bubble" 2 km in radius in which your target could be.  
	What you then do is fire multiple shots through that area hoping
to hit him with one of them.  The way I picture it, during a 1000 second
turn, you fire several hundred shots and maybe only get one hit.  It\'s a
procedure something like artillery.  You try to create "beaten zones"
which will catch the enemy.  Of course, you can try to increase your
chances by anticipating his movements.  For instance, a ship running from
you will not likely decelerate, so that reduces your "bubble" by half. 
Also, remember that missiles just close and then hit, they don\'t have the
"delayed signal problem". 
	For the people in the target ship, the effect is something like 
being in a B-52 bomber under AA fire.  Lots of explosions are going on 
around you, but not much of it hits you.   

> What about the nuclear variety?

The way I picture missiles is that they are trying to get in close enough
that their blast radius will intersect with the enemy, but they can\'t get
in too close or they become easy pickings for the ship\'s beam weapons, ECM
and so on.  So what you do is similar to the above, you fire several
missiles (say 5 to 10 in one round) and they home in to form a pattern of
overlapping blast radii that the enery hopefully "flies into".  Either
that, or they carry one-shot beam weapons (e.g. X-ray lasers), that they
fire when they get close enough for a good shot.  Nuclear weapons simply
have larger blast radii and thus cause more damage when at the same
distance as HE missiles.

> What happens when such a missile goes off high in a planet\'s
> atmosphere?

A nuke?  Well, lots of people get irradiated and die.  It also blocks out 
sensors (overload) for a time.

> What sort of nukes are available by TL15?

I would not think it unlikely that they would have anti-matter bombs by 
then.  Even if antimatter doesn\'t appear as a power source until TL-17 
(?), TL-15 societies should still be able to produce anti-matter in large 
amounts for military use.  It\'s kind of like the way we have fusion bombs 
but no fusion power.  An antimatter bomb would have similar effects to a 
nuke, only bigger and badder.  I think 1 gigaton bombs would be available 
(though HIGHLY controlled).  In my own settings, weapons of mass 
destruction are usually banned on penalty of death.

> What is a "fusion" warhead in Traveller?

Just a big bad nuke.  The difference is that it can potentially be 
relatively "clean" (no radiation), though it need not be if the designers 
don\'t want it to be.

> Is it a form of nuke?
> If so, do Nuclear Dampers protect against it?

Yes to both, IMNSHO.

Again, let me state that these answers are just based on my view of space 
combat, and may not wash well with "official" views and so on.  Hope this 
is helpful.

Charles.

