    'body' => 'Roger Sanger wrote:

>What is the range of sensors, such as the sensors aboard naval
>battleships?
>
>What are the ranges of starship weapons?

This varies extensively from version to version of even classic
Traveller.  One version of Book 2 gave half a light-second for
civilian detectors, and two light-seconds for military and IISS
detectors.  I think that there were negative DMs for weapons fire
at long range, but I don\'t remember the details.  

High Guard didn\'t have explicit ranges, just Short and Long, but
MegaTraveller brought back the hex grid, which had four range bands;
Visual, Near, Far, and Extreme.  If Near == Short and Far == Long,
then Near is out to 25 Mm (one MT hex) and Far is out to 250 Mm
(ten MT hexes, or 0.8 light-seconds).  Sensors have their own
rated ranges, with negative DMs for range to target, as I recall.

>What\'s to prevent a battleship from jumping-in to a system and
>immediately firing its weapons at premapped planetary targets?
>
>If they fire from far away, it could conceivably take 10 or more 
>minutes for the blasts to reach the planet.  By the time the planet
>fires back, the attacking ships could easily jump back out of system,
>or change vectors.

Well, the 100-diameter limit for a big size-8 world is at only
4.3 light-seconds, and in any case, most Traveller sensors will 
have problems getting a target lock at this range, even if the
guns will reach.  The only other question is whether or not a
ship can jump in that accurately.  Many people around here say
no.  I don\'t, and use hand-waving about the effects of "large
gravitic disturbances near the exit-point" to "drag" it around 
with a planet that\'s the destination of the ship.  The reason
that I do this is to let military couriers use their pre-jump
vector to have a high speed approach toward the planet. 

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonn0015@tc.umn.edu>

