>
>How do you lock-on to a target that is 10 light-seconds away, that
>is continously changing vectors?
>
>How do you hit such a target?
>
>Food for thought,
>Hyperodge

You saturate a fire zone based upon the target\'s "potential endpoint bell",
a shape which describes their potential positions over time, accounting for
their accelleration and vector.

>What is a "fusion" warhead in Traveller?
>
>Is it a form of nuke?
>
>If so, do Nuclear Dampers protect against it?

Yes (to all). One of the bombs dropped on Japan at the end of WWII was nuke
called an H-Bomb -- it was a fusion warhead.

>I hope that someone more knowledgeable than me about the
>physics involved will describe what happens to energy at
>long ranges.  I think that ranges (effective,
>half-strength, weak, ineffective, e.g.) will be defined by
>how much the energy is weakened by spreading out.

For non-lased energy, the relationship is the inverse square law:

2x base dist gives 1/4 base energy, 3x dist gives 1/9 base energy, etc.

Lased energy (lasers, masers, etc) has significantly more range per degradation.

>Restated:  What types of sensors are effective in detecting ships in space?
>
>Hyperodge

EMS is the easiest. (EMS= Electro Magnetic Spectrum). Passive and active
designs both work, depending upon ranges. Neutrino Sensors can tell you PP
type and output, but not too good for targeting.

>I never could make heads or tails of the MT sensor rules.
>
>Range varies from distant to interstellar.
>
>At long ranges, the sensory data would be seriously outdated.
>
>What other kinds of sensors can you think of?
>
>Hyperodge

The range bands in MT are for getting data. See DGP\'s _World Builder\'s
Handbook_ for details on MT Sensor rules, and tasks. Basically, though, it
workds like shooting a weapon to get a lock-on.

-Wil

