    'body' => 'Tom Trelenberg (ex-lurker?) asks (paraphrased):

"Can you crash-land an unstreamlined ship on a world?"

Nasty stuff atmosphere - makes your ship all hot and requires streamlining
to maneouvre once you\'ve got through the outer bit and cooled down a bit.
Well, dense atmosphere will burn you up then rip you apart for definite,
since an unstreamlined ship doesn\'t have the necessary heat-shielding and
fuselage shaping to withstand the atmospheric effects. Thin or trace
atmosphere gives you a chance because the heat-up will be much less and the
aerodynamic drag should be less so you might not get ripped apart. Given the
latter option I\'d do the following (to make the players feel they\'ve earned
their survival rather than just been allowed to land because you need it for
the plot...)

1) Atmospheric entry. Determine how many surface hits to apply to the craft
- say 6. Let the pilot roll for each hit, with the first 2 being easy to
get, the next 2 more difficult and the last 2 near-impossible. Adjust for
the ship hull type, i.e. close structure is probably easier to control than
open structure. Each failed pilot roll, apply the (random) surface damage to
the ship, with an appropriate description [turret hit]:

"The craft is buffeted by the atmosphere - you think you\'ve got it made when
red lights wink up around your turret - you\'re registering a huge
temperature surge... fire klaxons sound... lights dim as a small explosion
rumbles through the ship... your external viewer shows white-hot fuselage
peeling back from the turret... cut-outs isolate the turret and the lights
return to normal, but you\'re not through it yet..."

And that was just one failed roll...

2) Atmospheric \'gliding\' (avoiding the word "plummet" here). Same principle
as 1, but this reflects the aerodynamic strain - generate 6 (say) internal
damage hits and have the pilot roll again - perhaps an engineer could roll
as well to help the pilot: "Cap\'n, she canna\' take the strain. Ye canna\'
pull her up so  fast!" For each failed roll... [hold hit]

"The world outside is a roaring blizzard of tugging, dragging atmosphere.
Hull metal screams as something is gradually wrenched from its normal
position. Scotty (engineer) checks the internal cameras and yells: \'Cap\'n,
the cargo bay doors are buckling - if ye dinna slow us down that wind\'ll
push through and rip our insides out like an exploding haggis!\'"

3) Crash landing. Anything still left of the ship? Not after this bit...
Make the players roll, but frankly they ought to have baled out (ship\'s
boat, air raft, parachute, umbrella ala Mary Poppins...) by now. Ever seen
the photos of the wreckage of a _properly_ crashed air-liner. Not much left...

