EMAIL MAGAZINE CONCEPT

As most of you have no doubt noticed, I have been putting up some
pretty big posts.  I think that this may be sort of a drag for
those of you who just want to exchange ideas and short answers to
quick question and so on (but let me know if I\'m right, wrong or 
stupid).  
So...

I have been thinking of putting together a Traveller fanzine,
perhaps to be called The Imperial Exchange (though other name
ideas are welcome).  I originally thought that it might be a web-
based hyperzine, but that would be too much work, frankly.  Also,
I thought that perhaps The Traveller Chronicle might be a better
place to put CT/MT stuff, but from what I can see, it doesn\'t really
put out a lot of stuff on Traveller Classic (still my favorite). 
Anyone want to disagree with this last point?  Lily?
 
My newest idea is to create an email magazine.  It would have
short to medium articles on various subjects, and would be put
out quarterly.  It would emphasize Classic Traveller and
MegaTraveller.  The only problem with this is that it could not
easily contain images.  It is, of course, possible to attach a
list of images to an email message, but they could not be
inserted into text, I don\'t think.  Does anyone have any
solutions to this problem?  I\'m no email expert...

I\'d really like input from a lot of people on this topic,
positive or negative.  I think the e-magazine would take some of
the bigger blobs out of the mailing list and provide a good place
to publish amateur articles for pre-collapse Traveller stuff.

If I\'m wrong about the overly-long posts, please let me know...


SENSOR INFORMATION

This is in response to Roger Sanger\'s request for sensor info. 
There is a good treatment of it in an old product for Classic
Traveller called "Grand Survey".  They discuss the following
types of sensors:  Neutrino Sensor, EMS array, Densitometer, and
Neural energy scanner.  In the very likely event that you cannot
find a copy of "GS", here\'s the basic low-down:

Neutrino Sensor:  This detects particles put out by nuclear
reactions (both fission and fusion).  There is no way to "shield"
or "hold in" neutrinoes, as they pass easily through matter and
are very long-lasting particles.  As a ship\'s plant is nuclear
based, the NS is the first thing to detect a ship in combat mode
(i.e., a ship with its plant working and its transponder off). 
However, the position given by an NS is somewhat general, no good
for aiming with.  Also, the only info one gets about the target
is energy output of the powerplant.  The NS detects ships at
distances on the order of 1 to 10 light seconds, depending on how
much energy output the powerplant has and how good a sensor it
is.  This sensor is passive only.  That is, it is no good trying
to send out pulses of neutrinoes, they only pass through the
target and don\'t return.

Electromagnetic Spectrum Array:  A group of sensors detecting
everything from radio waves to gamma rays (including light, IR,
UV, microwaves, etc.).  If a ship has its transponder on (i.e.,
is not at battle stations), then the radio detector will be the
first thing to pick up the ship, probably at a range of several
million km (way out of combat range).  This is also the group of
sensors one uses to ID and target a ship once the NS has found
it.  I generally rule that a ship\'s configuration and size can be
determined long before combat range, while positive ID of ship
type can only be made at around 5 light seconds (and there\'s
still some ambiguity, you couldn\'t tell a Scout from a Seeker
except by performance).  EMS sensors can be passive.  Passive is
less effective, but active gives away your position automatically
to anyone in the vicinity (it\'s like turning on a flashlight in a
night fight, you can see other people, but they can see you even
better).  The EMS array can also be used prior to boarding a
disabled ship in order to find where resistance is hiding (it can
detect the IR signals of the troops unless they are somehow
shielded).

Densitometer:  This is basically a super-sensitive gravitometer. 
It detects the graviton output of matter.  In space combat, it
can be used to detect a ship that is running cold (plant off) or
to detect asteroids and such.  The range is max 500 000 kms for
ships and 50 000 kms for man-sized objects.  When one gets very
close to the enemy (500 km or less), it can be used to get a
rough picture of the interior of the ship before boarding.  The
Densitometer can be used to map out the interior of any
structure, and is very useful in prospecting.  This is a passive
sensor only.

Neural Energy Scanner:  This one is a little far-fetched.  It\'s
essentially a long-range EEG machine.  It picks up the electrical
signals from the nervous systems of living things.  It can
determine the race/species of a creature  being detected.  This
has an extremely short range, on the order of .5 km, so it is not
much use in combat.  Also, it cannot pick up signals through
hulls.  I picture it as a very finicky sensor which can be
thwarted easily be randomized magnetic field generators or
electromagnetic fluctuations of various sorts, as well as psi-
shields.  This is a passive sensor only.

Typically, military and scout ships will have all these sensors,
civilian ships only the first two.  Some of the info I have given
here disagrees with GS stuff, but agrees with other published
materials.


MORE SPACE COMBAT STUFF

I mentioned an article called "Planetary Invasions in Traveller"
a little while back.  It\'s in "Challenge #25" (the JTAS part of
it, natch).  It sheds light on some of the issues raised recently
regarding "pop-in...fire...pop-out" attacks and such.  Basically,
it asserts that attacking a planet is a very difficult thing to
do.  Ground based defenses are awesome by comparison to ship
based weapons.  If you just want to harass a planet with extreme
range fire, this can be accomplished, though the idea of jumping
in, attacking successfully and jumping out again without
suffering any consequences isn\'t plausible.  
On the other hand, invading and taking a planet is much worse. 
Any ship which lands to off-load troops is a sitting duck for any
orbiting defence satellite or starship, so you have to take out
every single one first.  To get close enough to the planet to land
troops, you have to be able to take an immense pounding from
ground-based meson weapons.

Okay, that enough from me for today...


