    'ts-index' => '1995-10-25.ab902',
    'body' => 'Tom Trelenberg has asked whether unstreamlined ships can be made to land 
in an atmosphere.  Several people have replied that a ship would have big 
trouble doing so.  I\'m not so sure.  The reason for the heat on re-entry 
for present-day space craft is that they are dropping into the atmosphere 
with a rapid orbital velocity.  The rapid speed is needed to keep the 
craft from dropping straight in like a rock, and also allows lift/braking 
against the rarified atmosphere at high altitude.
But in Traveller, ships have contra-grav, so they should be able to lower 
themselves slowly into the atmosphere no matter what their shape, and 
they need not have high speed to keep them from crashing.  After 
all, if a bunch of Vacc-suited guys in an open-topped air-raft can do it, 
why can\'t a ship with contra-grav?  It would just take lots of extra time 
and maybe some medium-tough piloting rolls.

