    'month' => '10',
    'index' => 'ab913',
    'body' => 'Charles Collin <charles@hebb.psych.mcgill.ca> wrote:

>A ship which is larger WILL tend to have a larger exhaust due to its (on
>average) larger powerplant (I assume you mean heat exhaust or drive
>exhaust).  Also, if you are detecting it by its albedo (I presume you mean
>energy bouncing off the ship?), then a larger ship will give off a more
>powerful signal due to its larger profile.  For instance, if the profile 
>of a ship facing your sensor is 100 m^2 and each m^2 is putting out 1 
>unit of energy, then a larger ship with a profile of 10000 m^2 will put 
>out 100 times the absolute amount of energy.

>However, the relationship between ship volume and detection range will not
>be 1 to 1 as Roger Sanger hypothesized.  Instead it follows a square-cube
>law.  For instance, consider a cubic ship 1000 m^3 in volume.  Each side
>of it will be 10 x 10 = 100 m^2 in area.  If we now increase the ship\'s
>volume 1000 times to 1 000 000 m^3, then the sides become 100 x 100 =
>10000 m^2.  In other words, ship volume has gone up 1000 times, but its
>average profile only goes up by 100 times.  This kind of thing will tend
>to apply to the heat profiles of drives and such as well. 

Its not going to be as simple as all of that.  The albedo is influenced by 
size, but a far more important element (in terms of detection) would be 
material and finish.  A 100-meter shiny white aluminum ball is pretty easy to 
detect, while a 100 meter blackened ship made of stealth-enhancing materials 
would have a much lower albedo for detection purposes.  Also, the drive heat 
profile would be affected by tech level and overall drive efficiency; an 
inefficient or poorly-maintained power plant will generate a lot of heat, and a 
poorly-directed thrust exhaust will make a much larger sensor target.

On average, I would expect that a purpose-built military starship will probably 
have a detection albedo one-tenth the intensity of a typical civilian vessel of 
comparable size, and possibly one-hundreth the intensity of some older or 
poorly maintained ships.  For a modern example, compare the radar crosssections 
of a typical Learjet versus a non-stealth B-1 bomber.  The B-1 is probably 10 
times the size of the Learjet, but has a radar crosssection vastly smaller than 
that of the Learjet.  And then there is that WWII German transport (JU-54?) 
with the corrugated metal finish; that aircraft has a radar signature that 
makes it look larger than a big dirigible.

Steven Charlton
