    'from' => 'Charles Collin charles@hebb.psych.mcgill',
    'body' => 'Hi There.

In response to Andrew Madden (x422):

> I disagree about the poor sensor readings.

In retrospect, you may be right.  You can just move the ship around and 
triangulate readings from several widely-spaced positions, effectively 
giving you a huge array size and good resolution, even at the huge 
distances involved.  Or use sensor drones.

> If you have a asteroidal-looking ship, and move away from your emergent 
> point, then you increase your survivability, and can remain after your 
> emergence flare reaches the planet.

True, but in well-defended places, you can bet every rock above 2 tons 
displacement is mapped, catalogued and tracked.

> o   How bright is the emergence flare?

Good question.  I have always pictured it as being a fairly powerful 
burst of exotic particles.  The fact that the radiation emited is of an 
unusual type makes the flare more detectable.  

> o   Based on the emergence flare brightness and the inverse square law, 
> How likely are you to be detected?

That depends on how well-defended the place is.  For hi-pop worlds, you 
can bet the whole sky is checked every few seconds at least, if not 
constantly.

> One of the best methods of surviving the jump is to begin moving at an 
<stuff deleted>
> Best yet, assume a speed which gives a far orbit, like a comet. That way 
> you look *exactly* like something that is supposed to be there (every 
> 2755.3 years or whatever). Basically assume a stable, highly eliptical 
> solar orbit, or make like a passing rogue.  BTW I *love* the idea of the 

Great concept.
I like the second idea better due to the catalogueing thing I noted 
above.  Defenders would be more likely to accept that they had missed a 
far-orbit comet or rogue in their catalogue than an inner system asteroid.
I\'m glad you like the batteries idea.  

> batteries. As an aside, Russian Sub design use batteries on the *outside* 
> of the pressure hull. This gives a shorter life, and harder replacement, 
> but they are then effective as ARMOR. What about using the excess space 
> in an asteroid in a similar concept. Treat battery cages as rubble ( 
> hell, thats what lithium hydride _looks_ like anyway.)

Hmm, maybe, but I\'d hate to have my batteries blown off by the ship that 
caught me with my plants down (bad pun intended).  It might be better to 
put the adjacent to the powerplant or alongside the jump-drive capacitors.

> By giving the ship some spin it should be possible to deploy sensors on 
> monofilament cable, or similar, to increase the effectiveness of your 
> sensor array. (very biy, very specialised folding EMS array). The spin 
> keeps the cables taught. The small size of the pods, and their passive 
> nature would make them impossible to detect, unless you collided with it, 

Yup.  I like it!  The spin axis doesn\'t have to be right at the target if 
you don\'t want to appear obvious, though that reduces the array size.  And 
again, you could just do away with the array and triangulate small array 
measures from different positions in space as your ship moves along.

> A 6g Fighter 10 light-seconds away will move a maximum of 1/2 A * T^2. or 
> 3000m, but in terms of total flight time of the laser, that\'s 20 seconds, 
> or a sphere of 12000m.

That\'s what makes fighters so hard to hit!

> How many small (i.e. player) ships are likely to be able to fill even a 
> 3000 m radius sphere repeatedly? Thats  4,188,790,204.786 m3 in the 
> probability sphere for the 6g fighter postulated elsewhere (at a distance 
> of 10 light seconds).

First of all, 10 light seconds is at best the extreme range for combat in my 
opinion, especially for hitting a fighter.  Anyway, you forget that you 
don\'t have to fill the whole sphere, you just have to send beams through 
a circular plane perpendicular to the direction of fire (i.e., the 
profile of the sphere).  Once the beams get there, they pass through the 
sphere effectively 
instaneously, so the third dimension is "factored out".  Also, if one 
assumes the fighter has an equal likelihood of being anywhere in the 
sphere, then you can concentrate your fire mostly near the center of the 
circular area.  The reason I say this is that there is more of the 
sphere\'s volume subtended by the central areas of the circle.

Now, if you can measure the output of the ship\'s drives, then 
you can tell approximately by how much it is  changing its vector and 
thus greatly narrow down the area it might be hiding in.  If the ship 
accelerated at its full 6 G\'s, for instance, it will have to be somewhere 
on the surface 
of its "probability sphere", it cannot be in the interior of it.  You can also 
narrow down the area by common sense.  For instance, a ship running from 
you will be unlikely to use maximum deceleration as a dodgeing tactic.

Also, I think you are underestimating the firing rates of the weapons 
involved.  A single laser turret could conceivably fire several thousand 
times in a 1000 second round.  Missiles, on the other hand, don\'t have 
any of these problems, since they can close and thus reduce the signal 
lag.  

Still, this discussion points out an interesting thing:  it should get 
exponentially more difficult to hit and damage a target as distance 
increases, as the "probability bubble" grows exponentially.


