    'topic' => 'An example of Space combat...',
    'body' => 'Here\'s an example of a ship firing on another: 

Given: 

	1. A target at 3 light second\'s distance. (much more realistic, in my 
opinion, than the 10 light second figure that has been thrown around).
	2. A target profile of 200 m^2 (roughly far-trader sized).
	3. Target acceleration of up to 2 G\'s.

	When a shot reaches the enemy, it will have been moving for 6
seconds (3 seconds for signal to reach sensors, 3 seconds for the shot to
get there). 

	In 6 seconds, the target can move 10 * 6*6 meters, or 360 meters,
maximum. 

	That means that the area in which the target could be is
effectively a circle (not a sphere, for reasons I and others have noted)
with an area of about 400 000 m^2. (3.14 * 360 * 360 = 406944)

	Therefore, if one divides the "probability circle" area by the
target profile area, there are roughly 2000 "locations" the ship could be
in. (400 000 / 200 = 2000). 

	If an attacking ship can fire 1000 shots (1 a second) in a round,
then it has roughly a 50% chance to hit the target, and that\'s without
adding in the "common sense" and "gunner\'s intuition" factors.  It also
does not take into account the fact that one can improve chances of a hit
by concentrating fire on the center of the "probability circle", again for
reaons I have noted previously. 

	Now, I realize the above example isn\'t perfect.  For one thing, as
each shot is fired, the target continues moving, so one might at first
think that the "probability circle" would be continually growing as shots
were fired.  But, the sensor information is also continally being updated,
meaning the size of the sphere stays the same (though its position is
changing).  So the example is only roughly correct, but it does serve to
show that you have pretty good chances to hit assuming a high firing rate. 

