    'topic' => ' Gravitics',
    'body' => 'Charles Collins writes:

> Okay, I\'ve got a problem here which may stir up some debate:  How do grav 
> plates work?  Obviously, there can be no answer of a purely scientific 
> nature, but it\'s nice to have a fictional operating principle for 
> technobabbling purposes.  
> 
> Here\'s my major concern:  Why do grav plates not exert their forces on 
> other bodies outside the ship?  For instance, if you turn on a 1G floor 
> field, then why does it not pull on the planet below you with a force of 
> 1G?  If you\'re using a 6G field to compensate for an average fighter\'s 
> acceleration, you should throw whole solar systems into disarray!

    [...possible explanation skipped...]

> So, what do you think?

I don\'t think there\'s any canon from GDW on the subject, and I don\'t
know how others deal with it, but here\'s a re-post of the a message
I mailed to the XBoat list a few months back (in response to a question
about ships jumping from inside other ships.)

> David J. Golden <goldendj@deltanet.com> writes:
> 
> > > How large is the largest body whose gravity can be
> > >ignored in determining safe jump points? Luna-sized? Big
> > >asteroid? Small asteroid? Just right asteroid?
> > 
> > I\'d rather see the "10 Diameter/100 Diameter Rule" replaced by a
> > certain curvature of space, i.e. gravity level. I\'d simply assume
> > the 10 Diameter rule was a rule of thumb based on Earth, so the
> > first critical gravity level is 1/100 G, or 0.098m/s/s. Then 100
> > Diameters would be 1/10,000 G, or 0.00098 m/s/s.  Then it doesn\'t
> > matter what size the body is. I mean, why would the danger distance 
> > be the same for our moon, with a (surface) gravity of 1/6G, and for
> > a neutron star the same size, with a mass and hence (surface) gravity
> > _significantly_ higher?
> 
> One has to be careful about treating *artificial* gravity the same
> as gravity generated by natural forces/objects, because the Laws of
> SF Absurdity begin to rapidly take over.
> 
> Take, for example, A-G generated in deckplates aboard a starship.
> Does the effect of the gravity generated by the internal deckplates 
> extend beyond the hull?  (One would assume that 1G generated by a
> grav-generator in the deck would reach as far as 1G generated by
> the earths surface, no?)  If so, then space-walking crewmen will
> experience 1G on the dorsel outer hull, but 0G on the ventral hull.
> 
> Or, what happens if we place a 1G grav-generator in both the floor
> and ceiling of a corridor with a 3-meter vertical clearance?  Will
> my head be pulled towards the ceiling while my feet stay firmly on
> the floor?  Will the floor hold more attraction for my body until
> I jump, at which point I \'fall\' to the ceiling?
> 
> I\'m currently co-refereeing the Traveller Mail-list PBEM with Mike
> Metlay (who I sure many of you remember fondly).  Mike holds a Ph.D.
> in high-energy physics and, after much discussion, this is how *we*
> treat artifical gravity.
> 
> Artificial gravity is a closed field effect.  It falls off in direct
> proportion to the strength of the generator and the \'shoulder\' of the
> drop is modified by modulation/harmony interference of the gravity waves.
> Spaceship/starship hulls are designed (deliberately) to behave like
> inverted Gaussian surfaces WRT artifical gravity waves.  Specifically,
> part of a ships internal gravitic system includes interference dampers
> in the hull that prevent the ships internal AG from reach beyond the
> hull.  This is necessary for safety reasons.  Imagine dozens, or even
> hundreds of ship docked at a high port, all with their internal gravity
> going 1G.  Re-enforcing the docking moorings to keep all the ships
> stationary would be prohibitively expensive.  Add to that, the attraction
> generated by the internal gravitics of the high port itself, and you\'ve
> got one serious mess on your hands.
> 
> Gravitics, when used for propulsion (grav-cars, grav-bikes, et.al), are
> even simpler, and the grav drive does nothing more than interfer with
> the existing, natural gravity waves in the area.  A spacecraft gravitic
> drive becomes less and less efficient as it moves further out of a star
> systems gravity well (as documented in both the RM Ref. Man. and the
> _Starship_Operators_Manual_).
> 
> As a result, as long as the two starships were parked outside the 100
> diameter limit of whichever ship wasn\'t jumping, either ship could jump
> successfully without being influenced by the gravitics of the other ship.
> As for one ship jumping from *inside* the hold of another ship, I maintain
> that the result would be fundementally the same as if the smaller ship
> tried to jump from a starport launch-pit, while still planetside:
> disasterous.

Anyway, the above posited behavior makes for easy and predictable effects
in *our* games.  Hopefully you\'ll find something useful in all that. :^)

        - Mark C.

