    'body' => 'Hi there. 

Leonard Erickson posted an idea for landing on an Oort cloud body and
melting it for fuel.  His claim was that such an undertaking would be
impossible to detect because there are "just too many cubic AU\'s to
search".  But, you don\'t have to search cubic AU\'s, you just have to have
sensors pointed at every part of the sky.  In other words, you, as a
defending sensor operator on a world, have to cover all *directions*, not
all units of volume.  There are some SETI ideas right now that would cover
10% of the sky continuously using only present day technology (radio
telescopes).  If you were to change their directions once every few 
seconds, you could cover the whole sky each minute.  If you assume higher 
technology and a MUCH more powerful motivating influence (i.e., survival 
instinct), then it is likely that most worlds will do *at least* this.  
They could then pick up the heat needed to melt the asteroid for fuel.  
Furthermore, if the Oort cloud is a good source of fuel, then it will 
definately be scanned for just this sort of activity.  

Remember, if you can think it up, the defenders have already done so, as
they are highly motivated to figure out anything you might do to kill
them. 

Leonard Erickson also posted an interesting idea about building a mass
driver in the outer system.  I don\'t think this is plausible either. 
You\'re talking a fairly big industrial effort here.  And, taking into
consideration the kind of monitoring I noted above as a *minimum*, you
would be picked up long before you finish the project.  Furthermore,
planetary defenses are going to be able to mash any asteroid you send at
them in under a minute.  A few big meson guns, firing at whatever rate
their mechanisms can handle (since aiming is not a consideration for a
non-maneuvering body) could pump out some serious destructive energy. 
And they don\'t have to vaporize it, just crack it into smaller masses and its
course will change or the peices will be vaporized by atmospheric
friction.  Vaccuum worlds, as previously posted, would build installations
deep enough to protect againt all but the biggest hits as a matter of
course. 

The bottom line, IMNSHO, is that both the above ideas might be possible, 
but they would be extremely difficult to pull off.

Charles Collin.

