    'month' => '10',
    'body' => 'Charles Collin <charles@hebb.psych.mcgill.ca> writes:

> Leonard Erickson posted an idea for landing on an Oort cloud body and
> melting it for fuel.  His claim was that such an undertaking would be
> impossible to detect because there are "just too many cubic AU\'s to
> search".  But, you don\'t have to search cubic AU\'s, you just have to have
> sensors pointed at every part of the sky.  In other words, you, as a
> defending sensor operator on a world, have to cover all *directions*, not
> all units of volume.  There are some SETI ideas right now that would cover
> 10% of the sky continuously using only present day technology (radio
> telescopes).  If you were to change their directions once every few 
> seconds, you could cover the whole sky each minute.

No you can\'t. Sensors have a limit known as "angular resolution". That
means that they can\'t resolve things that subtend less than their
angular resolution. The higher the angular resolution, the *wider* the
sensor array has tto be, abd thus the hard it is to turn.

For refeuling and observation, all you need is a body in the 1 km
range. 1 AU is 150e6 km. So 100 is 1.5e9 km. What\'s arctan 1/1.5e9?
Answer, a *very* small angle.

> If you assume higher 
> technology and a MUCH more powerful motivating influence (i.e., survival 
> instinct), then it is likely that most worlds will do *at least* this.  
> They could then pick up the heat needed to melt the asteroid for fuel.  

Again, you are wrong. If I do the melting on the "back" side of the
body, they won\'t be able to *see* the "heat" because it\'ll all be
radiating in the wrong direction.

> Furthermore, if the Oort cloud is a good source of fuel, then it will 
> definately be scanned for just this sort of activity.  

But how it is scanned, and from *where* make a big difference. And
there is a distinct limit to how paranoid you can *afford* to be.

BTW, if your sensors are good enough to pick this sort of thing up at
100 AU, they\'ll get *fried* by the incredibly stronger signals from
things like other planets in the system, and ships manuevering.

This is one of the *major* limits on astronomy right now. There\'s too
much background noise.
 
> Remember, if you can think it up, the defenders have already done so, as
> they are highly motivated to figure out anything you might do to kill
> them. 

But they have to balance the assumed likelihood of it happening vs the
costs of protecting against it.

We know damn well that a medium sized asteroid could wipe us out, but
we are only making half-hearted efforts to do anything about it.

> Leonard Erickson also posted an interesting idea about building a mass
> driver in the outer system.  I don\'t think this is plausible either. 
> You\'re talking a fairly big industrial effort here.  And, taking into
> consideration the kind of monitoring I noted above as a *minimum*, you
> would be picked up long before you finish the project.  Furthermore,
> planetary defenses are going to be able to mash any asteroid you send at
> them in under a minute.

But I\'m *not* sending an asteroid. I\'m sending a dinky little 1 ton
chunk of nickel iron, well stealthed, and equipped with manuevering
jets to make midcourse corrections. Less than half a meter across.

> A few big meson guns, firing at whatever rate
> their mechanisms can handle (since aiming is not a consideration for a
> non-maneuvering body) could pump out some serious destructive energy. 

And what are the odds of them being able to hit a target that small at
several light seconds? Answer, just about nil.

> And they don\'t have to vaporize it, just crack it into smaller masses and
its
> course will change or the peices will be vaporized by atmospheric
> friction.

The course *won\'t* change. Physics doesn\'t work that way. The pieces
will start spreading, but they should all hit a target the size of a
planet. And "vaporising in the atmosphere" sound great. But it isn\'t.
The *full* impact energy will go into the planet\'s atmosphere *if* the
pieces vaporise. That could ruin the planet right there.

For example, the million gee version will dump approximatelly 500
megatons into what it hits. That\'s enough to *kill* all unshielded
personnel on that side of the planet, and change global weather
patterns. It\'s also not certain that pieces travelling at 1.5% of c
will have *time* to vaporise.

On a vacuum world, you\'d have to dig one *hell* of a long way to be
same. Tens to hundreds of kilometers. And again, the radiation (X-rays
and gammas) from the plasma cloud would be lethal for hundreds or
thousands of km. You *don\'t* harden gear against *that* level of
radiation.

> The bottom line, IMNSHO, is that both the above ideas might be possible, 
> but they would be extremely difficult to pull off.

Not as difficult as you may think. :-)

