    'body' => 'Just a short question to Mr. Hostman.
Could you please explain how you got your numbers for how far a target ship 
could move between the time you detected it and your shots arrive...?
Last time I checked, the distance an accellerating body could cover was 
given by x = 0.5*A*t^2.
thus for a = 21 ms^-2  and t = 24 => x = 6048.

Another thing to keep in mind is that most ships cannot accellerate equally
well in all directions - they have to rotate their thrust axis. this takes time, and screwes up 
their own firing solutions. not to mention gives everyone severe cases of 
space-sickness if the ship lacks grav compensators. (recall the PLanet class
heavy cruiser in Rebellion sourcebook. :) thus the worst possible shape 
as far as evasive agility is concered is a long cylinder or dart.(preferred axis of rotation aligned with thrust axis) the best 
is a sphere, or a slab with the thrust axis aligned with the short side. 
I would imagine the best compromise between agility, atmospheric performance and stealth would be a T or a flying wing a-la B2.

Now, based on what has been mentioned re "probability bells of position" it
would seem that the best way to evade is to move on a plane perpendicular 
to the axis between the firer and the target, as well as to the velocity 
vector of the target. that way you maximize the apparent change of angle...
eg. if your ship is built like a standard free trader (down is pointng 
ventrally, not toward the tail) and you are being fired upon by someone straight off the starboard broadside, you should pull "up" or "down". If you are shaped like a B2 not only are you able to rotate quickly along that axis (pitch), 
you also present the smallest aspect... But on the other hand, if you are 
shaped like a B2 and the enemy is directly "above", you\'re hosed.
These things are very likely to be taken into account by a good designer, with
design reflecting relative importance of agility, stealth, mass,e tc.
Although it is interesting that the sphere not only wins the all-round 
agility contest, it is also the most mass-efficient. too bad it\'s so UGLY.

this is also  also exactly the kind of thing that "Predict" is designed to consider.In other words, each different target will ahve preferred axis of rotation, 
preferred arcs of fire (spinal mount), varying aspect area, etc.. 
I can easily see how you would need a good AI Expert system to deal with 
all the parameters in real time - as well as the knack of a good gunner.

switching topic to artificial grav - I think that one wouldn\'t need to worry 
about a 6-G fighter messing up solar systems. since the fighter is slightly
less massive than a planet, and assuming you aren\'t violating conservation of momentum what will move is the fighter - not the planet. although this might be annoying if you don\'t want to go towards the planet.
I would have to agree with the posted idea that artificial grav is a field 
projected between two plates, while anti-grav works by either attracting 
or repelling other gravity fields. The proble with these things though is that
we are VERY far from science, so we have to go by what feels cool and works in 
the game. Then again - I suppose someone could ask Kip Thorne how he would 
do this sort of thing. :)

cheers,
/ben

