    'body' => 'Hi there

In answer to Charles Collin:

I\'ve thought about artificial gravity, and come to some conclusions.
Firstly, I\'ve decided that the way in which artificial gravity makes
itself felt is the same as the way in which gravity does; ie. via
gravity, bent space-time, or whatever is flavour of the month.  Thus,
artificial gravity devices generate gravitons (which is the way I find
easiest to talk about it) at the same density as for the natural
gravity you wish to simulate.  This does not mean that you need to
distort space as much as a size 8 planet in order to get 1g.  The
gravity at the surface of Terra is 1g because (i) Terra is the mass it
is (ii) we are 6400 km from the centre.  If you compressed the mas of
Terra down to a ball the size of a spaceship (100m ?), then the
gravity 6400 km from the centre of that ball would still be 1g, but
the gravity on the surface would be about 16.4 thousand million g
because of the inverse square law (I think - certainly much higher
than at 6400 km) Thus, to get 1g on the surface of the 100m sphere,
you need much less than 1 Terran mass, ans the effect at 6400 km would
be 1/16.4 thousand million g.  Thus, the space-time distortion caused
by an artifcial gravity device does not need to be the same as that of
a planet with the same surface gravity.

In my game, I think grav plates work a bit like this: A grav plate
unit is a flat plain (sp?) which fits into the floor.  The controls
allow you to set a surface gravity and a "persistence" range, with
greater gravity and range requiring more power; the device obviously
has tolerences which causes it to break if settings are too high.  The
effect of setting strength and range is to place the origin (centre)
of the necessary pseudo-mass at a given distance from the plate.  I
then say that the plate can only have an effect in one direction, and
the gravitational origin is on the other side.



			  limit of field effect

     \\			  /
      \\			 /
       \\	x	/
	\\----/ <----  grav plate
	 \\	      /
	  	     
	   \\	y   /	
	       
	     \\	  /
	      	 
	       \\/
		point of origin


Thus, the gravity at x is proportional to the selected pseudo mass,
and inversely proportional to the inverse square of the distance from
the point of origin.  Note, that because the gravity only exists on
one side of the plate, there is no gravity at y, unless there is
another source acting on that point.  

If you have a series of grav plates, the result is a "plain" of
origin.  With the tolerances for power, it is possible to form a
strong grav field at the surface which drops off very quickly (high
pseudo mass, nearby point of origin) or a weak grav field which
extends a long way (low pseudo mass, far point of origin).  To produce
a uniform 1 g field on all decks of a starship, it is necessary to get
all the grav plates working together, so that the residual field from
the deck below is added to that of the deck above.  It is also
possible to extend the grav field beyond the hull of the ship by
simply fiddling with the settings.  Indeed, the grav field of the
"top" deck will always extend beyond the hull, unless you are willing
to have your head at significantly lower gravity than your feet (with
unfortunate physical consequences!), or of course the top deck has
void, fuel, or ungravitied cargo hold above it.  I think these factors
also explain why MT densitometers can identify artificial gravity
sources.

