toad@ugcs.caltech.edu (Benjamin Lane) writes:

Subject: Question.

 ----
Another thing to keep in mind is that most ships cannot accellerate equally
well in all directions - they have to rotate their thrust axis. this takes 
time, and screwes up
their own firing solutions. not to mention gives everyone severe cases of
space-sickness if the ship lacks grav compensators. (recall the PLanet class
heavy cruiser in Rebellion sourcebook. :) thus the worst possible shape
as far as evasive agility is concered is a long cylinder or dart.(preferred 
axis of rotation aligned with thrust axis) the best
is a sphere, or a slab with the thrust axis aligned with the short side.
I would imagine the best compromise between agility, atmospheric performance 
and stealth would be a T or a flying wing a-la B2.
 ----

The fact that ships must slew (ie change direction) in order to evade 
produces restrictions on the size and shape of the "probability bell".
There is however no rules in Traveller which help determine what the 
restrictions will be.
eg. can ships be designed with vectored thrust maneuver drives?

As for mucking up your own firing solutions I assume that the evasive 
maneuvers are computer controlled using a pseudo random sequence. As this 
sequence is pseudo random you know what your ship will do therefore you can 
compensate for your own evasion.
These pseudo random sequences would be a closely guarded secret ( think 
Star-Trek shield frequencies ;).

 ----
Now, based on what has been mentioned re "probability bells of position" it
would seem that the best way to evade is to move on a plane perpendicular
to the axis between the firer and the target, as well as to the velocity
vector of the target. that way you maximize the apparent change of angle...
 ----

Yes, I would think that the pilot\'s skill would be useful here. An other way 
would be for it to be entirely computer controlled, the crew merely 
assigning threat levels to each bogey and giving target priorities.

 ----
eg. if your ship is built like a standard free trader (down is pointng
ventrally, not toward the tail) and you are being fired upon by someone 
straight off the starboard broadside, you should pull "up" or "down". If you 
are shaped like a B2 not only are you able to rotate quickly along that axis 
(pitch),
you also present the smallest aspect... But on the other hand, if you are
shaped like a B2 and the enemy is directly "above", you\'re hosed.
These things are very likely to be taken into account by a good designer, 
with
design reflecting relative importance of agility, stealth, mass,e tc.
Although it is interesting that the sphere not only wins the all-round
agility contest, it is also the most mass-efficient. too bad it\'s so UGLY.
 ----

The other thing is that a sphere cannot reduce it\'s cross-section to a 
target by changing it\'s orientation and always has a relatively large cross 
section for it\'s volume.

 ----
this is also  also exactly the kind of thing that "Predict" is designed to 
consider.In other words, each different target will ahve preferred axis of 
rotation,
preferred arcs of fire (spinal mount), varying aspect area, etc..
I can easily see how you would need a good AI Expert system to deal with
all the parameters in real time - as well as the knack of a good gunner.
 ----

Yes, this also makes it easier to hit a ship you are attacking from several 
directions...


