    'from' => 'Stewart Eyres spe@jb.man.ac.uk',
    'body' => 'HI there

I\'ve been thinking about this jump flare thing.  From what has been 
written about Jump operation, I\'d say that the flare on *entry* to jump 
would be stronger than that on *exit*.  The SOM (and maybe elsewhere?) 
says that after the jump capacitors are charged, part of that charge is 
channeled to the hull grid (about 10 %) I think to format it for the 
remaining 90 % of the energy, which actually opens the path into 
jump-space.  I\'m rule that the 10 % formatting energy is retained to 
maintain the protective field seperating jump space from the little bit 
of real space containing the starship.  Thus, more energy is released at 
entry than at exit.  Of course, depending on what you believe jump space 
to be like, the opening through which the ship enters or leaves may allow 
exotic particles to escape, resulting in a characteristic flare.  

In my campaign, I allow sensor readings of a nearby jump entry to 
estimate the intended jump range (as this depends on the gross energy 
expenditure), assuming they know a reasonable amount about the jumping 
vessel (its size - which scales the energy expenditure).  However, 
actually predicting the destination requires (i) high resolution imaging 
of the hull grid at jump and (ii) large amount of computer time.  Even 
then, it would be almost impossible without at least two points of view 
(otherwise, how do you know what is happening to the grid on the other 
side of the vessel?), and a good idea of the operating parameters of the 
jumping vessel.  I think that the hull grid is usually given as having 
about a 1 metre seperation, which is about 1/1000000 radians at 1000 km, 
or about 200 milliarcseconds.  This is the resolution of about a 60 cm 
optical telescope, which is not too unreasonable with sythetic 
apertures.  However, if you say that not all the information from the hull 
grid is emitted optically, you need an integrated EM array, and your
resolution is limited by the longest wavelength you are interested in 
(radio?)  Also, 1000 km is pretty close in space terms, and the amount of 
computing power is going to be more than that required for calculating a 
starship\'s own jump.  Thus, a superior vessel could probably handle the 
calculations for an inferior vessel.  Essentially, you can fiddle with 
the emitting wavelength until you reach a maximum range to allow such 
things to be possible with which you are happy.

I suppose the amount of energy that is used at jump can be estimated from 
the fact that the jump "drive" is a high-throughput, low-efficiency 
fusion powerplant.  90 % of this energy is released on jump entry, an 10% 
on exit.  I\'d be against easy detection of emerging vessels, as it 
flumoxes so many adventure ideas.  In general, I allow my players to 
determine the intended range of a jumping vessel, but little else; this 
way, they think they are getting something out of their sensor readings, 
but essentially it is of no use :-)

