    'ts-index' => '1995-10-31.ab958',
    'body' => 'A couple more problems with the mass driver idea:
1) If the projectile has thrusters and a guidance system, then that makes 
it easier to detect.  Also, once you\'ve wrecked those, there\'s a good 
chance the rock will miss its target.  If it happens to be on course  for 
the world when this happens, it\'s still not a problem as the rock is now 
ballistic (i.e., not maneuvering) and its course will be totally 
predictable.  You can thus hit it with all sorts of stuff.
2) If you\'re firing the projectile from several AU away, you better send 
it through a part of space totally devoid of debris.  If the thing hits 
even a tiny pebble floating out there, it will vaporize or at least be 
cracked open.   In fact, this 
provides yet another way of defending against such a ploy:  the simple 
sand caster.  If you can put a cloud of particles in the projectile\'s 
path, it\'s gone.
3) To power the mass driver, you\'re going to need some BIG powerplants 
(esp. if you want to generate a million g!).  These can be detected.  In 
fact, I think this is the major problem with the idea.  It can never be 
built before someone finds it.

Charles.


