not quite...   ;^)

You see, the probability bubble is moving with the craft, the current 
vector is irrelevant. If you use the frame of reference of the target 
craft, then the probability bubble is **how much it can _change_ its 
vector in the next x seconds**. Not what the new vector is. What the 
current vector is, is usually irrelevant (unless they are going out of 
range, or they are so close your turrets cannot traverse fast enough to 
keep up.)

Also if you are maintaining a similar vector (usually the case when 
prosecuting an attack) then the vectors you each have almost cancel each 
other out anyway in terms of opening or closing the range.

In essence, how far you travel in a turn is irrelevant; how much you 
*change* your vector/speed is all that matters.

BTW I was more thinking of *missiles* having to fill that volume. A 1200m 
radius sphere is 7,238,229,473.871 m3. That\'s 7.3 cubic Kilometers!

Also, you cannot use \'common sense\' to narrow the area involved in the 
probability bubble, as some people *will* use unorthodox manoeuvres to 
evade. eg. During the 5FW as the Imperial player, at the height of the 
Zhodani assault, I invaded Zhodani territory, and started capturing 
planets. While this did not deter his main thrust (these were not my main 
defense) it did cause two of his follow-up and outflank fleets to be 
diverted. The Zhodani player diverted approximately 12-14 counters, while 
the Imperial invasion force was 4 ship counters (cruiser largest), in 
three fleets with some ground forces for garrison duty.

This unorthodox tactic made much better use of these four counters than 
if I had spent them in battle.

A P Madden
