    'month' => '11',
    'index' => 'ab972',
    'body' => 'Some people have put forth the idea that jump flares would not be visible 
from a great distance, but if we are to take the SOM as gospel, it says 
the jump flare is "almost painful to look at".  That means (according to 
visual psychophysics), you\'ve got a light somewhere in the range of 10^9 
candellas per m^3, or roughly the brightness of the surface of the noon 
sun!  I think this signal would carry for a fairly good distance.  If we 
assume that the signal is "normal light" (i.e., non-lased and devoid of 
exotic energies), then the signal should roughly degrade with the square of 
the distance.  Now, assuming that EMS sensors can normally pick up faint 
reflections from mat black ships in empty space at distances of several 
light seconds, they should be able to pick up the above emergence flare 
at HUGE distances with no problem.

Incidentally, this also argues for the jump flare indicating the 
rough size of the 
ship coming in (larger profile = more emited light).  I don\'t think the SOM 
says anything about the flare varying with jump number.  

BTW, several people seem to consider the SOM a "non-canonical" source.  
Why is this?  I don\'t know what the criteria for "canonical" are, does it 
have to come from GDW or what?  

Charles

