    'topic' => ' Space Combat',
    'index' => 'ab973',
    'month' => '11',
    'body' => 'Hi.  A P Madden stated a concern that missile bursts would have to fill 
huge volumes (on the order of cubic kms!) to hit a target at a range of 
several light seconds.  This is true.  One could never succeed in filling 
in the volume a ship might be in with shrapnel if one is sending out 
ballistic ordonance.  I usually picture 
missiles as closing to a fairly close distance, where they can estimate 
a new probability bubble (or bell, or sigmoidal shape, or whatever) that 
is much smaller (exponentially smaller as you close distance). They can 
then either fill this smaller  area with very high velocity shrapnel or (my 
own personal view from Traveller:2300) fire a one-shot, multiple beam weapon at 
the target (something like the x-ray lasers they were or are thinking 
about for Star Wars).

