  {
    'body' => 'Hey there;  Tom Trelenberg again.

First I wanted to thank everyone for the "unstreamlined ship landings"
discussion.  It was very helpful and I\'ve got a good idea of how to
handle things now.

Second, I wanted to throw in my non-canonical (all I own is three little
black books and some supplements, no MT or TNE, although I\'m trying to
rectify this) opinion on jump flares--no rotting fruit or vegatables 
please.

I have always thought of a ship in jump space as being in "a high energy
state" (as opposed to when its in real space being more of a ground
state--sorry for the Quantum analogies; the physics dept. makes me think
this way, I can\'t help it.)  Therefore, much of the energy produced to 
enter jump is bound into the ship in order to place it in this high 
energy space.  However, I have always played, that when the ship emerges,
it must shed this extra energy to return to its "ground state" which
will retun it to real space.  Consequently, in my games there is a minor
flare upon entry (due to J-drive inefficiency to couple its output energy
with the ship) but its magnitude is nothing in comparison to the flare
when the ship emerges; as it must now dump the energy of tens to thousands
of tons of fused H.

This has worked very well in my games.  It is true (as was mentioned) that
this can limit adventure posibilities (as the PC\'s ship doesn\'t quietly
glide into a system) but on the other hand, my players have often been 
glad for the bit of warning that someone might be after them....So it cuts
both ways.  Anyway with all that space out there from which to emerge, and 
the inability for a sensors to look for everything, in all directions, at
all times, in my opinion makes detection rather remote.  (This is of coarse
assuming that one comes out of jump in a random location in the system, I 
know that there has been a great deal of discussion on this too--but I still
hold it to be true)

As I said this is non-canonical (all this "hull jump grid" stuff is new to
me and I\'m still trying to figure it out), but I just thought that it might
be useful to throw in another opinion that has been proven workable (well...
by me anyway) gamewise.

Thanks for the posting space

Tom Trelenberg
