    'topic' => ' Unstreamlined Ship Landings',
    'body' => 'Someone let me have it for saying that missiles would knock a ship around
>at 10 g\'s.  Sorry, that was a bit of hyperbole.  Let me put it another
>way: a ship that can stand the rigors of combat (e.g. shock waves from
>nuclear weapons, high-g maneuvers) should be able to support its own
>weight when landing.

This is by no means certain.  The kind of forces and stresses that
a ship is going to have to withstand from a fluid shockwave  are
different than those from supporting it\'s weight on a hard surface.
It is quite possible to have a structure that can withstand
one and not the other.

>Now before someone tells me about naval battleships
>trying to stay together on land or something, let me remind everyone that
>the original question was about a PC ship (i.e., less than 1000 tons I\'m
>guessing).  It\'s strength-to-mass ratio should be pretty good.

Simple strength/mass may have very little to do with the situation.
You can have a structure that is designed to withstand certain
types of forces and is very poor at withstanding other forces
(and remember, we are talking about ships that were designed
with the belief that they wouldn\'t have to withstand forces
from landing.)

