For Charles:
>In terms of landing gear, you won\'t need any if there\'s water around.  
>The ship will float, assuming it\'s average density is that of liquid 
>hydrogen (as the design rules do).

My thought was that any form of close/dispersed, etc. structure would have
trouble supporting itself on land or water due to the structural stresses
involved. Then there are the straight logistics of the ship remaining
upright, etc. to be of any use. Picture almost _ANY_ of the bigger ships
from any Star Wars or Star Trek movie or Babylon 5, etc... and then picture
said ship landing on a flat surface or in the water. Nah! They would all
break up or roll over unless you provided a lot of extra supports or assumed
the entire ship had full contra-grav. Then again, that\'s only sci-fi and
Traveller is reality...

Andy
