    'month' => '11',
    'topic' => 'Imperial Annexation',
    'body' => 'From: LENSCOTT@aol.com
> 
> In the Traveller universe there are many minor races of humans transplanted
> by the Ancients scattered all over space. How are these worlds incorporated
> into the Imperium as the Imperium expands into  a particular region? Are the
> worlds so extremely willing to join the Imperium or does the Imperium annex
> them militarily if neccessary. 

The Imperium prefers to annex worlds willingly, but will not hesitate to 
annex worlds by force if it serves it\'s interests.  See the Pacification 
Wars.

Oftentimes, worlds are first settled by Imperials, who form their own 
governments.  Then, they become client states of the Imperium.  Finally, 
they are annexed.  It seems that most of the Spinward Marches was annexed 
by this method: Regina was annexed in this manner, and Subsector N 
(District 285? in 1202, called Plankwell subsector) is currently being 
annexed in this manner.  It takes time, but is largely nonviolent.

> If the Imperium allows its subject worlds a large degree of self rule (as
> long as the taxes are paid and intersteller trade isn\'t affected), how does
> it transform these conquered worlds into imperial worlds? 

Imperial worlds have a number of requirements: 
         - pay taxes. Taxes are assesed by world: the world pays the tax 
           via whatever means it wishes, from income taxes, sales taxes, 
           loans, etc.
         - support the military, esp. the Imperial Navy.
         - each world and it\'s major continents, divisions, and cities 
           has a noble hierarchy, either selected from the locals or 
           parachuted in by the Emperor.
         - Imperial law -- a minimum law code, forbidding murder, treason, 
           etc. -- is enforced.

It has been said that the Imperium is a trade confederation: most nations 
join the Imperium for the trade benefits, esp. before the Pacification 
Wars. The Imperial borders have been largely stable since then, with the 
only areas of expansion being in the Domain of Deneb (economic/population 
reasons) and the Solomani (military security, and cultural reasons). 

> Does it replace the existing governmental structure with a
> puppet ruler (as during the Cold War with third world countries)? 

Never, to my knowledge. (Excepting \'Offworld Rule\', which would mean 
military rule).  The Imperium is a feudal nobility, but doesn\'t go out of 
it\'s way to encourage this form of government.

> Does it bring in troops and govern directly with ground forces 
> (possibly expensive and dangerous)? 

Sometimes.  Terra was placed under military rule after the Rim War.

> What about removing trouble makers and bringing in tame
> colonists from other parts of the Imperium (a la Israel and the occupied
> territories)?

The Regency is doing this with the Sword Worlders: it has not proven to 
be a success, as mutual loathing has risen between settlers and locals.

