    'month' => '11',
    'topic' => 'mass driver & Oort cloud',
    'body' => 'Charles Collin <charles@hebb.psych.mcgill.ca> writes:

 > A couple more problems with the mass driver idea:
 > 1) If the projectile has thrusters and a guidance system, then that
 > makes it easier to detect.

The guidance system adds *nothing* to the detectability. Purely
passive, optical observations of stars and planets.

The thrusters are intended for *small* course corrections. Over a 40
day flight tme, it doesn\'t take much to nudge the final vector the
required amount. Probable thruster type is small ion thrusters, such as
are currently used for stationkeeping on geosynchronous satellites and
some probes. They have a *very* high Isp, and can produce milli-gee
thrusts for *months*. They are also almost impossible to detect.

The idea is that whevere the guidance package sees a course deviation
big enough to correct, it can fir the thrusters, which will make a
course change on the order of less than 1 second of arc.

 > Also, once you\'ve wrecked those, there\'s a good chance the rock will
 > miss its target.

See above, if you wreck the thrusters, it\'s unlikely to make the
projectile (*not* rock!) miss, because it\'ll have been on course within
less than 1 sec of arc!

 > If it happens to be on course  for the world when this happens, it\'s
 > still not a problem as the rock is now ballistic (i.e., not
 > maneuvering) and its course will be totally predictable.  You can
 > thus hit it with all sorts of stuff.

The thrusters aren\'t *intended* for dodging. Just for course
correction. So the course will *always* be predictable. The problem is
*finding* the projectile in time. 

detect  return  transit time to         Max intercept range (km)
range   time    time    intercept       6g      10g     100g
----  ----  ---- ----       ---- ---- ----
10 ls   10 s    667 s   657 s            12,677 21,129  211,293
 9 ls    9 s    600 s   591 s            10,269 17,115  171,148
 8 ls    8 s    533 s   525 s             8,114 13,523  135,228
 7 ls    7 s    467 s   460 s             6,212 10,353  103,534
 6 ls    6 s    400 s   394 s             4,564  7,607   76,066
 5 ls    5 s    333 s   328 s             3,169  5,282   52,823
 4 ls    4 s    267 s   263 s             2,028  3,381   33,807
 3 ls    3 s    200 s   197 s             1,141  1,902   19,016
 2 ls    2 s    133 s   131 s               507    842    8,452
 1 ls    1 s     67 s    66 s               127    211    2,113

It looks fairly clear that *physical* attacks are out of the question.
Lasers and PAWS aren\'t real likely to do significant damage in time.
Meson weapons *might*. One the other hand, what amount of damage does
it take to break up a 1 ton piece of *solid* metal, and what sort of
accuracy does it take to hit a less than 1 meter target at light second
ranges?

Plus, given that many here agree with me that *detection* is very
difficult, odds are that a detect at even *one* light second is
unlikely. How many shots can you get off in 66 seconds?

Finally, since it *won\'t* be making course corections in the last hour
or so, we could always mount a black globe on it and turn it on when
the projectile is an hour out. That makes both detection and
destruction essentially impossible. :-)

(of course, that\'s *real* expensive, and probably masses too much)

 > 2) If you\'re firing the projectile from several AU away, you better
 > send it through a part of space totally devoid of debris.  If the
 > thing hits even a tiny pebble floating out there, it will vaporize
 > or at least be cracked open.

And the odds of it hitting any such pebble are next to nil. 

 > In fact, this provides yet another way of defending against such a
 > ploy:  the simple sand caster.  If you can put a cloud of particles
 > in the projectile\'s path, it\'s gone.

See the table above to see just how hard it\'d be to do this. 

 > 3) To power the mass driver, you\'re going to need some BIG
 > powerplants (esp. if you want to generate a million g!).  These can
 > be detected.  In fact, I think this is the major problem with the
 > idea.  It can never be built before someone finds it.

The projectile from the million gee version has 20.25e18 joules of
energy. That\'s 20.25e12 Mj. Assume 90% losses. That makes the
input 202.5e12 Mj. 

100 AU is 150 billion km. The surface of a 100 AU sphere is roughly
282e27 m^2. That give 716e-18 Mj per sq. meter. or 716e-12 j/m^2. And
that\'s assuming that *all* the losses radiate omnidirectionally, and
that none of them go into any sort of "heat sink". 

I don\'t have a the value of Planck\'s constant handy, so I can\'t
estimate how many photons per square meter that\'ll be. Plus we need to
figure out what *frequency* the losses would be at.

If somebody has a table of atomic weights handy, they can figure out
how many hydrogen-1 atoms need to be fused to helium-4 atoms to
generate that much power. Multiply by two to get the total number of
neutrinos emitted. Then divide by the area above to get neutrinos per
square meter. The result will show how ineffective nuetrino sensors
will be. 

And while doubling the distance will double the transit time for the
projectile, it\'ll drop emissions to one *quarter*. 

And all this is assuming that I\'m generating enough power to fire
essentially "continously". If I generate the power at a lower level,
and store it in a capacitor bank or the like until I need it then my
rate of fire goes down, but so do the emission levels. 

At one shot per day, I\'ve just dropped the power requirements by
86,400. 

BTW, an earlier message referred to the eyes ability to "subtract things"
(like the overlying blood vessels) as an explanation of why sensors
wouldn\'t be bothered by "background noise". Sorry, it doesn\'t work that
way. You *can\'t* see a candle at 100 feet, if I\'m at 10 feet shining a
spotlight in your face. Heck, you won\'t be able to see a *road flare*
aat 100 feet in those circumstances! So unless there are no *stronger*
sources in your field of view, you won\'t be able to see a weak source.

