    'ts-index' => '1995-11-02.ab992',
    'body' => 'Someone mentioned that strength to mass ratio was not enough alone to 
keep a ship landing on a world surface together.  But it is if we assume 
a relatively simple shape (i.e. no struts and stuff).  Many unstreamlined 
ships are box or cylinder shapes, so they should do okay, especially if 
they land with their "tail down".  They can certainly take the stress 
along their thrust axis.  The ship may get damaged, but not severely.  
Keeping the ship upright should not be a problem with maneuver thrusters 
and a good computer.   

Also, if you do a soft water landing, you can use bouyancy to lower your 
weight and increase your strength to weight ratio.

Another thing you can do is simply hover above the surface and drop 
people off.

Charles.

