I don\'t know how much the Imperium is still expanding by
the Classic Traveller era, ca. 1100.  I think that most of
the expansion took place during the Pacification Campaigns
after the Long Night, when joining the Imperium and getting
the protection of its navy and the benefits of its support
for interstellar trade made it a very attractive option for
individual worlds subject to raiding and reliant on their
own, often scarce and depleted, resources.  (A sentence
that long should perhaps be written in German or Zdetl.) 
The Pacification Campaigns lasted from about 76 to 120.

By the early 1100s, District 268/Spinward Marches is on
its way to becoming Collace Subsector, and part of the
Imperium, and I suppose that some absorption of border
areas was going on, but not on anything like the scale of
the first 120 years.  The absorbable border states, except
for the coreward border, are all small states lying
between the Imperium and the other comparably large
states.  Maybe the Imperium and the Hivers, Zhodani, etc.
prefer to keep some buffers in place.  Along the coreward
border are the Vargr Extents -- does the Imperium want to
absorb any of them? 

> If the Imperium allows its subject worlds a large degree
> of self rule (as  long as the taxes are paid and
> intersteller trade isn\'t affected), how does it
> transform these conquered worlds into imperial worlds?

Transformation probably wasn\'t too big a deal 1000 years
ago during the great expansion of the Imperium -- after
all, these worlds had all been members of the Rule of Man
and, before that, of the Ziru Sirka.  Most of them were
happy to join Cleon\'s Imperium and get out the Long Night
and back to prosperity, trade, and peace. 

Transformation today (ca. 1110, say) still isn\'t too big a
deal.  What makes a world an Imperial world is a commitment
to the Imperium, which takes the form of paying taxes or 
tribute, submission to the draft, and allowing starports and 
Imperial bases.  There is no Imperial culture per se that a 
new member has to adopt, nor any Imperial code of laws (at 
least none that affect local governance), so joining the 
Imperium may not require major changes to a world.  

That\'s not to say that it may not cause major changes, or
that joining the Imperium would not be a big deal, as
military spending drops or increases because of joining the
Imperial defense network, trade increases as Imperial
tariffs no longer apply (that comment should generate some
discussion), and veterans return from Imperial service
with new ideas based on what they\'ve seen.

> Does it arrange treaties with the original governments
> on the worlds, and just set up a system of tribute?

Maybe.

> Does it replace the existing governmental structure with
> a puppet ruler(as during the Cold War with third world
> countries)? 

It might do this if the former government were hostile and 
the world was threat to Imperial security -- Arden/Vilis 
after the Fifth Frontier War comes to mind.

> Does it bring in troops and govern directly
> with ground forces (possibly expensive and dangerous)?

No -- I would think that a good frontier duke would be able 
to get an enemy of that world to that for the Imperium, 
saving cost and bad press.

> What about removing trouble makers and bringing in tame 
> colonists from other parts of the Imperium (a la Israel
> and the occupied territories)?

This probably happpened a lot more during the Pacification 
Campaigns than later.

> Anyone with any ideas or canonical info?

Some of each.

