    'body' => '

Internet=(xboat@mpgn.com)

2/11-95 Charles Collins wrote:

>1. The jumping object must be 1400 m^3 in volume but can
>be any mass.  If this is the case, then one could have the
>jump missile as an unfolding or inflating sort of thing with a
>tiny jump drive, powerplant and fuel tank to carry the
>reduced mass into jump space.  Of course this doesn\'t
>work if you assume the size of the j-drive is dependent on
>the volume of the jumping object, so you have to make
>some pretty "convenient" assumptions.

<two other possibilities snipped>

>From MT it is known that the minimum size for a starship is
100 (displacement) tons, which is a measure of volume.
You can always design a very simple ship with a 100 ton
hull, a jump drive, necessary fuel and computers and lots of
empty space. This should be faily inexpensive compared
to other starships, but will probably run in the MCr range
anyway (I don\'t have the rules with me right now). This is
because the size of the jump drive is a function of only two
variables: The maximum distance it can jump and the
volume of the ship. Then, no matter what you do (inflatable
hulls, etc.), you\'ll still need a full jump drive. No "tiny" jump
drives are possible.

Furthermore: Inflatable hulls would probably inflate a little
different each time, making the grid initializing erronous. It
might be quite unstable too. This results in a high risk of
misjumps (at best).

This is not to shoot down all the interesting hypotheses,
which has been made, but simply to come up with an
explanation consistent with canon why jump missiles are
impossible. It is my firm belief that the existence of jump
missiles would severely damage the background of
traveller as we know it.

Mark Seemann
ms@oem.dk
