    'date' => 'Fri, 3 Nov 1995 11:47:51  0500 (EST)',
    'body' => 'Hi there.  


----
The idea is that whevere the guidance package sees a course deviation
big enough to correct, it can fir the thrusters, which will make a
course change on the order of less than 1 second of arc.
----

So then your projectile is (for the purposes of hitting it) effectively 
ballistic the whole way?  That means anyone picking it up will be able to 
hit it every time at any distance.   Detecting a 1m rock at several 
LS is not difficult at all.  We can do it with the sensors we have today.
With 
TL15 sensors using interferometry to create sensor arrays with 
orbit-sized baselines, the resolution will be incredible!  You don\'t even 
need a planet, you can just use a group of ships\' sensors to create an 
array of extremely high power.

The accuracy required to hit a 1 meter rock at LS ranges is not a 
problem.  Any non-maneuvering target that can be detected can be hit at 
those tech levels.  Even today, we can aim a probe at Pluto at a distance 
of many AU.  Why?  Because it doesn\'t change course. Since you claim your 
projectile doesn\'t either, it is what is known as a target with a trivial 
solution.  I think you are under-estimating the power of technology here.  
TL-15 isn\'t just 20th century tech with jump-drives shoved in it, computer 
and sensor tech will have improved (very conservatively) a 
thousand-fold!  I think you are also forgetting that you are no longer 
dealing with ship sensors and computers here, but the resources of an 
entire planet (presumably and advanced one if you are going to go 
through all the trouble to build a mass driver to attack it).

Your assertion that lasers and PAWs won\'t do sufficient damage is at odds 
with the fact that they can demolish starships with hulls much thicker 
than that.  And again, we won\'t be talking about piddly little ship 
weapons here, but an entire defensive network of massive weapons designed 
to repel fleets of invading warships.  You honestly believe their 
combined might isn\'t going to be able to vaporize a 1m projectile?

Your assertion that putting a black globe on the thing will make it 
harder to detect and hit is again wrong.  An object with its black globe 
on is *easier* to hit because of the hole it leaves in the background.  
Also, the smallest black globe generators are about 15 tons, making your 
projectile much larger, easier to detect, harder to accelerate and so 
on.  Furthermore, the black-globe will make it easier to destroy!  All 
you have to do know is overload the capacitors carried with the thing 
(again the capacitors increase size), and the whole thing vaporizes.  
Hitting the black globe is not difficult because of the "hole in space" 
problem, and since the projectile is effectively ballistic, you can hit 
it every time and easily overload the capacitors.

BTW, my point about eyes being able to subtract out backgrounds stands.  
Just because the visual systems range of subtractive function is limited 
to 14 log units doesn\'t mean that the sensors you build must be that 
way.  You can in fact see a candle flame at a 100 feet by the way.  In 
fact, under ideal conditions, you can see a candle flame up to 1 km 
away!  But that doesn\'t matter, my point is that if a messy biological 
system like the eye can adjust to light levels ranging from 10^-6 cd/m^2 
to 10^10 cd/m^2 and still see detail, then TL 15 sensors should be able 
to do much better.  

Incidentally, you still haven\'t dealt with the logistical problems 
mentioned by several people in earlier issues.

I like the idea for tractor/pressor beams! :-)

