    'month' => '11',
    'topic' => 'mass drivers',
    'body' => 'Charles Collin <charles@hebb.psych.mcgill.ca> writes:


 >> The idea is that whevere the guidance package sees a course
 >> deviation big enough to correct, it can fir the thrusters, which
 >> will make a course change on the order of less than 1 second of
 >> arc.

 > So then your projectile is (for the purposes of hitting it)
 > effectively ballistic the whole way?

Yep.

 > That means anyone picking it up will be able to hit it every time at
 > any distance. 

Nope. Only if they are close enough. Remember, PAWS, Lasers, and meson
guns all have range limits. And projectile weapons have to be close
enough to reach an intercept position before the projectile passes it.

 > Detecting a 1m rock at several LS is not difficult at all.  We can
 > do it with the sensors we have today.

No we can\'t. Especially if the *projectile* (not rock!) is stealthed.
Please state your source for thinking that we can.

 > With TL15 sensors using interferometry to create sensor arrays with
 > orbit-sized baselines, the resolution will be incredible!  You don\'t
 > even need a planet, you can just use a group of ships\' sensors to
 > create an array of extremely high power.
  
Unfortunately, the *resolution* isn\'t the issue. It\'s the signal
strength. The wide baseline gives you higher resolution, but your
minimum observable signal is limited by the size of the *indivual*
sensors, not be the aggregate size. If you can pick up a signal, then
you can get great detail. But you have to pick up the signal first, and
that is *solely* a function of the collecting area at the given sensor.

 > The accuracy required to hit a 1 meter rock at LS ranges is not a 
 > problem. 

I beg to differ. Your pointing accuracy (for beam weapons, which are the
only things that have a *chance* of hitting) is physically impossible.
To hit at *one* LS, you have to be within .5 meters of your aiming
point. So we have a right triangle 3e8 meters on one side and .5 meters
on the other. That\'s a tangent of 1/6e8, or an arc of 9.5e-8 degrees.
or 344 *millionths* of a second of arc. 

To put it another way, if you have to be within .5 meters at 3e8
meters, then at 1 km you have to be within 1.67e-6 meters. Or in other
words, if your "pointing circles" are 1 km in radius (yeah, right!),
you have to be able to position on them to less than 2 microns! I\'ve
*worked* with micron tolerances. You won\'t get them on something that
big without making it too expensive to use, no matter *what the tech
level is. Besides, a temp change of a hundreth of a degree will cause
the setting circle to change size by *meters*. And vibrations will be
far larger than a the 2 micron tolerance.

Now, scale this down to the more likely size of circles a mere 10
meters across, and you get even less likely results (positioning to
better than the size of an atomic nucleus).

With the best pointing you can get, and with *no* change in settings,
your shots will be scattered over *hundreds* of meters. If you hit, it
will be by pure chance. So it\'ll take you hundreds of shots, but you
have to correct your aim after *every* shot because of the speed of
approach. And the time factor says you don\'t have *time* to fire
hundreds of times.

 > Any non-maneuvering target that can be detected can be hit at those
 > tech levels.

No it can\'t. As noted above, you reach a point were your CEP (circular
error probable) is so much bigger than the target, that hits are
essentially impossible.

 > Even today, we can aim a probe at Pluto at a distance of many AU.
 > Why? Because it doesn\'t change course.

Pluto is *much* bigger. And we have a much better trajectory solution
for it. And those probes require *numerous* course corrections along
the way!

 > Since you claim your projectile doesn\'t either, it is what is known
 > as a target with a trivial solution.  I think you are
 > under-estimating the power of technology here.

And I *know* that you are over-estimating the extent to which the laws
of physics limit your ability to shoot back.

 > TL-15 isn\'t just 20th century tech with jump-drives shoved in it,
 > computer and sensor tech will have improved (very conservatively) a
 > thousand-fold!

Sensor tech *cannot* improve that far. There\'s not a thousand-fold
increase in sensitivity *left* to make. Once you can detect down to the
level of the background noise, you *can\'t* get any improvement in
detection by increasing the sensitivity. We already have sensors that
can register individual photons at most wavelengths. You *can\'t* do
better than that. 

The problem is seperating the signal from the backround noise. And
other than reducing the noise generated *in* the sensor, you can\'t do
anything about noise. It is not *possible* to detect any signal weaker
than background noise. Period. If you think otherwise, you do not
understand the subject. 

Improvements in computer tech aren\'t relevant here.

 > I think you are also forgetting that you are no longer dealing with
 > ship sensors and computers here, but the resources of an entire
 > planet (presumably and advanced one if you are going to go through
 > all the trouble to build a mass driver to attack it).
  
No. I simply happen to know that there are inherent limits on some
things. Limits which *no* improvement in tech level can get around.

 > Your assertion that lasers and PAWs won\'t do sufficient damage is at odds 
 > with the fact that they can demolish starships with hulls much thicker 
 > than that.

I didn\'t say that they couldn\'t. I *wondered* how well they will do
against a sold chunk of metal, with no systems to damage. Especially
considering the low odds of getting a direct hit. It\'s far more likely
that ghits will be the fringe of the beam. 

Remember, a ship is a target with a minimum of several *thousand* times
the cross-sectional area of the projectile. How many square meters of
target does even the smallest ship present?

 > And again, we won\'t be talking about piddly little ship weapons
 > here, but an entire defensive network of massive weapons designed to
 > repel fleets of invading warships.  You honestly believe their combined
 > might isn\'t going to be able to vaporize a 1m projectile?
  
If they can target it in time. The odds are better than a thousand to
one *against* their getting a hit at 1 LS. And by making *minor*
variations in launch velocity, I can do a "time on target" attack. I
can speend several *weeks* firing projectiles, and they\'ll all arive at
the same time. Can you handle a thousand of them? How about ten
thousand? A hundred thousand? A million? (a million would be far
cheaper than the mass driver, and could be launched in a mer two weeks
at a rate of 1 every 1.25 seconds).

 > Your assertion that putting a black globe on the thing will make it 
 > harder to detect and hit is again wrong.  An object with its black globe 
 > on is *easier* to hit because of the hole it leaves in the background.  

At one light second, the odds of the globe occulting *one* star are
millions to one. So much for your "hole in the background". Work it out
for yourself if you don\'t believe me.

 > Also, the smallest black globe generators are about 15 tons, making your 
 > projectile much larger, easier to detect, harder to accelerate and so 
 > on.  Furthermore, the black-globe will make it easier to destroy!  All 
 > you have to do know is overload the capacitors carried with the thing 
 > (again the capacitors increase size), and the whole thing vaporizes.  

It was only an idea. On the other hand, I seriously doubt that you can
get off enough *hits* to overload it during the time between detection
and impact. Remember, it\'s almost impossible to get a hit until the
last few *seconds* of flight, due to aiming limitations.

 > Hitting the black globe is not difficult because of the "hole in space" 
 > problem, and since the projectile is effectively ballistic, you can hit 
 > it every time and easily overload the capacitors.

Again, it\'s *not* possible to hit it except by blind luck. And it\'d
take several shots to overload. 

 > BTW, my point about eyes being able to subtract out backgrounds stands.  
 > Just because the visual systems range of subtractive function is limited 
 > to 14 log units doesn\'t mean that the sensors you build must be that 
 > way.  You can in fact see a candle flame at a 100 feet by the way. 

You missed my point *totally*. I did not say that you couldn\'t see a
candle at 100 feet. I said that you couldn\'t see one at 100 feet if I
was shing a *brighter* light into your eyes from 10 feet away! That\'s a
*considerably* different situation, and it demonstrates the "background
noise" problem. Heck, light a candle outdoors on a sunny day. Then
*try* seeing the flame from 100 feet away on a bright, sunny day. You
aren\'t likely to be able to see it unless there\'s a dark background.
The ambient light levels overwhelm it.

 > In fact, under ideal conditions, you can see a candle flame up to 1
 > km away!  But that doesn\'t matter, my point is that if a messy
 > biological system like the eye can adjust to light levels ranging
 > from 10^-6 cd/m^2 to 10^10 cd/m^2 and still see detail, then TL 15
 > sensors should be able to do much better.
 
And my point is that the sensor is going to be limited by the
*brightest* source in it\'s fields of view, as well as by background
noise. A ship at 1 light second will totally overwhelm any signals from
100 AU. 
 
 > Incidentally, you still haven\'t dealt with the logistical problems 
 > mentioned by several people in earlier issues.

Because I don\'t think they are that significant. Since if reasonable
precautions are taken, we *won\'t* be detected from the inner reaches of
the system, the only real consideration is the expense. And more
expensive projects (in relation to GNP) *have* been undertaken.
 
And if it\'s possible to detect me at 100 AU, I can move out to 1000.
That makes the flight time 10 times as long, but makes me 1/100th as
detectable. That makes timing a bit more important, but you can abort
the attack simply by having a ship in the inner system beam an "abort"
signal in the direction of the incoming projectiles. This\'d make them
re-target on the star, and thus be pretty much unnoticed.

