    'body' => '>Reply-To: xboat@MPGN.COM
>> Were that entirely so, we\'d know nothing about the corona. The problem
with
>> dim objects isn\'t wheter or not the background is greater apparent
>> magnitude, but the ability ability to notice changes from background that
>> are orders of magnitude smaller than background, and in the same
>> frequencies as background. Computer tech can improve effective sensor
>> performance significantly, by allowing greater discrimination. The problem
>> with current low light sensors is that their sensitivity is only within a
>> low magnitude; the future is in sensors which have an operational
>> flexibility at great magnitudes, while still being able to discriminate
>> fluctuations of a tiny magnitude.
>
>The problem with this is that in order to image faint sources and do it
>well enough you\'ll be using narrow field instruments and you\'ll have
>pretty long integration times on the detector.  You might well be able
>to find the target, but how many of these things will you need to cover
>the entire volume of space every couple days when your field is a few
>arc seconds wide----and you have to integrate on the source for several
>minutes?  Quantum efficiency of detectors is really really high now, and
>you get get more than 100% of the photons.
>
>It\'d be useful to figure out the scanning rate, as well as what kinda
>magnitudes these critters would be at the distances discussed.
>
>> By TL 15, the sensitivity should be pretty good. And yes, we can track
>> objects of under 10m out to several LS... NASA currently does to around
>> lunar orbit (over 1.5 LS). NASA and the USAF are actively tracking over
>> 3000 objects in orbit, some under 0.25m. (Again, See "Nova", the recent
one
>> about the threat of cometary Impact. {I thought fondly of this thread
while
>> I wathced it})
>
>They also said that it would take them 500 years to complete one survey
>with the 2 astronomers they have doing this kind of stuff.  More
>telescopes would help, and running 24 hour days would help.  Seems like
>it could get down to a scan every 2 days using these figures.

Merrick: NASA isn\'t the only one doing close orbital checking... I know
that my brother-in-law does little more than count satelites for the USAF,
at a Hawaiian Observatory. ESA counts Sats and Space Junk. The Russian Fed
counts sats and space junk. NASA, USAF, RCAF jointly look and count space
junk.

to quote Schumaker (of Shumacher-levy) "only 12 people are looking" was a
reference to asteroid searches. Nobody will actually tell how many military
types are looking... Maybe no-one actually knows.

The current limit on scanning is a combined factor of lack of suitable
instruments, and a lack of trained perople to maximize the use of many of
the existing instruments (Like University of Alaska Fairbanks\' Radio
Astronomy gear... mostly dormant).

I feel that by TL 15, hourly scans should be possible to cover most of the
sphere, with relatively good range and discrimination... 4 high orbit sats
with huge PEMS arrays (4-6 per sat) could get a quite panoramic view, and
each could synthetically combine it\'s on-board arrays, or dump data to a
groundside clearinghouse which synthesizes them all.


-Wil

William F. Hostman

