    'index' => 'ac016',
    'body' => 'Dear Folks -

A late reply...

In Xboat 420, William Hostman replied to a question about nukes:
>>What is a "fusion" warhead in Traveller?
>>Is it a form of nuke?
>>If so, do Nuclear Dampers protect against it?

>Yes (to all). One of the bombs dropped on Japan at the end of WWII was nuke
>called an H-Bomb -- it was a fusion warhead.

Merrick was quite correct, in his reply to William. "Little Boy" was a
gun-type
uranium warhead, while "Fat Man" was an implosion-type plutonium warhead.
H-bombs were not perfected until 1952 (by the USA; the Soviet Union\'s first
was
in 1953, partly sped up due to successful spying).

Note that "Fat Man" was essentially identical to the first A-bomb, "Trinity".
The Manhattan Project scientists were not convinced that it would work, as it
depended on conventional explosives to push a ring of plutonium into a tight
sphere. If the sphere was not formed correctly, it wouldn\'t have worked -
critical mass would not have been reached. "Trinity" proved that the bomb
worked.

The first one dropped in anger was actually "Little Boy" - they were so
utterly
certain it would work that they didn\'t even bother to test it.

- Hyphen
 (David Jaques-Watson)

