First off, the above was regarding the use of *beam* weapons.

Missiles have a better chance, but since the object to be intercepted
is travelling at 1.5% of c, they have to be *very* close or *very* fast
to intercept unless the projectile is detected at unreasonable ranges.

Check a few issues back for the table showing how close a missile
launcher would have to be to make an intercept assuming *constant*
acceleration at various rates.

>By TL 15, the sensitivity should be pretty good. And yes, we can track
>objects of under 10m out to several LS... NASA currently does to
>around lunar orbit (over 1.5 LS). NASA and the USAF are actively
>tracking over 3000 objects in orbit, some under 0.25m. (Again, See
>"Nova", the recent one about the threat of cometary Impact.

Well, remember that a 1 meter onject is 100 times harder to observe
than a 10 meter object. And that my projectiles are deliberately
stealthed. 

And even a 10 LS detection isn\'t as much help as some would think.
Remember, impact will be in less than 11 minutes from when you detect
it. What are the odds of having a missile that can intercept before
impact. 

