>to 1LS; and can hit 2m target at lunar orbit with a reference laser
>for lunar orbit measurements. (legacy of the apollo program, but I
>don\'t recall just which one).

There are several laser reflectors on the moon. But it doesn\'t require
all that much pointing accuracy to hit them. The laser has spread out
to several *miles* across by the time it gets there. But since the
reflectors use special quartz "corner" mirrors, the part of the beam
that reaches them is reflected directly back to the source.

This still give *distance* measurements accurate to a high degree.

