    'month' => '11',
    'index' => 'ac029',
    'body' => '

Robert Flammang <FLAMMANG@vms.cis.pitt.edu> said:

>  But Jump Torpedoes ARE cannon. They can be found in the CT
> adventure "Leviathan" published by GDW.

and sdn00097@sdn.dk (Mark Seemann) responded:

> Yes, I _know_ that "Leviathan" contains jump torpedoes. What I was trying 
to
> say in my last message is that canonical sources are not mutually 
consistent

Although Leviathan was published by GDW, it wasn\'t written by them. It was 
written by the design team at Games Workshop here in the UK (who were 
printing Traveller under licence at the time). I know, because I saw the 
proofs for it at Games Workshop shortly before it was printed.

What this means is that the jump torpedo could quite easily have slipped 
through GDW\'s checking and become canon by accident. Classic Traveller had 
the \'not less than 100 tons\' limit for jump-capable craft too, and, as jump 
torpedoes are mentioned nowhere else (in Classic, MT or TNE), I can only 
assume that this is what actually happened.

> They do not damage the background of Classic Traveller; they are an
> indispensible part of it.

Although they do not damage the background, I would dispute that jump 
torpedoes are indispensible. From his comments, I think Mark Seemann holds a 
similar view. As he says:

> we can discuss this issue from now till hell freezes over, and keep 
hitting each
> other in the head with quotes from different canonical sources.
<snip>
> _I_ don\'t view "Leviathan" as a source that I can use (canonical or
> not), because it conflicts with the way _I_ read other canonical sources.

There are a lot of things I like in Leviathan, but I don\'t view jump 
torpedoes as canon, because they are not detailed elsewhere and the MT rules 
were not changed to allow jump capability in anything less than 100 tons.

> The challenge is to come up with an explanation consistent with canon why
> jump torpedoes are POSSIBLE.

You could always try GDW\'s original get-out clause (ancient artifacts), or 
you could say that they are experimental and that the Leviathan was the 
test-bed for them.

Finally:
> Let\'s not make a religous war out of this.

Hallelujah!.... er, I mean, OK.

Kind Regards

Dave Elrick

