    'body' => 'Hi there

Leonard Erickson said

> Once you can detect down to the
> level of the background noise, you *can\'t* get any improvement in
> detection by increasing the sensitivity.

Um, in IR Astronomy, the noise from the sky and the receiver (ie. the
"background") is of order 1000000 times the signal from the astronomical
objects.  You can always increase your sensitivity by increasing the
number of independent samples of what you are observing by egs. (i)
increasing integration time (ii) increasing the "bandwidth" of your
receivers (iii) increasing the number of sensor elements.  Sensitivity is 
simply the weakest signal you cab detect.  All you have to do to detect a 
signal anywhere in your local system is build enough sensor arrays that 
you can integrate for long enough in each direction on a reasonable 
timescale to have a good chance of picking up the activity you are 
interested in.  The only limitation from the point of view of detection 
is an economic/political will one, not a technological/physics one.  BTW, 
when I sadi that IR astronomer deal with background noise 1000000 times 
the signal, most of that is due to the atmosphere.  If you can put your 
sensor arrays in orbit, much of the noise goes away, but you can still 
see thing 1000000 times dimmer than the (much reduced) remaining background!

