    'index' => 'ac033',
    'topic' => 'background and noise',
    'body' => 'Although I agree with the "principles" of Stewart\'s post in Digest 435
I feel compelled to notice that there is a big difference between noise
and background. If the noise happens to be 1000000 times the signal you
are doomed. If the background is 1000000 times the signal and is not too
variable (or as in the near-IR you "chop") then the related noise will only
be the square root of it and the signal to noise will increase as the
square root of the integration time, number of exposures or whathever else
you do to see something. 

It is also worth noticing that in the optical reaching levels 100 times
fainter
than the sky background is normal

similarly 1000 times fainter than the background is "normal" in the K band
(2.2 microns).

A 1000000 times below the background = 15 magnitudes is not trivial...

Concerning getting rid of the atmosphere effects, one way is just to fly
above
it. Indeed in the next Hubble Space Telescope refurbishment mission "we" will
install NICMOS, a near-IR camera. Alternatively people are playing with the
idea of filtering out the (important) part of the atmospheric background that
is in emission lines. This gains a factor 10 or so when observing from the 
ground.

                   Cheers,
                       Massimo
