There are a couple of problems with the system as outlined in Book 2.  
Sandcasters are not very well explained, and neither are missiles.  They 
mention that missiles "start with the same vector as the firing craft", 
but don\'t explain any further (at what rate to do missiles accelerate, 
for instance?).  Also, have you ever tried a battle using fighters or 
other high acceleration ships using CT space combat?  Can anyone say 
"gymnasium"?  

The way I resolve these issues is as follows.  Feel free to lambaste me 
for my ignorance, as it\'s been a long time since I used the CT space 
combat system, but here goes:

Sand-casters:  Each shot from a sand-caster produces a circle of 
sand 25 mm in diameter that can be sent in any direction with a vector up 
to 100 mm in length.  That is, the sand is "shot", usually so as to be 
interposed between firer and opponent.  The sand has the vector of the 
firing ship plus whatever vector it was given when fired.  Any ship firing 
through sand gets a -3 to hit.  This is based on some information I read 
(in JTAS?) which said that sandcasters could be used as powerful weapons 
against ground troops, hitting them with a "giant shotgun blast" of very 
high velocity particles.

Missiles:  Based on some information in the Annic Nova adventure, I have 
missiles accelerate for up to 10 turns at 10 g\'s.  When they get within 
10mm of a target, they fire, doing 1D6 hits.

Gymnasium Floors as Space Maps:  One way to reduce the size of the 
surface needed for combat is to reduce the length of a turn but keep 
everything else constant.  A good turn length is 316 seconds (call it 5 
minutes).  With this, ships move 10 mm per g each turn instead of 100.  It 
keeps things more manageable, and you still have a scale which allows cool 
gravitational effects and such.

Well, there you go.  Some of my figures may be off in the above, as I 
haven\'t used the CT system in a while (I now use my own space combat 
system based partially on Brilliant Lances and partly on High Guard), but 
I hope this helps.

Charles

