    'body' => 'PICL115@FSPHY1.HEP.FSU.EDU writes:

 > Secondly, in Xboat 434 I asked Paul Colley if he would expound on
 > his post concerning a local EMP generator (Xboat 420).  I did not
 > mean to restrict this question only to Paul.  If anyone else has
 > anything on this please share with the rest of us.

The basic idea is that you dump a huge current pulse into a coil
wrapped around a ferrite or steel core. This creates a *huge* spike in
the magnetic field. It also tends to impose huge stresses on the coil.
Left to itself the coils would either explode (the magnetic field
imposes a *significant* pressure on the coil) or melt from the high
current flow.

But at the moment the current peaks, you set off explosive charges
arranged so as to implode the coil. Since the field is "trapped" in the
core, imploding it raises the field density even higher. It also
amplifies an "uneven-ness" in the field. These inhomogenities, combined
with the the *huge* field density create the EMP. 

As I understand it, we can build a briefcase sized device that\'d
clobber most electronics for as much as 100 yards. And since the blast
is an implosion, there\'d be very little blast damage (the briefcase
would probably contain most of it).

 > Finally, I wanted to add some possible fuel to the already terribly
 > bloody mass driver war we are currently experiencing.  Some quick
 > (and possibly incorrect) calculations indicate that in order for a
 > _mostly_ ballistic projectile to hit an Earth-sized planet at 100AU,
 > the 1000km long accelerator will have to be accurate to within
 > 87/1000 of a second of arc (manuevering of projectile not assumed)
 > to the position of the planet 40 days in the future (is this
 > position known w/o error?).

Well, I knew better than to assume that sufficient accuracy could be
gotten on launch. That\'s why I put course correction thrusters on the
projectiles. Also, the position of the planet should be know fairly
well (from observations made during construction), and the guidance
package and thrusters should handle the rest. I was assuming only about
a 1 second accuracy on launch, and I expect that one *minute* would be
sufficient.

 > I assume thrusters on the 1000km diameter oort body will have to
 > move the accel to this percision and then stabalize it within this
 > degree of percision as well.

I wouldn\'t want that job. That\'s why I figured on only stabilizing to
one arc-second, and using course corrections.

 > Also, at tech 15 will components of a guidance system be able to
 > withstand a 1000g impulse and still remain properly calibrated?

Yes. Because we *already* handle that sort of thing. Proximity fuzed
anti-aircraft shells have a radar set in the nose. And they are fired
from artillery! We were doing this in WWII when the radar sets had to
use *tubes*. They retain calibration quite well. 

At one million gees, it\'s a bit harder. But I suspect that we can
handle this *now*. Solid state gear is *tough*. It handles acceleration
well. It\'s *vibration* that\'s a killer.

