    'date' => 'Wed, 22 Nov 1995 18:37:59  0500 (EST)',
    'body' => 'Hi All.  This is for you physics types.  I was thinking about some 
alternate settings for Traveller, and I\'ve come up with a few questions 
about antimatter.

1. Why is antimatter such a difficult source of energy to develop (i.e.,
according to the Traveller background)?  We can produce very tiny amounts
of anti-matter now, and contain it.  It seems like a simple matter to
allow it to annihilate with normal matter and harness the energy.  Is it
simply a matter of producing sufficient quantities? 

2. Does producing antimatter use up more energy than it can potentially 
return?  How likely is it that one could develop an efficient-enough 
production technique to yeild reasonable returns (i.e., is this a 21st 
century concept, or a 21st millenium concept?)?

3. How likely is one to find large amounts of antimatter in 
space?  If a system were made of anti-matter, would we know it?  Could 
there be large amounts of "dark" antimatter out there?  

4. This one is a bit psycho:  If there were a collapsed anti-matter 
object (black hole, neutron star, etc.), would it have different 
qualities than the same sort of normal matter object?  What if a normal 
matter black hole smacks into an antimatter black hole (do you get a 
galaxy-cracking explosion, or just a more massive black hole?)?

5. Aside from the particles having opposite charges, what are the 
properties of antimatter?  Does it follow the same rules for gravity, 
electromagnetism and so on?

Food for thought, (Sorry to steal your line, Rodge  :-)
Charles.

