Producing it for a net energy gain would require extremely high 
technology (it is theoretically allowed - see below). Todays production 
methods are wholly unfeasible for any sort of sensible use never mind the 
storage problems. For example CERN (Centre of European Particle Physics) 
takes as much power as the entire canton of Geneva and has probably never 
even produced a gram of anti-matter over it\'s entire history (just over 
40 years).
 
> >  Actually, it would be a matter (no pun intended) of _containing_ the
stuff
> >  [...] You can\'t build something out of promatter to attach your
antimatter
> >  [...] You need fields that have all of the properties of matter except
for
> >  the physicality and they have to be not only airtight, but totally
> >  anything-tight;
> 
> Not *exactly*, Jeff ...
> 
> Antimatter only reacts with matter particles of the same type: in other
> words, an anti-neutrino will only react with the exact same type of
> normal-matter neutrino.  Anti-electrons (positrons) react with electrons,
> and anti-protons with protons, and so on.  Anti-protons aren\'t hard to make
> (as antimatter goes), and are charged.  They *will* react with most objects
> made of matter - because the nucleus of every atom contains protons.

No - for example positrons have electric charge and therefore will INTERACT 
with ALL charged particles irrespective of type. Positrons will only 
ANNHILIATE with other electrons however for protons/anti-protons and 
neutron/anti-neutrons things are a lot more complicated since they are 
each made up of 3 quarks (or anti-quarks) and so and anti-proton can 
partially annhilate with a neutron and vice versa.

> Containing antimatter isn\'t quite as hard as you make out - *if* the
> antimatter particles have a charge, they can be contained
electromagnetically
> just like any other type of subatomic particle.  You can use an airtight
> containment vessel (made out of normal matter) to hold the vacuum, and
inside
> that have an electromagnetic container so that the antimatter doesn\'t
escape
> to hit the walls of the container.

Yes it is! Electromagnetic containment works but is limited to extremely 
small amounts of anti-matter and it also has a limited life time since it\'s 
not possible to create a perfect vacuum so some will interact with air.

> Various clever designs have been developed for just this purpose; Dr.
Robert
> L. Forward mentions several that have been proposed in his book _Future
> Magic_.  It\'s worth noting that current high-energy phsyics research
centers
> currently produce and store antimatter as part of their experimental
> programs.  

Yes we do BUT only for small quantities for small amounts of time.

> As a sweeping generalization, any technology that could contain
> and maintain a fusion reaction for power generation could probably have no
> trouble containing and controlling an antimatter reaction.

I very much doubt this since fusion reactions generate a few MeV. A 
proton/anti-proton reaction will generate a few 100 Mev.

> > X::>2. Does producing antimatter use up more energy than it can
potentially
> >  ::>return?

Depends on how you produce it! With current technology the answer is an 
emphatic yes - LOTS. However in theory at least there is no reason why we 
can\'t take a lump of normal matter and convert it into anti-matter. All 
the fundamental conservation laws are satisfied - charge, energy, 
momentum. The problem is that conservation of things called \'lepton 
number\' and \'baryon number\' are violated. Lepton number, for ordinary 
matter, is essentially the number of electron minus the number of 
positrons whereas baryon number is the number of protons and neutrons 
minus the number of anti-neutrons and anti-protons, again only for normal 
matter.

Theorists tell us that at extremely high energies these number 
conservation laws are violated - in fact our existence is good proof of 
this since we are made of protons, neutrons and electrons so, assuming 
the universe started in the Big Bang, something must have generated 
particles and not anti-partciles.

Because of this difference between matter and anti-matter it MAY be 
possible to build a machine to exploit this and convert particles into 
anti-particles but knowing there is such a difference is a long, long way 
from exploiting it. In fact the whole process is on very dodgy ground 
theoretically, nevermind experimentally, but heck this is science FICTION!

> > X::>5. Aside from the particles having opposite charges, what are the
> >  ::>properties of antimatter?  Does it follow the same rules for gravity,
> >  ::>electromagnetism and so on?
> 
> Yes.

NO!

For 3 out of 4 of the fundamental forces of nature (strong, 
electromagnetic and gravity) they are thought to be (and to within 
measurements they are) the same but there IS a difference between matter 
and anti-matter for the weak force!

If you look at the decays of neutral kaons (a types of mesons made from a 
strange and a down quark) then you see a difference between matter and 
anti-matter. The clearest example of this is that the two decays:

	KL -> Pi+ Mu- Nubar

and 	KL -> Pi- Mu+ Nu

(Pi= pion, Mu=muon, Nu=muon neutrino. Pi+/-, Mu+/- and Nu/Nubar are 
particle/antiparticle pairs.)

occur with a difference frequency. This means that Pi- are produced more 
often than Pi+, for example, and so the weak force (which is responsible 
for this decay) sees some difference between them. The exactly mechanism 
as to why is not known, although several theories exist. In fact the 
experiment I\'m working on at CERN is currently trying to discover the 
mechanism behind this effect so hang around a few years and we may find out!

> The properties of antiparticles which we\'ve been able to produce (which
> includes anti-electrons and anti-protons, and probably more by now) have
> been pretty-well investigated, and found to be "as expected" (the reason
it\'s
> so well-checked is that *if* there was a difference, there\'d probably be a
> Nobel prize in it for someone ...)

There was - in 1964 Cronin, Fitch and Turlay discovered the effect 
mentioned above and won the Nobel prize some years later.

Roger

