    'body' => 'HI all,
	while most of the important points regarding anti-matter have 
already been discussed, there are still a few points to make;
storing antimatter is certainly not easy - however, with grav technology,
and superconducting magnets available, it might be feasable. you\'ve 
probably all heard about that superconducting magnet that was kept 
suspended for years thanks to its own magnetic field. also, while 
electro-magnetic fields won\'t affect neutral particles, keep in mind that
gravity fields will.
and certainly there are powerful such fields available, since that is 
supposedly how SD materials are made.(I am more comfortable blaming that 
on magnetic monopoles, but that\'s just my own opinion..)
and shielding antimatter from neutrons shouldn\'t be too difficult - 
you have superdense materials that will even reflect a few neutrinos 
(Starship Ops Manual). not that free neutrons are that common, since they
decay in about 11 minutes..

as for energy efficiency - when annihilation occurs the result is gamma-rays.
however, due to the high intensities, these gammas can produce other 
particles (which is where the losses might occur). However, recall that 
at TL-15 you can muck around with interaction probabilities as a result of 
mastering the strong and weak nuclear forces. perhaps you could increase 
your efficiency that way? 

when it comes to coverting matter into anti-matter - you are violating 
several conservation laws there. some beleive that such laws are violated at 
high energies - but then you need to get these high energies. I would imagine 
that is why you\'d need a powerful accelerator or some such... 

But why bother with all this messy anti-matter? You can use a black hole 
to get 100% matter-to-energy conversion thanks to hawking radiation. 
this was brought up a few months ago on this list - but the basics are this:
a small black hole will "evaporate" due to hawking radiation at rate that 
increases as the mass of the hole decreases. if you feed the black hole 
matter at the rate at which it is radiating, it will never stop radiating.
of course there are drawbacks - the black hole has to be on the order of 
10^15 grams, if you stop "feeding" it it will radiate away all its energy 
and explode in your face, and finally if you accidentially drop in into 
a star or planet - well, that\'s just too bad for that star or planet... 
but the pluses are this - 100% conversion and a great way to annoy your 
enemies.

On another matter - someone asked about mesons. they have restmasses lying 
in between those of nucleons and electrons ( hence the name mesons ), which 
is on the order of a few hundred MeV. on the other hand they are travelling 
VERY (0.999999+ c)
close to the speed of light (they have to since they don\'t last very 
long - you need a HUGE time-dilation in order for them to go anywhere)
so they have a lot of energy.. 
it is true that they will not penetrate normal matter without interacting -
since mesons contain quarks they interact with nuclei. typical penetration 
depths of neutral pions would be on the order of centimetres. 
however, they deposit all their energy in that distance - which makes for 
a great weapon. just not one you can shoot through planets with.
Now, if you like the idea of such a gun ( and I think deep meson sites are cool) you can always wave your hands and say that at TL-13 or so it becomes possible to create a co-moving (ie one that moves with the mesons) strong nuclear field that prevents meson-nuclei interactions.. or something equally sci-fi...
hope this helps..

cheers,
/ben
