shadow@ (Leonard Erickson) writes:

 ----
Whoa! The mechanism for Hawking radiation *doesn\'t* work that way.
What\'s happening is that virtual particle pair are constantly being
created everywhere. They are always a particle and its anti-particle.
They quickly recombine and the energy involved exists for such a short
period that Heisenberg uncertianity allows the temporary violation of
conservation of energy.
 ----

Ahem, I know this.

 ----
Near a black hole, one of the particles (it doesn\'t *matter* whetether
its the "normal" one or the "antimatter" one) is likely to cross the
event horizon. That means that when the time allowed by the uncertainty
principle is up, there\'s missing energy. So the result is that the
*non*-trapped particle continues on its way, and the black hole loses
that much mass.
 ----

Ah, that explaination works _much_ better than the previous one I\'d read 
which only mentioned the "anti-matter particle going into black-hole, normal 
matter one escaping" case. I _had_ thought that there appeared to be 
something wrong with it but hadn\'t seen it expressed as above.

Django.

