    'index' => 'ac127',
    'topic' => 'Anti-matters',
    'body' => '>Derek Wildstar <wildstar@qrc.com> writes:
>
>> Todays production methods are wholly unfeasible for any sort of sensible use
>> never mind the storage problems.
>
>Although if there were a crushing need for it, a production facility could
>probably be built for antimatter that would be considerably more efficient
>that the current research facilities.

Depends on what you want to do with it. Just producing it is fine take
any high energy beam and smack it into a lump of material and load of
anti-particles will be produced. The problem is that in order to store
the anti-matter you have to cool it and this is the big problem.  The
small acceptance of the cooling process means you loose most of the
stuff you produce. Also most of the anti-matter you produce is in the
form of mesons which decay. The probability of producing an
anti-proton, say, from a proton hitting a target is very small
compared to the probability of producing other particles (mainly
photons, pions and neutrons are produced).

Current research facilities, eg. the LEAR ring at CERN, are designed
specifically to capture as many anti-protons as possible and to cool
them for capture or use at low energies. Without a significant increase in
money I doubt you could build a more efficient system.

>Massimo Stiavelli <mstiavel@stsci.edu> writes:
>2. magnetic containment is a tricky business but it can be done. The
>problem is that of scale. At CERN they have been able to store something like
>200 anti-protons for a couple of months..this is not what you would like..
>Neutrons can be shielded relatively easily, getting a reall good vacuum
>is more of a problem. Also one needs the antiproton beam to be really
>cold, that is achievbed by the so-called stochastic cooling and also by
>electron cooling if I am not mistaken. The trick is to cool it
>down something you cannot touch (note that electrons can touch anti-protons
>relatively safely). Perhaps Roger has more recent information on this.

Stochastic cooling is still the initial method used for cooling. This
can then be followed by a variety of methods, one of which is the
electon method you mention. I believe there are other methods using
lasers but I\'m not really an expert in this field so I can\'t
comment. Once they have the anti-protons down to a few keV in energy
they trap them in an electric bottle and inject electrons in the
central region to cool them down further.

		|			|
		|	  ...		|
		|	  ...		|
	  ---->	|	  ...		|
 protons enter	|	  ...		|
 here		|	  ...		|
		|			|
             positive	   ^	    positive
			electrons

The protons essentially bounce back and forth scattering off the
electrons and cooling down to very low energies.

These storage methods cannot work for a very long time since
eventually the anti-protons will interact with the traces of air in
the container - it\'s not possible to make a perfect vacuum.

Stepping into the realms of science fiction now it may be possible to
trap anti-protons within a crystal lattice. We know that we can
channel charged particles by bending a crystal lattice (our experiment
actually uses this technique) and there are people who think it may be
possible to use crystals as accelerators by exciting vibrations within
them while passing charged particles through them, so why not the
reverse? Pass your anti-protons through a crystal and use the
vibrations to slow them down and let them get trapped in the gaps
between the atoms. Such a storage method would be extremely safe - no
problem if there is a power cut or your fuel tank gets damaged and to
extract the anti-protons just excite the crystal vibrations to
accelerate them out. Inside the crystal they will be protected from
the nuclei containing protons by a cushion of electrons which repell
them so they should be relatively stable. Anyway it\'s just a thought
on how you could safely store anti-matter.


>merrick@Rt66.com (Merrick Burkhardt) writes:
>>       Fraction = exp(-X/0.176)      (X in metres)
>> (note that this is independent of the particle\'s energy)
>> 
>> but this is the same for protons and neutrons. Essentially any particle 
>> accelerator is as effective as a meson gun. The claims made in Traveller 
>> that they will \'sail through a planet and then decay\' are complete 
