>
>How is the 0.176 arrived at?  

Its actually 0.167m for iron, my typo, sorry! The parameter is called
the interaction length and you obtain it by experiment - you smack
some protons into various ticknesses of iron and count how many make
it through. 

>Could you post some sample values for this for different materials if
>you\'ve got \'em (or even how you calculate a pion cross section for a
>given nucleus (first order would be fine).

There is an impirical formula for calculating it which I can\'t find
right at the moment. I can give you the values for various materials
from a data book I have but they are not really everyday materials
(anyone have a beryllium teapot? :-). You may be able to find more
info at:
	http://durpdg.dur.ac.uk/HEPDATA

>Derek Wildstar <wildstar@qrc.com> writes:
>Historically, Traveller "Meson Guns" are supposed to fire Pi neutral mesons.
>The above is true for them as well, correct?

Yes, although these mesons have such a short lifetime that you would
need and ENORMOUS amount of energy to make them last long enough to be
of use. Since they consist of a quark and anti-quark of the same type
they will interact just like any other meson. What I think the meson
gun designer was thinking of was muons. These are NOT mesons but do
penetrate matter relatively well (not planetary thicknesses but 10m of
iron is no problem at all)

>According to the official Traveller PSG (pseudoscience-gobbledygook)
>explanation, these mesons are supposed to interact with matter only very
>weakly, until they decay.  The distance they travel before decaying is
>then controlled by firing them at relativistic velocities.

This is physically complete rubbish. Mesons interact through the
strong and, if charged, electromagnetic forces. They could also
interact through the weak force but the effect is so small you can\'t
see it in comparison to the others. The decay mechanisms quite often
involve the weak force though.

What you need to produce similar behaviour (although nothing I can
think of will make them all decay in one place) is an unstable,
neutral, weakly interacting particle, sort of like a neutrino which
can decay. Off the top of my head I can\'t think of any theories which
even predict such a particle, but then again we never know what\'s out
there until we take a look.........

Roger
