> Charles.

  They were published by Digest Group Publications, the late lamented
company that published a wide variety of material for Traveller and
MegaTraveller in the 1980s.  They are MegaTraveller products, and contain
detailed descriptions of the social and economic structures of these
races, as well as history.  This is presented both from the point of view
of the Race itself and from a outside observer, so you get a real feel for
how the race thinks.  There are also rules for character generation and
sector maps .  The original plan was to do books on all the major races -
only these two books were finished before DGP quit publishing. 

  As far as content goes, they are updated and expanded versions of the
Traveller series of Alien Modules on the various alien races.  My favorite
one of the old series is the Solomani one - what other science fiction
game has people from Earth as aliens!?  The DGP books are worth getting 
even if you have the older Alien Modules, since they contain more and 
better written stuff.

  As to their worth, I consider them to be some of the best-written stuff 
for Traveller ever produced.  DGP has a well deserved reputation for 
high-quality products, and Rats & Cats and Doggies & Drones are among the 
best things they did.  If Sneaks & Geeks had been half as good, there 
would have been a lot less complaining on this list.  

  If you like Traveller, the two books are close to must-haves.  If you 
have further questions, let me know. 
 
----
