    'body' => 'sudet@well.com (Glenn M. Goffin) wrote:
> I am working on the real history of the Civil War of 604-622, and have
> prepared the working hypothesis set forth below.

While your hypothesis is interesting, I don\'t believe that it is supported
by the known facts about the Imperial Civil War.  There are a number of facts
which have to be accounted for in any theory of the Imperial civil war,
including:

o All of the "Emperors of the Flag" were highly-ranked Imperial admirals.
  (this is explained adequately in your theory).

o The fighthing of the Civil War involved most or all of the Naval forces
  of the Imperium, but much fewer ground forces.  (This is also adequately
  explained by your theory).

o Several sources note that the Imperial Bureaucracy continued uninterrupted
  during the Imperial Civil War, and MegaTraveller materials indicate that
  the economic disruption of the "Rebellion" (Second Civil War) was much
  greater than the "First" Civil War of 604-622.  In particular, these
  sources note that First Civil War attacks on planets and production
  centers were not nearly as commonplace as in the Second Civil War.  (This
  seems highly at odds with your theory).

o According to Marc Miller (at a talk given at Origins in 1982), the Civil
  War was originally added to the chronology to make the (rather high)
  number of Emperors fit the age of the Imperium.  During the height of
  the Civil War, a vicious cycle was operating, where the de-facto ruler
  of the Imperium[1] would be assasinated by an ambitious subordinate or
  defeated in battle by the admiral of a rival fleet.

[1] Note that few, if any, of hte Emperors of the Flag were formally
    recognized by the Moot and/or Imperial Bureaucracy, but instead invoked
    Succession by Right of Assasination to "legitimize" their rule.  Those
    that proclaimed themselves "By Right of Fleet Control" didn\'t even have
    that - they had instead managed to capture the Capitol and Imperial
    Core.

o Also according to Marc at the same talk, Arbellatra\'s primary innovation
  was in *not* proclaiming herself Empress - but, instead, Regent; and in
  instituting a search for a legitimate heir to the throne.  This
  (presumably combined with effective suppression of possible threats to her
  rule) broke the cycle of ambitious admirals seeking the Throne.  It was
  possible to invoke the Succession by Right of Assasination tradition
  against someone who was Emperor, but the same rationale seemed even more
  flimsy when used against a Regent.  (Again, this facet of the Civil War
  should probaly be broughgt out by a history of the Civil War).

o Arbellatra re-organized the Imperial Navy, and instituted other measures
  to help prevent a recurrence of the Civil War.  A history of the Civil
  War should note how the previous system helped contribute to the War.
  (Your theory does this rather well).

> Thank you for your attention.  Your comments and criticism are appreciated.

I\'m looking forward to seeing more of your work!


wildstar@qrc.com
