Expanding on this....

The Travellers\' Digest article by Clay Bush on Imperial history (TD #18, as
I recall) clearly points out who was and who wasn\'t confirmed legally by the
Imperial Moot.  I don\'t recall if similar information was in the Imperial
Encyclopedia or not.  If you look at the progression of emperors, part of
the problem was that the Moot would often narrowly approve someone, and then
the faction that lost would support someone else, or some rogue would come
along and kill off the Moot\'s candidate and take power, sometimes with
enough strength to force the Moot to accept them temporarily.

For instance, notice that Arbellatra Alkhalikoi was appointed Grand Admiral
of the Marches by Cleon V, who was narrowly confirmed by the Moot.  This
may have helped her cause -- Cleon V was legally emperor, so her appointment
was legal as well.  This may have helped to reinforce the air of legitimacy
around her when she moved to become Regent, and may also have attracted a
core of support in the Moot from the noble senators who supported Cleon V\'s
confirmation in 615.

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonnevil@itlabs.umn.edu>

