    'ts-index' => '1995-12-16.ac207',
    'body' => '> From: Michael.Barry@FINANCE.ausgovfinance.telememo.au

Michael:

You have some very good ideas.  May I post your comments to the History of
the Imperium Working Group list, where we\'re having a similar discussion?

> write a scenario or a sourcebook, but I doubt if anybody can pry
> GDW/Challenge away from their ridiculous Reformation Coalition.

I\'m afraid I agree.  Sigh.

>1.
>One aspect of this that you have not explored is the high probability
>that these feudal fleets within the Imperium had probably been fighting
>against each other (on and off) since long before the Civil War;
>In this situation, the Emperor might just keep out of their way through
>fear

Yes, this makes sense.  It\'s part of the constantly shifting balance of
power between the nobility and the Emperor.  Arbellatra and her successors
did what they could to weaken the nobility and strengthen the throne;
Strephon undid all of it with a few keystrokes.  (Yes, that\'s a gross
oversimplification.)

>2.  Your explanation of the politics of the Imperium during the Civil War
>seems a bit too democratic. Imperial citizens\' opinions wouldn\'t really
>matter

Opinions, per se, don\'t matter.  Mao Tse-tung was quite right to say that
political power comes from the barrel of a gun.  If the citizens find that
oppression is too hard to bear, they\'ll arm themselves (figuratively as
well as literally) and oppose it.  An example would be providing
intentionally contaminated food and/or fuel to the fleets.  Resistance
would be facilitated by agents carrying information, propaganda, etc. from
world to world.  Is this where the Ine Givar come from?

> 3.
> the bureaucracy kept going regardless of who was in charge.
> they probably functioned like a feudal fiefdom in themselves, under
> their own highly hierarchical, obsessively impartial, magnificently
> bureaucratic system

I\'m going to adopt this, too.

> 4.  From what I know of history, I find it a bit bizarre that a Civil
> War could cause minimal damage to the population and political structures.
> Historically, civil wars have been a fight to the death mobilising the
> whole population into massive repetitive assaults until the winner is the
> last pathetic remnant left standing...but I guess if the CT canon says the
> Civil War didn\'t do much damage, we work with that.

What is our canonical source for the First Civil War not doing much
damage?  The continued functioning of the bureaucracy is the only
indication that I have of it.

>5.  What happened to the Imperium\'s borders while the fleet admirals were
>off eating each others\' tails around Capital?

This is a nice thread.  The various fleets must have devoted some of their
resources to border defense.  They probably had an agreement to work
together as necessary in that capacity (which may well have been more
often honored in the breach).

> 6.  The feudal fleets probably operated on a system of "gentlemans\'
> war";
> it would certainly explain why Arbellatra, just having won a real,
> \'dirty\' war, could sweep through this pack of pansies in short order.

Gentlesophonts\' war, we say here in Berkeley, but yes, this makes sense.
It also explains how the war didn\'t wreck the Imperium like civil wars
usually do -- the civs themselves weren\'t doing much fighting, although in
an 18-year conflict some recruiting would have to go on.  I\'m going to
have to rethink my oppression of citizens theme; it may be that I can
justify leaving them mostly out of it.


--Glenn
