>From the 5FW boardgame we get the following information about the
Ine Givar:

    The Zhodani player has at his disposal the forces of the  Ine
    Givar - a guerrilla movement fighting against the Imperium on
    a number of worlds.  Each guerrilla unit  has  two  modes  of
    operations: covert and overt.  When covert, a guerrilla  unit
    is in hiding on its world and  is  ignored  for  all  surface
    combat and world control purposes.  When overt,  a  guerrilla
    unit is treated as a regular Zhodani troop unit.

    A guerrilla unit\'s tech level is the tech level of the  world
    on which it is operating.  A full strenth guerrilla unit  has
    a strength equal to 10% of the full  strength  value  of  the
    world\'s defense battalion factor, regardless of whatever  the
    current strength of the defense battalions is.  For  example,
    a full strength guerrilla unit on Efate would have a strength
    of 100 (battalions) and a tech level of 13.

    The Zhodani player places the ten guerrilla units before  any
    other units are deployed.  At least three must be  placed  on
    Efate,  and  at  least  one  must  be  placed  on  Ruie.  The
    remaining six may be placed on any Imperial controlled worlds
    that have defense battalion factors and are not interdicted;
    they may be placed singly or in groups.



Additionally, the Traveller News Service gave hints of  terrorist
activity on Efate, Pixie, Feri  and  Forboldn.  In  078-1107  the
Imperium  deployed  16  or  more  brigades  on  Efate  to   fight
insurgents.



Pronounciation of "Ine Givar" is either "In-Eh Jiv-Or" if it is a
Zhodani name or "In-Eh Give-Or" if not.  The last  "a"  being  an
"Ah" sound is aparently  peculiar  to  Solomani  languages,  both
Zhodani and Vilani pronounce it as "oc" (as in lock).



Regards PLST
